{"title_page": "The Incredible Dr. Pol", "text_new": "{{short description|American reality television series}}\n{{Merge from|Jan Pol (veterinarian)|discuss=Talk:The Incredible Dr. Pol#Proposed merge with Jan Pol (veterinarian)|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Incredible Dr. Pol\n| image                =\n| caption              =\n| genre                = [[Reality television]]\n| camera               =\n| picture_format       =\n| audio_format         =\n| runtime              = 44\u201350 minutes\n| creator              = [[Jon Schroder]]\n| developer            = Charles Pol\n| producer             = Charles Pol\n| executive_producer   =\n| starring             = {{plainlist|class=nowrap|\n* [[Jan Pol (Veterinarian)|Jan Pol]]\n* [[#Diane Pol|Diane Pol]]\n* [[#Charles Pol|Charles Pol]]\n* [[#Brenda Grettenberger|Brenda Grettenberger]]\n* [[#Emily Thomas|Emily Thomas]]}}\n| narrated             = Ari Rubin\n| theme_music_composer =\n| opentheme            =\n| endtheme             =\n| country              = United States\n| location             = [[Weidman, Michigan]]\n| language             = English\n| company              = {{ubl|[[National Geographic]]|Super Alright}}\n| network              = [[Nat Geo Wild]] \n| first_aired          = 2011\u2013present\n| last_aired           = \n| num_seasons          = 16\n| num_episodes         = 173 (October 2019)\n| list_episodes        =\n| related              =\n| website              = http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/wild/the-incredible-dr-pol/\n}}\n\n'''''The Incredible enano Dr. Pol''''' is an American enano[[reality television]] show on [[Nat Geo Wild]] el doc pol se encarga de los p\u00e1ncreas y salpullidos de las personas, especialmente de lucys [[veterinarian]] [[Jan Pol (Veterinarian)|Jan Pol]] and his family and employees at his practice in rural [[Weidman, Michigan]].<ref name=\"Zimich\">{{cite web |url= http://veterinarynews.dvm360.com/dvm/Veterinary%20Food%20Animal/The-Incredible-Dr-Pol/ArticleStandard/Article/detail/746149 |title=The Incredible Dr. Pol |date=November 1, 2011 |first1=Rachael |last1=Zimlich |work=DVM360 Magazine |publisher= |accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Ali\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-ca-st-dr-pol-rural-vet-nat-geo-television-20180215-htmlstory.html |first1=Lorraine |last1=Ali |date=February 16, 2018 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |title=TELEVISION: Calf pulling and puppy worming: rural vet Dr. Pol is reality TV\u2019s most unlikely star |accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"James\">{{cite web |url= http://veterinarynews.dvm360.com/michigan-appeals-court-finds-favor-dr-pol |title=Michigan appeals court finds in favor of Dr. Pol. Overturns disciplinary action ordered by state regulatory board in relation to negligence, incompetence findings. |date=July 1, 2016 |first1=Katie |last1=James |work=Veterinary News |accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>  The subject matter, its cast, and its long running popularity on [[cable television]] are seen as an odd mix.<ref name=\"Ali\"/> The series premiered in 2011 and has two seasons every year, for a total of 16 through October 2019.<ref>{{cite web |date= |title= Full Episode Guide |url= http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/wild/the-incredible-dr-pol/ \n|work=The Incredible Dr. Pol |location= Weidman, Michigan |access-date= 16 July 2019|quote=S1.E1: Oct 29, 2011 ... S15.E1: Jul 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n[[File:Diane and Jan Pol speak to the Netherlands embassy.jpg |right | thumb|Diane and Jan Pol in 2019]]\n{{Main article|Jan Pol (veterinarian)}}\n*Jan Pol (born on 4 September 1942, in [[Wateren]], Netherlands)<ref>{{cite tweet|title=On this date in 1942, Dr. Pol was born in Wateren, The Netherlands|user=drpol|author=Dr. Jan Pol verified Twitter account |number= 1036959998679674880|date=4 September 2018|accessdate= 7 April 2019|archivedate= 7 April 2019| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20190407160154/https://twitter.com/drpol/status/1036959998679674880|url-status=live}}</ref>, studied [[veterinary medicine]] at [[Utrecht University]], graduating in 1970. Moved with his wife Diane to [[Harbor Beach, Michigan]], and Pol worked for a veterinarian for more than 10&nbsp;years. They then moved to [[Weidman, Michigan]], where they started their own practice, Pol Veterinary Services, out of their home in 1981.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/wild/the-incredible-dr-pol/articles/meet-the-vets/|title=Meet the Pol Team-Dr.Pol |date=19 July 2012 |publisher= [[National Geographic (TV network)|National Geographic TV network]]|accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.santeesd.net/cms/lib/ca01000468/centricity/domain/91/dr.pdf Meet Dr.Pol] - website [[Santee School District]] (pdf)</ref><ref name=\"Celebs\"/>   His practice has transformed from large animals to a mix with small animals.  Because of the unavailability of emergency care animal hospitals in this rural area, emergencies make up a large portion of the practice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodsoapbox.com/interview-dr-pol-looks-back-at-2019-ahead-at-2020/ |title=INTERVIEW: Dr. Pol looks back at 2019, ahead at 2020  |date=December 31, 2019  |first1=John |last1=Soltes |accessdate=January 5, 2020 |publisher=hollywoodsoapbox.com}}</ref>  He claims to have served more than 19,000 clients in his many years of practice.<ref name=\"Celebs\"/>  Dr. Pol says that despite his advancing years, he can't retire: there are not veterinarians stepping into the breach to take care of farm animals.<ref name=\"Cutler\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2018/03/08/incredible-dr-pol-cant-retire-because-other-vets-wont-treat-farm-animals/407633002/ |title=Incredible Dr. Pol' can't retire because other vets won't treat farm animals |first1=Jacqueline |last1=Cutler |newspaper=[[USA TODAY]] |date=March 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n*Diane Pol (born in [[Mayville, Michigan]], in 1943), met Jan Pol when he was a foreign exchange student at Mayville High School in 1961. She has a master's degree in Special Reading and used to be a teacher at Harbor Beach Elementary Schools. Diane and Jan have been married for 50&nbsp;years.<ref name=\"Facts vet and Wild\">{{cite web| url= http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/wild/the-incredible-dr-pol/articles/facts-vet-and-wild/ |title= Facts vet and Wild |date= 29 September 2011 |accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n*Charles Pol (graduated from the [[University of Miami]] in Florida, 2003)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newswatch.nationalgeographic.com/2014/02/28/incredible-dr-pol-nat-geo-wild-animals-science-veterinarians-nation/ |title=Q&A: The Real Story of 'The Incredible Dr. Pol' |first=Carrie |last=Arnold |date=28 February 2014 |url-status=dead |accessdate=26 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140520101943/http://newswatch.nationalgeographic.com/2014/02/28/incredible-dr-pol-nat-geo-wild-animals-science-veterinarians-nation/ |archive-date=20 May 2014 }}</ref> Producer.<ref name=\"Ali\"/><ref name=\"Denhart\"/>\n*Brenda Grettenberger (born in 1967, [[Eaton Rapids, Michigan]]) graduated from [[Michigan State University College of Veterinary Medicine]] in 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/wild/the-incredible-dr-pol/articles/meet-the-vets/ | title=Meet the Pol Team\u2013 Dr.Brenda |date=19 July 2012| accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n*Emily Thomas (born in 1984 in [[Warner Robins, Georgia]]) graduated from [[University of Georgia College of Veterinary Medicine]] in 2010, is married and the mother of three children.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dr. Emily Thomas Wiki: Married, husband, Kids, age, Net Worth. |url=https://thecelebsinfo.com/dr-emily-thomas-biography/ |website=thecelebsinfo.com |publisher=Thecelebsinfo |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Filming Incredible Dr. Pol.jpg | right|thumb | Filming ''The Incredible Dr. Pol'' in 2019]]\nPol is surprised that the show became a hit \"watched by everybody\u2014all kinds of life, all ages, big family show, and I think this is what is so fantastic.\u201d  He credits his son Charles, who is the series producer, and who successfully pitched the series to National Geographic.  According to Pol  Charles counseled him, \u201cDad, do your work. That is interesting enough. Don\u2019t look at the camera, don\u2019t do anything for the camera.\u201d  \nPol continues. \"... it\u2019s not scripted; it is real\u201d<ref name=\"Denhart\">{{cite news |url=https://www.realityblurred.com/realitytv/2018/07/incredible-dr-pol-interview/|title= National Geographic: How The Incredible Dr. Pol is filmed: an interview with Dr. Pol|first1=Andy |last1=Denhart |work=[[Reality Blurred]] |date=July 5, 2018 |accessdate=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Viewer's complaint and legal fall-out==\nIn 2012, a disciplinary board placed Dr. Pol on probation for negligence and incompetence.<ref>{{cite news |url=\nhttp://veterinarynews.dvm360.com/dr-pol-reality-tv-veterinarian-fined-and-placed-probation-negligence-incompetence |title=Dr. Pol, reality TV veterinarian, fined and placed on probation for negligence, incompetence |quote=National Geographic says disciplinary action will not affect the highly rated show.|date=October 5, 2012 |first1=Julie |last1=Scheidegger |publisher=[[DVM360 Magazine]] |accessdate=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn fact, his practices have been the subject of multiple disciplinary proceedings, and his performance has received a mixed reception by veterinarians.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.petful.com/pet-health/dr-pol-controversy/ |title=Why the \u201cIncredible\u201d Dr. Pol Is So Controversial in the Vet World |quote=Cable TV\u2019s famous veterinarian has faced charges of negligence and incompetence since his show first aired. |author=Dr. Debora Lichtenberg, VMD |date=August 3, 2019 |accessdate=January 5, 2020}}</ref>  Another veterinarian flatly states that the show exhibit antiquated Veterinary practices, going back more than a quarter century; and thereby convey a false impression of the profession.<ref name=\"Zimlich\"/>\n\nHis treatment of a dog, as depicted on the show, spawned a complaint.  The professional standards complaint was placed by a viewer, not the pet's owner.<ref name=\"Draplin\">{{cite news |url= https://www.michigancapitolconfidential.com/22588 |title=News Story: Court Overrules Licensing Board, Exonerates Vet Who Saved Dog |quote=Reality TV viewer complained after Dr. Pol helped Mr. Pigglesworth |first1=Derek |last1=Draplin |date=July 12, 2016|work=[[CapCon]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[List of Speakers of the Michigan House of Representatives|Michigan Speaker of the House]] [[Kevin Cotter]] sponsored House Bill 5176, seeking to prohibit authorities from investigating reports of misconduct or allegations \u201cbased upon information obtained from viewing the broadcast of a reality program.\u201d<ref name=\"Draplin\"/>  Dr. Pol testified in favor of the bill.  It was referred to the House Health Policy Committee in December 2013, died in committee, and has not been re-introduced.<ref name=\"Draplin\"/>\n\nIn March 2015, an administrative hearing found a breach of the standard of care.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://veterinarynews.dvm360.com/pol-defense-michigan-veterinary-board-discusses-negligence-charges |title=Michigan state veterinary board rules against Dr. Pol Orders fine and CE in response to negligence, incompetence charges; controversial reality TV veterinarian calls his approach 'common sense.' |date=March 26, 2015 |author=dvm360.com staff |work=DVM360 |accessdate=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, government regulators in [[Michigan]] found Pol in contempt for his treatment and care of a [[Boston terrier]] that was hit by a car and suffered an eye proptosis and broken pelvis in May 2011. A disciplinary [[subcommittee]] of the Michigan Board of Veterinary Medicine decided on 26th March to fine Dr. Pol $500 and put his license on probation for not complying with the least possible standards of care required by the state. Pol was also ordered to complete an educational course. His sentencing was overturned, however, by the [[Michigan Court of Appeals]], which stated that \u201cthe owners of the dog were happy with the care it has been given\u201d and called the previous decision by the subcommittee \"arbitrary and capricious\".<ref name=\"Celebs\">{{cite web|url=https://thecelebsinfo.com/dr-jan-pol-biography/|title=Dr. Pol wiki, bio, married, wife Diane Pol, children, age, net worth.|date=Mar 3, 2018|accessdate=Jan 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Zimlich\">{{cite web|url=http://veterinarynews.dvm360.com/dvm/Veterinary%20Food%20Animal/Veterinarians-review-The-Incredible-Dr-Pol/ArticleStandard/Article/detail/754727|title=Some reviews of 'The Incredible Dr. Pol' reality show not so incredible|last=Zimlich|first=Rachael|work=Veterinary News|accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180813152230/http://listcinema.sojackrussell.com/tag/documentary.html ]</ref>  The complaint was placed by a viewer, not the pet's owner.<ref name=\"Draplin\"/>\n\nIn 2016, the Court of Appeals reversed and remanded, holding ''inter alia'' that there was no competent evidence that there was a breach of the standard of care.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/michigan/court-of-appeals-unpublished/2016/327346.html |title=BUREAU OF HEALTH CARE SERVICES V JAN H POL DVM  DVM Bureau of Professional Licensing v. Jan H. Pol, DVM  (Per Curiam Opinion) Case No. 327346 |publisher=[[Justia]] |date=June 23, 2016 |pages=1, 9}}</ref>  There were supporters of the ruling based on notions of elemental [[due process]], including vagueness of the charge, lack of an objective and clear legal standard, and variance of the evidence presented from the charges lodged.<ref name=\"Carser\">{{cite web |url=https://www.veterinarypracticenews.com/bureau-health-care-services-v-dr-pol-important/ |title=Why the Bureau of Health Care Services v. Dr. Pol is so important |quote=Dr. Jan Pol was found guilty of not meeting required minimum standards of veterinary care, but his conviction  and penalty were reversed |date=January 12, 2018 |author=David Carser, BVSC, LLB, CML |accessdate=January 5, 2010}}</ref> At this juncture, a spokesman from [[Mackinac Center for Public Policy]] opined that consumers and the market place, not an officious government, should be able to make care decisions for their animals.<ref name=\"Draplin\"/>\n\nHowever, in late 2019 after remand, the [[Michigan Court of Appeals]] in another [[unpublished decision]], wrote an extended opinion which affirmed the lower decisions that imposed discipline.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/michigan/court-of-appeals-unpublished/2019/344666.html |title=IN RE JAN H POL DVM Bureau of Professional Licensing v. Jan H. Pol, DVM (Per Curiam Opinion) (Unpublished) Case No. 34666 |publisher=[[Justia]]|date=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://www.myseries.tv/the_incredible_dr_pol/episodes/ ''Incredible Dr. Pol'', Episode guide]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Incredible Dr. Pol, The}}\n[[Category:2010s American reality television series]]\n[[Category:2011 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:National Geographic Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American reality television series}}\n{{Merge from|Jan Pol (veterinarian)|discuss=Talk:The Incredible Dr. Pol#Proposed merge with Jan Pol (veterinarian)|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Incredible Dr. Pol\n| image                =\n| caption              =\n| genre                = [[Reality television]]\n| camera               =\n| picture_format       =\n| audio_format         =\n| runtime              = 44\u201350 minutes\n| creator              = [[Jon Schroder]]\n| developer            = Charles Pol\n| producer             = Charles Pol\n| executive_producer   =\n| starring             = {{plainlist|class=nowrap|\n* [[Jan Pol (Veterinarian)|Jan Pol]]\n* [[#Diane Pol|Diane Pol]]\n* [[#Charles Pol|Charles Pol]]\n* [[#Brenda Grettenberger|Brenda Grettenberger]]\n* [[#Emily Thomas|Emily Thomas]]}}\n| narrated             = Ari Rubin\n| theme_music_composer =\n| opentheme            =\n| endtheme             =\n| country              = United States\n| location             = [[Weidman, Michigan]]\n| language             = English\n| company              = {{ubl|[[National Geographic]]|Super Alright}}\n| network              = [[Nat Geo Wild]] \n| first_aired          = 2011\u2013present\n| last_aired           = \n| num_seasons          = 16\n| num_episodes         = 173 (October 2019)\n| list_episodes        =\n| related              =\n| website              = http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/wild/the-incredible-dr-pol/\n}}\n\n'''''The Incredible Dr. Pol''''' is an American [[reality television]] show on [[Nat Geo Wild]] that follows Dutch-born [[veterinarian]] [[Jan Pol (Veterinarian)|Jan Pol]] and his family and employees at his practice in rural [[Weidman, Michigan]].<ref name=\"Zimich\">{{cite web |url= http://veterinarynews.dvm360.com/dvm/Veterinary%20Food%20Animal/The-Incredible-Dr-Pol/ArticleStandard/Article/detail/746149 |title=The Incredible Dr. Pol |date=November 1, 2011 |first1=Rachael |last1=Zimlich |work=DVM360 Magazine |publisher= |accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Ali\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-ca-st-dr-pol-rural-vet-nat-geo-television-20180215-htmlstory.html |first1=Lorraine |last1=Ali |date=February 16, 2018 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |title=TELEVISION: Calf pulling and puppy worming: rural vet Dr. Pol is reality TV\u2019s most unlikely star |accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"James\">{{cite web |url= http://veterinarynews.dvm360.com/michigan-appeals-court-finds-favor-dr-pol |title=Michigan appeals court finds in favor of Dr. Pol. Overturns disciplinary action ordered by state regulatory board in relation to negligence, incompetence findings. |date=July 1, 2016 |first1=Katie |last1=James |work=Veterinary News |accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>  The subject matter, its cast, and its long running popularity on [[cable television]] are seen as an odd mix.<ref name=\"Ali\"/> The series premiered in 2011 and has two seasons every year, for a total of 16 through October 2019.<ref>{{cite web |date= |title= Full Episode Guide |url= http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/wild/the-incredible-dr-pol/ \n|work=The Incredible Dr. Pol |location= Weidman, Michigan |access-date= 16 July 2019|quote=S1.E1: Oct 29, 2011 ... S15.E1: Jul 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n[[File:Diane and Jan Pol speak to the Netherlands embassy.jpg |right | thumb|Diane and Jan Pol in 2019]]\n{{Main article|Jan Pol (veterinarian)}}\n*Jan Pol (born on 4 September 1942, in [[Wateren]], Netherlands)<ref>{{cite tweet|title=On this date in 1942, Dr. Pol was born in Wateren, The Netherlands|user=drpol|author=Dr. Jan Pol verified Twitter account |number= 1036959998679674880|date=4 September 2018|accessdate= 7 April 2019|archivedate= 7 April 2019| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20190407160154/https://twitter.com/drpol/status/1036959998679674880|url-status=live}}</ref>, studied [[veterinary medicine]] at [[Utrecht University]], graduating in 1970. Moved with his wife Diane to [[Harbor Beach, Michigan]], and Pol worked for a veterinarian for more than 10&nbsp;years. They then moved to [[Weidman, Michigan]], where they started their own practice, Pol Veterinary Services, out of their home in 1981.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/wild/the-incredible-dr-pol/articles/meet-the-vets/|title=Meet the Pol Team-Dr.Pol |date=19 July 2012 |publisher= [[National Geographic (TV network)|National Geographic TV network]]|accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.santeesd.net/cms/lib/ca01000468/centricity/domain/91/dr.pdf Meet Dr.Pol] - website [[Santee School District]] (pdf)</ref><ref name=\"Celebs\"/>   His practice has transformed from large animals to a mix with small animals.  Because of the unavailability of emergency care animal hospitals in this rural area, emergencies make up a large portion of the practice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodsoapbox.com/interview-dr-pol-looks-back-at-2019-ahead-at-2020/ |title=INTERVIEW: Dr. Pol looks back at 2019, ahead at 2020  |date=December 31, 2019  |first1=John |last1=Soltes |accessdate=January 5, 2020 |publisher=hollywoodsoapbox.com}}</ref>  He claims to have served more than 19,000 clients in his many years of practice.<ref name=\"Celebs\"/>  Dr. Pol says that despite his advancing years, he can't retire: there are not veterinarians stepping into the breach to take care of farm animals.<ref name=\"Cutler\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2018/03/08/incredible-dr-pol-cant-retire-because-other-vets-wont-treat-farm-animals/407633002/ |title=Incredible Dr. Pol' can't retire because other vets won't treat farm animals |first1=Jacqueline |last1=Cutler |newspaper=[[USA TODAY]] |date=March 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n*Diane Pol (born in [[Mayville, Michigan]], in 1943), met Jan Pol when he was a foreign exchange student at Mayville High School in 1961. She has a master's degree in Special Reading and used to be a teacher at Harbor Beach Elementary Schools. Diane and Jan have been married for 50&nbsp;years.<ref name=\"Facts vet and Wild\">{{cite web| url= http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/wild/the-incredible-dr-pol/articles/facts-vet-and-wild/ |title= Facts vet and Wild |date= 29 September 2011 |accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n*Charles Pol (graduated from the [[University of Miami]] in Florida, 2003)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newswatch.nationalgeographic.com/2014/02/28/incredible-dr-pol-nat-geo-wild-animals-science-veterinarians-nation/ |title=Q&A: The Real Story of 'The Incredible Dr. Pol' |first=Carrie |last=Arnold |date=28 February 2014 |url-status=dead |accessdate=26 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140520101943/http://newswatch.nationalgeographic.com/2014/02/28/incredible-dr-pol-nat-geo-wild-animals-science-veterinarians-nation/ |archive-date=20 May 2014 }}</ref> Producer.<ref name=\"Ali\"/><ref name=\"Denhart\"/>\n*Brenda Grettenberger (born in 1967, [[Eaton Rapids, Michigan]]) graduated from [[Michigan State University College of Veterinary Medicine]] in 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/wild/the-incredible-dr-pol/articles/meet-the-vets/ | title=Meet the Pol Team\u2013 Dr.Brenda |date=19 July 2012| accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n*Emily Thomas (born in 1984 in [[Warner Robins, Georgia]]) graduated from [[University of Georgia College of Veterinary Medicine]] in 2010, is married and the mother of three children.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dr. Emily Thomas Wiki: Married, husband, Kids, age, Net Worth. |url=https://thecelebsinfo.com/dr-emily-thomas-biography/ |website=thecelebsinfo.com |publisher=Thecelebsinfo |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Filming Incredible Dr. Pol.jpg | right|thumb | Filming ''The Incredible Dr. Pol'' in 2019]]\nPol is surprised that the show became a hit \"watched by everybody\u2014all kinds of life, all ages, big family show, and I think this is what is so fantastic.\u201d  He credits his son Charles, who is the series producer, and who successfully pitched the series to National Geographic.  According to Pol  Charles counseled him, \u201cDad, do your work. That is interesting enough. Don\u2019t look at the camera, don\u2019t do anything for the camera.\u201d  \nPol continues. \"... it\u2019s not scripted; it is real\u201d<ref name=\"Denhart\">{{cite news |url=https://www.realityblurred.com/realitytv/2018/07/incredible-dr-pol-interview/|title= National Geographic: How The Incredible Dr. Pol is filmed: an interview with Dr. Pol|first1=Andy |last1=Denhart |work=[[Reality Blurred]] |date=July 5, 2018 |accessdate=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Viewer's complaint and legal fall-out==\nIn 2012, a disciplinary board placed Dr. Pol on probation for negligence and incompetence.<ref>{{cite news |url=\nhttp://veterinarynews.dvm360.com/dr-pol-reality-tv-veterinarian-fined-and-placed-probation-negligence-incompetence |title=Dr. Pol, reality TV veterinarian, fined and placed on probation for negligence, incompetence |quote=National Geographic says disciplinary action will not affect the highly rated show.|date=October 5, 2012 |first1=Julie |last1=Scheidegger |publisher=[[DVM360 Magazine]] |accessdate=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn fact, his practices have been the subject of multiple disciplinary proceedings, and his performance has received a mixed reception by veterinarians.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.petful.com/pet-health/dr-pol-controversy/ |title=Why the \u201cIncredible\u201d Dr. Pol Is So Controversial in the Vet World |quote=Cable TV\u2019s famous veterinarian has faced charges of negligence and incompetence since his show first aired. |author=Dr. Debora Lichtenberg, VMD |date=August 3, 2019 |accessdate=January 5, 2020}}</ref>  Another veterinarian flatly states that the show exhibit antiquated Veterinary practices, going back more than a quarter century; and thereby convey a false impression of the profession.<ref name=\"Zimlich\"/>\n\nHis treatment of a dog, as depicted on the show, spawned a complaint.  The professional standards complaint was placed by a viewer, not the pet's owner.<ref name=\"Draplin\">{{cite news |url= https://www.michigancapitolconfidential.com/22588 |title=News Story: Court Overrules Licensing Board, Exonerates Vet Who Saved Dog |quote=Reality TV viewer complained after Dr. Pol helped Mr. Pigglesworth |first1=Derek |last1=Draplin |date=July 12, 2016|work=[[CapCon]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[List of Speakers of the Michigan House of Representatives|Michigan Speaker of the House]] [[Kevin Cotter]] sponsored House Bill 5176, seeking to prohibit authorities from investigating reports of misconduct or allegations \u201cbased upon information obtained from viewing the broadcast of a reality program.\u201d<ref name=\"Draplin\"/>  Dr. Pol testified in favor of the bill.  It was referred to the House Health Policy Committee in December 2013, died in committee, and has not been re-introduced.<ref name=\"Draplin\"/>\n\nIn March 2015, an administrative hearing found a breach of the standard of care.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://veterinarynews.dvm360.com/pol-defense-michigan-veterinary-board-discusses-negligence-charges |title=Michigan state veterinary board rules against Dr. Pol Orders fine and CE in response to negligence, incompetence charges; controversial reality TV veterinarian calls his approach 'common sense.' |date=March 26, 2015 |author=dvm360.com staff |work=DVM360 |accessdate=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, government regulators in [[Michigan]] found Pol in contempt for his treatment and care of a [[Boston terrier]] that was hit by a car and suffered an eye proptosis and broken pelvis in May 2011. A disciplinary [[subcommittee]] of the Michigan Board of Veterinary Medicine decided on 26th March to fine Dr. Pol $500 and put his license on probation for not complying with the least possible standards of care required by the state. Pol was also ordered to complete an educational course. His sentencing was overturned, however, by the [[Michigan Court of Appeals]], which stated that \u201cthe owners of the dog were happy with the care it has been given\u201d and called the previous decision by the subcommittee \"arbitrary and capricious\".<ref name=\"Celebs\">{{cite web|url=https://thecelebsinfo.com/dr-jan-pol-biography/|title=Dr. Pol wiki, bio, married, wife Diane Pol, children, age, net worth.|date=Mar 3, 2018|accessdate=Jan 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Zimlich\">{{cite web|url=http://veterinarynews.dvm360.com/dvm/Veterinary%20Food%20Animal/Veterinarians-review-The-Incredible-Dr-Pol/ArticleStandard/Article/detail/754727|title=Some reviews of 'The Incredible Dr. Pol' reality show not so incredible|last=Zimlich|first=Rachael|work=Veterinary News|accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180813152230/http://listcinema.sojackrussell.com/tag/documentary.html ]</ref>  The complaint was placed by a viewer, not the pet's owner.<ref name=\"Draplin\"/>\n\nIn 2016, the Court of Appeals reversed and remanded, holding ''inter alia'' that there was no competent evidence that there was a breach of the standard of care.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/michigan/court-of-appeals-unpublished/2016/327346.html |title=BUREAU OF HEALTH CARE SERVICES V JAN H POL DVM  DVM Bureau of Professional Licensing v. Jan H. Pol, DVM  (Per Curiam Opinion) Case No. 327346 |publisher=[[Justia]] |date=June 23, 2016 |pages=1, 9}}</ref>  There were supporters of the ruling based on notions of elemental [[due process]], including vagueness of the charge, lack of an objective and clear legal standard, and variance of the evidence presented from the charges lodged.<ref name=\"Carser\">{{cite web |url=https://www.veterinarypracticenews.com/bureau-health-care-services-v-dr-pol-important/ |title=Why the Bureau of Health Care Services v. Dr. Pol is so important |quote=Dr. Jan Pol was found guilty of not meeting required minimum standards of veterinary care, but his conviction  and penalty were reversed |date=January 12, 2018 |author=David Carser, BVSC, LLB, CML |accessdate=January 5, 2010}}</ref> At this juncture, a spokesman from [[Mackinac Center for Public Policy]] opined that consumers and the market place, not an officious government, should be able to make care decisions for their animals.<ref name=\"Draplin\"/>\n\nHowever, in late 2019 after remand, the [[Michigan Court of Appeals]] in another [[unpublished decision]], wrote an extended opinion which affirmed the lower decisions that imposed discipline.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/michigan/court-of-appeals-unpublished/2019/344666.html |title=IN RE JAN H POL DVM Bureau of Professional Licensing v. Jan H. Pol, DVM (Per Curiam Opinion) (Unpublished) Case No. 34666 |publisher=[[Justia]]|date=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://www.myseries.tv/the_incredible_dr_pol/episodes/ ''Incredible Dr. Pol'', Episode guide]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Incredible Dr. Pol, The}}\n[[Category:2010s American reality television series]]\n[[Category:2011 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:National Geographic Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "186.185.183.31", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Incredible_Dr._Pol"}
{"title_page": "Barbara Creecy", "text_new": "{{short description|South African politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix     = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                 = Barbara Creecy\n| native_name          = \n| native_name_lang     = \n| honorific-suffix     = [[Parliament of South Africa|MP]]\n| image                = Barbara Creecy.jpg\n| image_size           = 220px\n| smallimage           = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                  = \n| caption              = Creecy in 2014\n| office               = [[Minister of Environment, Forestry and Fisheries]]\n| deputy               = [[Maggie Sotyu]]\n| president            = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n| term_start           = 30 May 2019\n| term_end             = \n| predecessor          = ''Position established''\n| successor             = \n| office1               = Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]\n| premier1              = \n| term_start1           = 22 May 2019\n| term_end1             = \n| predecessor1          = \n| successor1            = \n| constituency1        = [[Gauteng]]\n| office2              = [[Government of Gauteng|Gauteng MEC for Finance]]\n| premier2             = [[David Makhura]]\n| term_start2          = 23 May 2014\n| term_end2            = 25 May 2019\n| predecessor2         = [[Mandla Nkomfe]]\n| successor2           = [[Panyaza Lesufi]]\n| office3              = [[Government of Gauteng|Gauteng MEC for Education]]\n| premier3             = [[Nomvula Mokonyane]]\n| term_start3          = 8 May 2009\n| term_end3            = 23 May 2014\n| predecessor3         = [[Angie Motshekga]] \n| successor3           = [[Panyaza Lesufi]]\n| office4              = [[Government of Gauteng|Gauteng MEC for Sports, Recreation, Arts and Culture]] \n| premier4             = [[Paul Mashatile]]<br>[[Mbhazima Shilowa]]\n| deputy4              = \n| term_start4          = 29 April 2004\n| term_end4            = 8 May 2009\n| predecessor4        = [[Mondli Gungubele]]\n| successor4          = Nelisiwe Mbatha-Mthimkhulu\n| office5             = Member of the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]]\n| leader5             =\n| term_start5         = 27 April 1994\n| term_end5           = 7 May 2019\n| predecessor5        = \n| successor5          = \n| office6            =\n| term_start6        = \n|constituency6       = \n| birthname          = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1958|06|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        =\n| nationality        = South African\n| party              = [[African National Congress]]\n| otherparty         = [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]]\n| spouse             = \n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = \n| residence          = \n| education          =\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Witwatersrand]]<br>[[University of London]]\n| occupation         = \n| profession         = Politician\n| known_for          = \n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| awards             =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| website            = \n}}\n'''Barbara Dallas Creecy''' (born 17 June 1958) is a South African politician and previous anti-apartheid activist. A member of the [[African National Congress]], she is currently serving as [[Minister of Environment, Forestry and Fisheries]], and a Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]. She previously served as a Member of the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]], having been elected in 1994. In 2004, she was named Gauteng MEC for Sports, Recreation, Arts and Culture. She served until 2009 when she was appointed MEC for Education. Newly-elected Premier [[David Makhura]] moved Creecy to the Gauteng Finance portfolio in 2014.<ref>[http://www.gauteng.gov.za/government/departments/provincial-treasury/Pages/MEC-profile.aspx Ms Barbara Creecy MEC FOR FINANCE], ''Gauteng Digital Platform''. Retrieved 29 May 2019.</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Creecy was sworn in as a [[National Assembly of South Africa|Member of Parliament]]. On 29 May 2019, President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] named her the new Minister of Environment, Forestry and Fisheries.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-29-in-full-cyril-ramaphosas-new-cabinet-in-his-own-words/ IN FULL | Cyril Ramaphosa's new cabinet, in his own words], ''TimesLIVE'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 29 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBarbara Creecy was born in [[Johannesburg]]. She attended the [[University of Witwatersrand]] and obtained an Honours degree in Political Science. Later on, she completed a Master's degree in Public Policy and Management with the [[University of London]].<ref>[https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/environment-forestry-and-fisheries-ministry/barbara-creecy-ms Barbara Creecy, Ms], ''South African Government''. Retrieved on 28 July 2019.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nCreecy was an anti-apartheid activist and worked in the underground structures of the African National Congress whilst a student at the [[Witwatersrand University]]. She worked for the Civic Desk of the [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]] and soon joined an NGO that provided training and organisational development support to trade unions and community structures. She had previously been a member of the Provincial Executive Committee of the ANC.<ref>[https://www.smartprocurementworld.com/westerncape/2013/01/barbara-creecy.html Barbara Creecy MEC for Finance Gauteng Provincial Treasury], ''Smart Procurement World''. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\nCreecy was one of the longest-serving Members of the Gauteng Provincial Legislature, having been elected in 1994. During her first two terms, she served as the Deputy Chief Whip as well as Chairperson of both the Social Development and Education Committees.<ref>Ndaba, Baldwin. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/sacp-lauds-gautengs-first-african-woman-finance-mec-24979210 SACP lauds Gauteng's 'first African woman' finance MEC], Gauteng, ''IOL'', 4 June 2019. Retrieved on 28 July 2019.</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Premier [[Mbhazima Shilowa]] appointed her as MEC for Sports, Recreation, Arts and Culture. [[Paul Mashatile]] took over as [[Premier of Gauteng]] in 2008 and retained Creecy in her post.<ref>Grobler, Fienie. [https://mg.co.za/article/2008-10-07-mashatile-elected-to-lead-gauteng Mashatile elected to lead Gauteng], ''Mail & Guardian'', 7 October 2008. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>Rossouw, Mandy. [https://mg.co.za/article/2008-10-04-which-way-will-he-swing Which way will he swing?], ''Mail & Guardian'', 4 October 2008. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Creecy moved to the Education portfolio and served in that post until May 2014, when Premier [[David Makhura]] selected her as the new Gauteng Finance MEC.<ref>[https://www.sanews.gov.za/south-africa/gautengs-new-mecs-announced Gauteng's new MECs announced], ''SA News'', 8 May 2009. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.politicsweb.co.za/archive/the-new-gauteng-cabinet--david-makhura The new Gauteng cabinet \u2013 David Makhura]. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\nFollowing the May 2019 elections, Creecy took office as a Member of the National Assembly. The media speculated that she would be appointed to the National Finance Department, as either Minister or Deputy Minister. On 29 May 2019, President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] appointed her to the post of Minister of Environment, Forestry and Fisheries.<ref>Haffajee, Ferial. [https://www.fin24.com/Economy/analysis-who-could-replace-nene-get-to-know-barbara-creecy-and-mondli-gungubele-20181008 ANALYSIS: Who could replace Nene? Get to know Barbara Creecy and Mondli Gungubele], ''Fin24'', 8 October 2018. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.businesslive.co.za/fm/features/cover-story/2019-05-16-bets-for-the-new-cabinet/ Bets for the new cabinet], ''BusinesLIVE'', 16 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2019-05-29-cabinet-announcement-expected-on-wednesday-at-8pm-presidency-confirms Cabinet announcement expected on Wednesday evening, Presidency confirms], ''Mail & Guardian'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-29-breaking-ramaphosa-announces-cabinet/ Ramaphosa announces cabinet: Mabuza, Gordhan, Mboweni \u2013 and De Lille], ''TimesLIVE'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/from-patricia-to-pandor-here-is-ramaphosas-new-smaller-cabinet-20190529 From Patricia to Pandor \u2013 Here is Ramaphosa's new (smaller) Cabinet], ''News24'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/creecy-barbara/ People's Assembly profile]\n*[https://ewn.co.za/video/10367/barbara-creecy---1976--being-brought-up-by-a-single-mother---being-a-career-mom Barbara Creecy - 1976, being brought up by a single mother & being a career mom]\n*[https://ewn.co.za/2019/08/08/behind-the-politics-creecy-on-student-activism-juggling-career-and-family-life BEHIND THE POLITICS: Creecy on student activism, juggling career and family life]\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Creecy, Barbara}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:University of the Witwatersrand alumni]]\n[[Category:White South African anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of South Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African politician}}