batha-Mthimkhulu\n| office5             = Member of the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]]\n| leader5             =\n| term_start5         = 27 April 1994\n| term_end5           = 7 May 2019\n| predecessor5        = \n| successor5          = \n| office6            =\n| term_start6        = \n|constituency6       = \n| birthname          = \n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        =\n| nationality        = South African\n| party              = [[African National Congress]]\n| otherparty         = [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]]\n| spouse             = \n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = \n| residence          = \n| education          =\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Witwatersrand]]<br>[[University of London]]\n| occupation         = \n| profession         = Politician\n| known_for          = \n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| awards             =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| website            = \n}}\n'''Barbara Dallas Creecy''' is a South African politician and previous anti-apartheid activist. A member of the [[African National Congress]], she is currently serving as [[Minister of Environment, Forestry and Fisheries]], and a Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]. She previously served as a Member of the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]], having been elected in 1994. In 2004, she was named Gauteng MEC for Sports, Recreation, Arts and Culture. She served until 2009 when she was appointed MEC for Education. Newly-elected Premier [[David Makhura]] moved Creecy to the Gauteng Finance portfolio in 2014.<ref>[http://www.gauteng.gov.za/government/departments/provincial-treasury/Pages/MEC-profile.aspx Ms Barbara Creecy MEC FOR FINANCE], ''Gauteng Digital Platform''. Retrieved 29 May 2019.</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Creecy was sworn in as a [[National Assembly of South Africa|Member of Parliament]]. On 29 May 2019, President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] named her the new Minister of Environment, Forestry and Fisheries.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-29-in-full-cyril-ramaphosas-new-cabinet-in-his-own-words/ IN FULL | Cyril Ramaphosa's new cabinet, in his own words], ''TimesLIVE'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 29 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBarbara Creecy was born in [[Johannesburg]]. She attended the [[University of Witwatersrand]] and obtained an Honours degree in Political Science. Later on, she completed a Master's degree in Public Policy and Management with the [[University of London]].<ref>[https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/environment-forestry-and-fisheries-ministry/barbara-creecy-ms Barbara Creecy, Ms], ''South African Government''. Retrieved on 28 July 2019.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nCreecy was an anti-apartheid activist and worked in the underground structures of the African National Congress whilst a student at the [[Witwatersrand University]]. She worked for the Civic Desk of the [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]] and soon joined an NGO that provided training and organisational development support to trade unions and community structures. She had previously been a member of the Provincial Executive Committee of the ANC.<ref>[https://www.smartprocurementworld.com/westerncape/2013/01/barbara-creecy.html Barbara Creecy MEC for Finance Gauteng Provincial Treasury], ''Smart Procurement World''. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\nCreecy was one of the longest-serving Members of the Gauteng Provincial Legislature, having been elected in 1994. During her first two terms, she served as the Deputy Chief Whip as well as Chairperson of both the Social Development and Education Committees.<ref>Ndaba, Baldwin. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/sacp-lauds-gautengs-first-african-woman-finance-mec-24979210 SACP lauds Gauteng's 'first African woman' finance MEC], Gauteng, ''IOL'', 4 June 2019. Retrieved on 28 July 2019.</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Premier [[Mbhazima Shilowa]] appointed her as MEC for Sports, Recreation, Arts and Culture. [[Paul Mashatile]] took over as [[Premier of Gauteng]] in 2008 and retained Creecy in her post.<ref>Grobler, Fienie. [https://mg.co.za/article/2008-10-07-mashatile-elected-to-lead-gauteng Mashatile elected to lead Gauteng], ''Mail & Guardian'', 7 October 2008. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>Rossouw, Mandy. [https://mg.co.za/article/2008-10-04-which-way-will-he-swing Which way will he swing?], ''Mail & Guardian'', 4 October 2008. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Creecy moved to the Education portfolio and served in that post until May 2014, when Premier [[David Makhura]] selected her as the new Gauteng Finance MEC.<ref>[https://www.sanews.gov.za/south-africa/gautengs-new-mecs-announced Gauteng's new MECs announced], ''SA News'', 8 May 2009. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.politicsweb.co.za/archive/the-new-gauteng-cabinet--david-makhura The new Gauteng cabinet \u2013 David Makhura]. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\nFollowing the May 2019 elections, Creecy took office as a Member of the National Assembly. The media speculated that she would be appointed to the National Finance Department, as either Minister or Deputy Minister. On 29 May 2019, President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] appointed her to the post of Minister of Environment, Forestry and Fisheries.<ref>Haffajee, Ferial. [https://www.fin24.com/Economy/analysis-who-could-replace-nene-get-to-know-barbara-creecy-and-mondli-gungubele-20181008 ANALYSIS: Who could replace Nene? Get to know Barbara Creecy and Mondli Gungubele], ''Fin24'', 8 October 2018. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.businesslive.co.za/fm/features/cover-story/2019-05-16-bets-for-the-new-cabinet/ Bets for the new cabinet], ''BusinesLIVE'', 16 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2019-05-29-cabinet-announcement-expected-on-wednesday-at-8pm-presidency-confirms Cabinet announcement expected on Wednesday evening, Presidency confirms], ''Mail & Guardian'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-29-breaking-ramaphosa-announces-cabinet/ Ramaphosa announces cabinet: Mabuza, Gordhan, Mboweni \u2013 and De Lille], ''TimesLIVE'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/from-patricia-to-pandor-here-is-ramaphosas-new-smaller-cabinet-20190529 From Patricia to Pandor \u2013 Here is Ramaphosa's new (smaller) Cabinet], ''News24'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/creecy-barbara/ People's Assembly profile]\n*[https://ewn.co.za/video/10367/barbara-creecy---1976--being-brought-up-by-a-single-mother---being-a-career-mom Barbara Creecy - 1976, being brought up by a single mother & being a career mom]\n*[https://ewn.co.za/2019/08/08/behind-the-politics-creecy-on-student-activism-juggling-career-and-family-life BEHIND THE POLITICS: Creecy on student activism, juggling career and family life]\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Creecy, Barbara}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:University of the Witwatersrand alumni]]\n[[Category:White South African anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added birthdate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barbara_Creecy"}
{"title_page": "Francis Cottington, 1st Baron Cottington", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}[[File:Francis Cottington, 1st Baron Cottington from NPG.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Lord Cottington]]\n\n'''Francis Cottington, 1st Baron Cottington''' (c. 1579{{spaced ndash}}1652) was the [[England|English]] lord treasurer and ambassador and leader of the pro-Spanish, pro\u2013Roman Catholic faction in the court of [[Charles I of England|Charles I]].\n\n==Early life==\nHe was the fourth son of Philip Cottington of [[Godmanston]] in [[Somerset]]shire. According to [[Sir Richard Hoare, 2nd Baronet|Hoare]], his mother was Jane, daughter of Thomas Biflete, but according to [[Edward Hyde, 1st Earl of Clarendon|Clarendon]], \"a Stafford nearly allied to Sir Edward Stafford\", through whom he was recommended to [[Sir Charles Cornwallis]], ambassador to the court of [[Philip III of Spain]], becoming a member of his suite and acting as English agent on the latter's recall, from 1609 to 1611.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n==Career==\n\nIn 1612 he was appointed English consul at [[Seville]].<ref name=\"hunneyball\">{{cite web|last1=Hunneyball|first1=Paul|title=COTTINGTON, Sir Francis, 1st Bt. (c. 1579-1652), of Charing Cross, Westminster and Hanworth, Mdx.; later of Fonthill Gifford, Wilts.|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/cottington-sir-francis-1579-1652|website=History of Parliament|publisher=The History of Parliament Trust|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> Returning to England, he was made a clerk of the council in September 1613. His Spanish experience rendered him useful to [[James I of England|King James]], and his bias in favour of Spain was always marked. He seemed to have promoted the Spanish policy from the first, and pressed on [[Diego Sarmiento de Acu\u00f1a, conde de Gondomar]], the Spanish ambassador, the proposal for the Spanish in opposition to the [[Henrietta Maria of France|French]] marriage for Prince Charles (later King Charles I).{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nIn 1616 he went as ambassador to Spain, transferring in 1618 the proposal of mediation by James I in the dispute with [[Frederick V, Elector Palatine]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}<ref name=\"hunneyball\"/>\n\n[[File:Wenceslas Hollar - Lord Cottington.jpg|thumb|left|Francis Cottington was created Baron Cottington of Hanworth in [[Middlesex]] in 1631.]]\n\nAfter his return he was appointed secretary to Prince Charles in October 1622, and was [[knight]]ed and made a [[baronet]] in 1623.<ref name=Cockayne>[https://archive.org/stream/cu31924092524374#page/n241/mode/2up  George Edward Cokayne ''Complete Baronetage, Volume 1'' 1900]</ref> He strongly disapproved of the prince's expedition to Spain, as an adventure likely to upset the whole policy of marriage and alliance, but was overruled and chosen to accompany him. His opposition greatly incensed [[George Villiers, 1st Duke of Buckingham]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Walter|first1=Henry|title=A History of England: Extending from the accession of James I to the abdication of James II|date=1834|publisher=J.G.F. & J. Rivington|page=85|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RvNRAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA85 }}</ref> and still more his perseverance in the Spanish policy after the failure of the expedition, and on Charles I's accession Cottington was through his means dismissed from all his employments and forbidden to appear at court. The duke's assassination, however, enabled him to return.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nHe was a Roman Catholic at least at heart, becoming a member of that communion in 1623, returning to [[Protestantism]], and again declaring himself a Roman Catholic in 1636, and supporting the cause of the Roman Catholics in England.<ref>{{cite web |title=COTTINGTON, Sir Francis, 1st Bt. (c.1579-1652), of Charing Cross, Westminster and Hanworth, Mdx.; later of Fonthill Gifford, Wilts. |url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/cottington-sir-francis-1579-1652 |website=The History of Parliament |publisher=The History of Parliament Trust |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> On 12 November 1628 he was made a [[Privy Council of England|privy councillor]], and in March 1629 appointed [[chancellor of the exchequer]].<ref name=\"hunneyball\"/> In the autumn he was again sent as ambassador to Spain; he signed the peace treaty of 5 November 1630 and subsequently a secret agreement arranging for the partition of the [[Dutch Republic]] between Spain and England in return for the restoration of the Palatinate. On 10 July 1631 he was created Baron Cottington of Hanworth in [[Middlesex]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nIn March 1635 he was appointed master of the [[Court of Wards and Liveries]], and his exactions in this office added greatly to the unpopularity of the government. He was also appointed a commissioner for the [[Treasury]], together with [[William Laud]], and a fierce rivalry sprang up between the two men. However, in their personal encounters Cottington nearly always had the advantage, because he practised great reserve and possessed great powers of self-command, an extraordinary talent for dissembling, and a fund of humour. Laud completely lacked these qualities, and although really possessing much greater influence with Charles, he was often embarrassed and sometimes exposed to ridicule by his opponent.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nThe aim of Cottington's ambition was the place of lord treasurer, but Laud finally triumphed and secured it for his own nominee, [[William Juxon|Bishop Juxon]], when Cottington became \"no more a leader but meddled with his particular duties only.\"<ref>Strafford's ''Letters'', ii. 52</ref> He continued, however, to take a large share in public business and served on the committees for foreign, [[Ireland|Irish]], and [[Scotland|Scottish]] affairs. In the last, appointed in July 1638, he supported the war, and in May 1640, after the dismissal of the [[Short Parliament]], he declared it his opinion that at such a crisis the king might levy money without the [[Parliament of England|Parliament]]. His attempts to get funds from the [[City of London]] were unsuccessful, and he had recourse instead to a speculation in [[black pepper|pepper]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n[[File:LordCottington.jpg|thumb|Francis Cottington's title became extinct at his death because all his children predeceased him.]]\n\nHe had been appointed constable of the [[Tower of London|Tower]], and he now prepared the fortress for a [[siege]]. In the trial of [[Thomas Wentworth, 1st Earl of Strafford|Strafford]] in 1641, Cottington denied on oath that he had heard him use the incriminating words about \"reducing this kingdom\". When the parliamentary opposition became too strong to be any longer defied, Cottington, as one of those who had chiefly incurred their hostility, hastened to retire from the administration, giving up the court of wards in May 1641 and the chancellorship of the exchequer in January 1642.<ref name=\"hunneyball\"/> He rejoined the king in 1643, took part in the proceedings of the [[Oxford Parliament (1644)|Oxford Parliament]], and was made [[Lord High Treasurer|lord treasurer]] on 3 October 1643. He signed the surrender of Oxford in July 1646, and being excepted from the indemnity retired abroad.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n==Career decline and death==\n\nHe joined Prince Charles at [[the Hague]] in 1648, and became one of his counsellors. In 1649, together with [[Edward Hyde, 1st Earl of Clarendon|Edward Hyde]], Cottington went on a mission to Spain to obtain help for the royal cause, having an interview with [[Cardinal Mazarin]] at [[Paris]] on the way. They met, however, with an extremely ill reception, and Cottington found he had completely lost his popularity at the Spanish court, one cause being his shortcomings and waverings in the matter of religion. He  announced his intention of remaining in Spain and of keeping faithful to Roman Catholicism, and took up his residence at [[Valladolid]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Granger|first1=James|title=A Biographical History of England|date=1824|publisher=Baynes|page=[https://archive.org/details/historyengland02granuoft/page/273 273]|url=https://archive.org/details/historyengland02granuoft|quote=Francis Cottington.}}</ref> where he was maintained by the [[Jesuit]]s. He died there on 19 June 1652, his body being subsequently buried in [[Westminster Abbey]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Cottington|url=http://www.westminster-abbey.org/our-history/people/francis-cottington|publisher=Westminster Abbey|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe had amassed a large fortune and built two magnificent houses at [[Hanworth]] near [[Heathrow]] and [[Fonthill Gifford|Fonthill]] near [[Tisbury, Wiltshire|Tisbury]], [[Salisbury]]. Cottington was evidently a man of considerable ability, but the foreign policy he pursued was opposed to the national interests and futile in itself. According to Clarendon's verdict \"he left behind him a greater esteem of his parts than love of his person.\"\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married in 1623 Anne, a daughter of Sir William Meredith and the widow of Sir Robert Brett. All his children predeceased him, and his title became extinct at his death.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Cottington, Francis Cottington, Baron |volume=7 |page=254}} This cites:\n**{{cite DNB|wstitle=Dart, John|volume=14|no-icon=1}}, and authorities there quoted\n**[[Edward Hyde, 1st Earl of Clarendon|Clarendon]]'s ''State Papers and Life''\n**[[Thomas Wentworth, 1st Earl of Strafford|Strafford]]'s ''Letters''\n**[[Samuel Rawson Gardiner|Gardiner]]'s ''Hist. of England and of the Commonwealth''\n**[[Sir Richard Hoare, 2nd Baronet|Hoare]]'s ''Wiltshire''\n**[[William Laud|Laud]]'s ''Works'', vols. iii.-vii.\n**Winwood's ''Memorials: A Refutation of a False and Impious Aspersion cast on the late Lord Cottington''\n**[[John Dart]], ''Westmonasterium'', i. 181 (epitaph and monument).\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{Commons category|Francis Cottington, 1st Baron Cottington}}\n* {{cite DNB|wstitle=Cottington, Francis|volume=12|first=Charles Harding |last=Firth }}\n* {{cite ODNB|first=Fiona|last=Pogson|title=Cottington, Francis, first Baron Cottington (1579?\u20131652)|id=6404}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|en}}\n{{succession box\n| title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Camelford (UK Parliament constituency)|Camelford]]\n| before=  [[Henry Carey, 2nd Earl of Monmouth|Sir Henry Carey]]\n| before2= [[Edward Carr (MP)|Edward Carr]]\n| with= [[Edward Hare]]\n| years=1624\u20131625\n| after= [[Henry Hungate|Sir Henry Hungate]]\n| after2= [[Thomas Coteel]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bossiney (UK Parliament constituency)|Bossiney]]\n| before=  [[Richard Weston, 1st Earl of Portland|Sir Richard Weston]]\n| before2= [[Thomas Bevans]]\n| with= [[Jonathan Prideaux]]\n| years=1625\n| after= [[Charles Lambart, 1st Earl of Cavan|The Lord Lambert]]\n| after2= [[Paul Speccot]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Saltash (UK Parliament constituency)|Saltash]]\n| before=  [[Richard Buller|Sir Richard Buller]]\n| before2= [[John Hayward (MP for Bridgnorth and Saltash)|Sir John Hayward]]\n| with= [[Richard Buller|Sir Richard Buller]]\n| years=1628\u20131629\n| after= Parliament suspended until 1640\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] | before=[[Edward Barrett, 1st Lord Barrett of Newburgh|Lord Barrett of Newburgh]] | after=[[John Colepeper, 1st Baron Colepeper|Sir John Colepeper]] | years=1629\u20131642}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | rows=3 | before=[[Theophilus Howard, 2nd Earl of Suffolk|The Earl of Suffolk]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[List of Vice-Admirals of Dorset|Vice-Admiral of Dorset]] | years=1640\u20131642}}\n{{s-vac | next=[[John Arthur (English politician)|John Arthur]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Lord Lieutenant of Dorset]] | years=1640\u20131641}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[William Cecil, 2nd Earl of Salisbury|The Earl of Salisbury]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Custos Rotulorum of Dorset]]|alongside=[[Denzil Holles, 1st Baron Holles|Hon. Denzil Holles]]<br>[[John Digby, 1st Earl of Bristol|The Earl of Bristol]]| years=1640\u20131646}}\n{{s-vac| reason=[[English Interregnum]]|next=[[John Digby, 3rd Earl of Bristol|The Earl of Bristol]]}}\n|-\n{{s-vac | 1 = co | reason=[[Edward Littleton, 1st Baron Lyttleton of Mounslow|The Lord Lyttleton of Mounslow]]<br>as First Lord|last=[[William Juxon|The Bishop of London]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Lord High Treasurer]] | years=1643\u20131646}}\n{{s-vac | 1 = co | reason=[[Edward Hyde, 1st Earl of Clarendon|Edward Hyde]] as First Lord|next=[[Thomas Wriothesley, 4th Earl of Southampton|The Earl of Southampton]]}}\n{{s-reg|en}}\n{{s-new|creation}}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Baron Cottington]]\n       | years  = 1631\u20131652}}\n{{S-non|reason=Extinct}}\n{{s-reg|en-bt}}\n{{s-new|creation}}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Cottington baronets|Baronet]]<br>'''(of Hanworth)\n       | years  = '''1623\u20131652}}\n{{S-non|reason=Extinct}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{House of Stuart Lord High Treasurers}}\n{{House of Stuart Chancellors of the Exchequer}}\n{{First Lords of the Admiralty|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{EB1911 article with no significant updates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cottington, Francis Cottington, 1st Baron}}\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of England]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the Exchequer of England]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of England to Spain]]\n[[Category:Lord-Lieutenants of Dorset]]\n[[Category:Members of the pre-1707 English Parliament for constituencies in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1624\u20131625]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1625]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1628\u20131629]]\n[[Category:People from Somerset]]\n[[Category:1570s births]]\n[[Category:1652 deaths]]\n[[Category:Clerks of the Privy Council]]\n[[Category:16th-century English nobility]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:Burials at Westminster Abbey]]\n[[Category:17th-century English diplomats]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}[[File:Francis Cottington, 1st Baron Cottington from NPG.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Lord Cottington]]\n\n'''Francis Cottington, 1st Baron Cottington''' (c. 1579{{spaced ndash}}1652) was the [[England|English]] lord treasurer and ambassador and leader of the pro-Spanish, pro\u2013Roman Catholic faction in the court of [[Charles I of England|Charles I]].\n\n==Early life==\nHe was the fourth son of Philip Cottington of [[Godmanston]] in [[Somerset]]shire. According to [[Sir Richard Hoare, 2nd Baronet|Hoare]], his mother was Jane, daughter of Thomas Biflete, but according to [[Edward Hyde, 1st Earl of Clarendon|Clarendon]], \"a Stafford nearly allied to Sir Edward Stafford\", through whom he was recommended to [[Sir Charles Cornwallis]], ambassador to the court of [[Philip III of Spain]], becoming a member of his suite and acting as English agent on the latter's recall, from 1609 to 1611.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n==Career==\n\nIn 1612 he was appointed English consul at [[Seville]].<ref name=\"hunneyball\">{{cite web|last1=Hunneyball|first1=Paul|title=COTTINGTON, Sir Francis, 1st Bt. (c. 1579-1652), of Charing Cross, Westminster and Hanworth, Mdx.; later of Fonthill Gifford, Wilts.|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/cottington-sir-francis-1579-1652|website=History of Parliament|publisher=The History of Parliament Trust|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> Returning to England, he was made a clerk of the council in September 1613. His Spanish experience rendered him useful to [[James I of England|King James]], and his bias in favour of Spain was always marked. He seemed to have promoted the Spanish policy from the first, and pressed on [[Diego Sarmiento de Acu\u00f1a, conde de Gondomar]], the Spanish ambassador, the proposal for the Spanish in opposition to the [[Henrietta Maria of France|French]] marriage for Prince Charles (later King Charles I).{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nIn 1616 he went as ambassador to Spain, transferring in 1618 the proposal of mediation by James I in the dispute with [[Frederick V, Elector Palatine]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}<ref name=\"hunneyball\"/>\n\n[[File:Wenceslas Hollar - Lord Cottington.jpg|thumb|left|Francis Cottington was created Baron Cottington of Hanworth in [[Middlesex]] in 1631.]]\n\nAfter his return he was appointed secretary to Prince Charles in October 1622, and was [[knight]]ed and made a [[baronet]] in 1623.<ref name=Cockayne>[https://archive.org/stream/cu31924092524374#page/n241/mode/2up  George Edward Cokayne ''Complete Baronetage, Volume 1'' 1900]</ref> He strongly disapproved of the prince's expedition to Spain, as an adventure likely to upset the whole policy of marriage and alliance, but was overruled and chosen to accompany him. His opposition greatly incensed [[George Villiers, 1st Duke of Buckingham]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Walter|first1=Henry|title=A History of England: Extending from the accession of James I to the abdication of James II|date=1834|publisher=J.G.F. & J. Rivington|page=85|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RvNRAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA85 }}</ref> and still more his perseverance in the Spanish policy after the failure of the expedition, and on Charles I's accession Cottington was through his means dismissed from all his employments and forbidden to appear at court. The duke's assassination, however, enabled him to return.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nHe was a Roman Catholic at least at heart, becoming a member of that communion in 1623, returning to [[Protestantism]], and again declaring himself a Roman Catholic in 1636, and supporting the cause of the Roman Catholics in England.<ref>{{cite web |title=COTTINGTON, Sir Francis, 1st Bt. (c.1579-1652), of Charing Cross, Westminster and Hanworth, Mdx.; later of Fonthill Gifford, Wilts. |url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/cottington-sir-francis-1579-1652 |website=The History of Parliament |publisher=The History of Parliament Trust |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> On 12 November 1628 he was made a [[Privy Council of England|privy councillor]], and in March 1629 appointed [[chancellor of the exchequer]].<ref name=\"hunneyball\"/> In the autumn he was again sent as ambassador to Spain; he signed the peace treaty of 5 November 1630 and subsequently a secret agreement arranging for the partition of the [[Dutch Republic]] between Spain and England in return for the restoration of the Palatinate. On 10 July 1631 he was created Baron Cottington of Hanworth in [[Middlesex]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nIn March 1635 he was appointed master of the [[Court of Wards and Liveries]], and his exactions in this office added greatly to the unpopularity of the government. He was also appointed a commissioner for the [[Treasury]], together with [[William Laud]], and a fierce rivalry sprang up between the two men. However, in their personal encounters Cottington nearly always had the advantage, because he practised great reserve and possessed great powers of self-command, an extraordinary talent for dissembling, and a fund of humour. Laud completely lacked these qualities, and although really possessing much greater influence with Charles, he was often embarrassed and sometimes exposed to ridicule by his opponent.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nThe aim of Cottington's ambition was the place of lord treasurer, but Laud finally triumphed and secured it for his own nominee, [[William Juxon|Bishop Juxon]], when Cottington became \"no more a leader but meddled with his particular duties only.\"<ref>Strafford's ''Letters'', ii. 52</ref> He continued, however, to take a large share in public business and served on the committees for foreign, [[Ireland|Irish]], and [[Scotland|Scottish]] affairs. In the last, appointed in July 1638, he supported the war, and in May 1640, after the dismissal of the [[Short Parliament]], he declared it his opinion that at such a crisis the king might levy money without the [[Parliament of England|Parliament]]. His attempts to get funds from the [[City of London]] were unsuccessful, and he had recourse instead to a speculation in [[black pepper|pepper]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n[[File:LordCottington.jpg|thumb|Francis Cottington's title became extinct at his death because all his children predeceased him.]]\n\nHe had been appointed constable of the [[Tower of London|Tower]], and he now prepared the fortress for a [[siege]]. In the trial of [[Thomas Wentworth, 1st Earl of Strafford|Strafford]] in 1641, Cottington denied on oath that he had heard him use the incriminating words about \"reducing this kingdom\". When the parliamentary opposition became too strong to be any longer defied, Cottington, as one of those who had chiefly incurred their hostility, hastened to retire from the administration, giving up the court of wards in May 1641 and the chancellorship of the exchequer in January 1642.<ref name=\"hunneyball\"/> He rejoined the king in 1643, took part in the proceedings of the [[Oxford Parliament (1644)|Oxford Parliament]], and was made [[Lord High Treasurer|lord treasurer]] on 3 October 1643. He signed the surrender of Oxford in July 1646, and being excepted from the indemnity retired abroad.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n==Career decline and death==\n\nHe joined Prince Charles at [[the Hague]] in 1648, and became one of his counsellors. In 1649, together with [[Edward Hyde, 1st Earl of Clarendon|Edward Hyde]], Cottington went on a mission to Spain to obtain help for the royal cause, having an interview with [[Cardinal Mazarin]] at [[Paris]] on the way. They met, however, with an extremely ill reception, and Cottington found he had completely lost his popularity at the Spanish court, one cause being his shortcomings and waverings in the matter of religion. He  announced his intention of remaining in Spain and of keeping faithful to Roman Catholicism, and took up his residence at [[Valladolid]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Granger|first1=James|title=A Biographical History of England|date=1824|publisher=Baynes|page=[https://archive.org/details/historyengland02granuoft/page/273 273]|url=https://archive.org/details/historyengland02granuoft|quote=Francis Cottington.}}</ref> where he was maintained by the [[Jesuit]]s. He died there on 19 June 1652, his body being subsequently buried in [[Westminster Abbey]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Cottington|url=http://www.westminster-abbey.org/our-history/people/francis-cottington|publisher=Westminster Abbey|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe had amassed a large fortune and built two magnificent houses at [[Hanworth]] near [[Heathrow]] and [[Fonthill Gifford|Fonthill]] near [[Tisbury, Wiltshire|Tisbury]], [[Salisbury]]. Cottington was evidently a man of considerable ability, but the foreign policy he pursued was opposed to the national interests and futile in itself. According to Clarendon's verdict \"he left behind him a greater esteem of his parts than love of his person.\"\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married in 1623 Anne, a daughter of Sir William Meredith and the widow of Sir Robert Brett. All his children predeceased him, and his title became extinct at his death.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Cottington, Francis Cottington, Baron |volume=7 |page=254}} This cites:\n**{{cite DNB|wstitle=Dart, John|volume=14|no-icon=1}}, and authorities there quoted\n**[[Edward Hyde, 1st Earl of Clarendon|Clarendon]]'s ''State Papers and Life''\n**[[Thomas Wentworth, 1st Earl of Strafford|Strafford]]'s ''Letters''\n**[[Samuel Rawson Gardiner|Gardiner]]'s ''Hist. of England and of the Commonwealth''\n**[[Sir Richard Hoare, 2nd Baronet|Hoare]]'s ''Wiltshire''\n**[[William Laud|Laud]]'s ''Works'', vols. iii.-vii.\n**Winwood's ''Memorials: A Refutation of a False and Impious Aspersion cast on the late Lord Cottington''\n**[[John Dart]], ''Westmonasterium'', i. 181 (epitaph and monument).\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Francis Cottington, 1st Baron Cottington}}\n* {{cite DNB|wstitle=Cottington, Francis|volume=12|first=Charles Harding |last=Firth }}\n* {{cite ODNB|first=Fiona|last=Pogson|title=Cottington, Francis, first Baron Cottington (1579?\u20131652)|id=6404}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|en}}\n{{succession box\n| title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Camelford (UK Parliament constituency)|Camelford]]\n| before=  [[Henry Carey, 2nd Earl of Monmouth|Sir Henry Carey]]\n| before2= [[Edward Carr (MP)|Edward Carr]]\n| with= [[Edward Hare]]\n| years=1624\u20131625\n| after= [[Henry Hungate|Sir Henry Hungate]]\n| after2= [[Thomas Coteel]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bossiney (UK Parliament constituency)|Bossiney]]\n| before=  [[Richard Weston, 1st Earl of Portland|Sir Richard Weston]]\n| before2= [[Thomas Bevans]]\n| with= [[Jonathan Prideaux]]\n| years=1625\n| after= [[Charles Lambart, 1st Earl of Cavan|The Lord Lambert]]\n| after2= [[Paul Speccot]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Saltash (UK Parliament constituency)|Saltash]]\n| before=  [[Richard Buller|Sir Richard Buller]]\n| before2= [[John Hayward (MP for Bridgnorth and Saltash)|Sir John Hayward]]\n| with= [[Richard Buller|Sir Richard Buller]]\n| years=1628\u20131629\n| after= Parliament suspended until 1640\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] | before=[[Edward Barrett, 1st Lord Barrett of Newburgh|Lord Barrett of Newburgh]] | after=[[John Colepeper, 1st Baron Colepeper|Sir John Colepeper]] | years=1629\u20131642}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | rows=3 | before=[[Theophilus Howard, 2nd Earl of Suffolk|The Earl of Suffolk]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[List of Vice-Admirals of Dorset|Vice-Admiral of Dorset]] | years=1640\u20131642}}\n{{s-vac | next=[[John Arthur (English politician)|John Arthur]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Lord Lieutenant of Dorset]] | years=1640\u20131641}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[William Cecil, 2nd Earl