{"title_page": "Edna Mode", "text_new": "{{short description|\"The Incredibles\" character}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color              = #080410\n| series             = [[The Incredibles (franchise)|The Incredibles]]\n| name               = Edna Mode\n| image              = Edna Mode promotional image.jpg\n| first              = ''[[The Incredibles]]'' (2004)\n| last               = ''[[Incredibles 2]]'' (2018)\n| creator            = [[Brad Bird]]\n| voice              = Brad Bird\n| full_name          = Edna Mode\n| nickname           = E\n| species            = Human\n| occupation         = [[Fashion design]]er<br>[[Costume designer]]\n}}\n'''Edna \"E\" Mode'''<ref name=\":38\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=YyniCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA156&lpg=PA156&dq=Spoiled,+stupid+little+stick+figures+with+poofy+lips+who+think+only+about+themselves&source=bl&ots=dESvSHX-_1&sig=7EGgbqG1-Al1dcsSXDy_d8uiumY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiC9K_W0azZAhWD6YMKHS3oB9UQ6AEIYjAO#v=onepage&q=Spoiled%2C%20stupid%20little%20stick%20figures%20with%20poofy%20lips%20who%20think%20only%20about%20themselves&f=false|title=The Art of The Incredibles|last=Cotta Vaz|first=Mark|publisher=Chronicle Books|year=2015|isbn=9781452147574|location=United States|pages=62|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218090250/https://books.google.ca/books?id=YyniCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA156&lpg=PA156&dq=Spoiled,+stupid+little+stick+figures+with+poofy+lips+who+think+only+about+themselves&source=bl&ots=dESvSHX-_1&sig=7EGgbqG1-Al1dcsSXDy_d8uiumY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiC9K_W0azZAhWD6YMKHS3oB9UQ6AEIYjAO#v=onepage&q=Spoiled%2C%20stupid%20little%20stick%20figures%20with%20poofy%20lips%20who%20think%20only%20about%20themselves&f=false|archivedate=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":31\" /> is a fictional character in [[Pixar]]'s [[Computer animation|animated]] [[superhero film]] ''[[The Incredibles]]'' (2004) and its sequel ''[[Incredibles 2]]'' (2018). She is an eccentric fashion designer renowned for designing the costumes of several famous superheroes, having worked particularly closely with [[Bob Parr (The Incredibles)|Mr. Incredible]] and [[Elastigirl]] (Bob and Helen Parr), with whom she has maintained a strong friendship. When the couple resumes their superheroic careers after fifteen years, Edna is summoned out of retirement to aid both characters, first by equipping Mr. Incredible with a new costume and then by restoring Elastigirl's confidence in herself as a superheroine.\n\nEdna was created by screenwriter and director [[Brad Bird]] to explain how ''The Incredibles''<nowiki/>' superheroes obtain their costumes, a topic he believes is rarely explored in superhero films convincingly. Bird also decided to voice the character himself after several actresses originally considered for the role failed to replicate Edna's unique accent. The director understood that, in addition to fashion expertise, the character would also need to demonstrate proficiency in science, engineering and technology in order to create costumes capable of withstanding the trials of superheroic activities, and ultimately conceived her as a short, confident character of both German and Japanese descent based on these countries' reputations as small yet powerful nations. Inspired by [[Q (James Bond)|Q]] from the ''[[James Bond (franchise)|James Bond]]'' franchise, Edna is widely believed to have been based primarily on costume designer [[Edith Head]], although there continues to be constant speculation as to which celebrities inspired Edna, particularly ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' editor-in-chief [[Anna Wintour]] and actress [[Linda Hunt]].\n\nDespite having only supporting roles in both films, Edna has since established herself as ''The Incredibles''{{'}} [[breakout character]] due to her popularity among fans. While film critics agree that Edna is a [[Scene stealer|scene-stealer]], particularly praising her humor and dialogue, Bird has also been lauded for his voice acting, earning an [[Annie Award]] for [[Annie Award for Voice Acting in a Feature Production|Voice Acting in a Feature Production]] for his performance as the character. Edna has been recognized as one of Pixar's greatest characters by several prominent media publications.\n\n==Development==\n===Creation and voice===\n[[File:Brad bird cropped 2009.jpg|thumb|209x209px|In addition to creating the character, writer and director [[Brad Bird]] also provides the voice of Edna, using a unique accent that has been described as a hybrid between German and Japanese.|left]]Edna was created for ''The Incredibles'' by writer and director [[Brad Bird]].<ref name=\":33\" /> Having watched several [[Superhero fiction|superhero-themed films and television shows]] prior to developing ''The Incredibles'', Bird had often found himself wondering who is responsible for making the superheroes' elaborate costumes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2004/oct/22/20041022-090900-7146r/|title=\u2018Incredibles\u2019 creator eyes superheroes\u2019 home lives|last=|first=|date=October 22, 2004|website=[[The Washington Times]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202659/https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2004/oct/22/20041022-090900-7146r/|archivedate=February 17, 2018|access-date=February 17, 2018}}</ref> Bird conceived Edna upon discovering that, despite featuring characters dressed in fancy, extravagant costumes, traditional [[superhero film]]s rarely offer plausible explanations as to how superheroes come to obtain these outfits, or who provides them in the first place.<ref name=\":0\" /> The director wanted to debunk the [[Trope (literature)|trope]] of muscular superheroes sewing their own costumes, finding it hard to believe that superheroes would suddenly develop a strong enough interest in fashion and textiles to design their own outfits.<ref name=\":0\" /> Therefore, Bird decided that if the world was populated with superheroes, there would naturally also be people responsible for designing their costumes who must also have a background in science and engineering,<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://lifestyle.howstuffworks.com/family/activities/movie-fun-night/how-the-incredibles-works4.htm|title=Ultimate Guide to 'The Incredibles' \u2013 'The Incredibles' Characters|last=Arkoff|first=Vicki|date=|website=[[HowStuffWorks]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202846/https://lifestyle.howstuffworks.com/family/activities/movie-fun-night/how-the-incredibles-works4.htm|archivedate=February 17, 2018|access-date=February 17, 2018}}</ref> thereby envisioning Edna as a scientist and technical genius in addition to being a fashion designer.<ref name=\":0\" /> The director elaborated, \"The way I saw it, the costumes had to be created by somebody with a scientific and engineering background\", thus conceiving Edna as \"a half-German, half-Japanese, tiny powerhouse of a character\".<ref name=\":6\" /> ''The Incredibles'' was the first Pixar film to earn a [[PG-Rating|PG rating]]; Edna is considered to be one of the studio's earliest attempts at approaching \"[[Dark-comedy|darker, edgier comedy]],\" which is particularly demonstrated by the scene in which the character cites several [[Graphic violence|graphic]] examples of capes directly resulting in the deaths of several superheroes, one of whom is shown being consumed and killed by a jet turbine.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite web|url=http://ew.com/gallery/pixar-top-12-movie-moments/12-the-incredibles-edna-modes-no-capes-speech|title=Pixar: Top 12 Movie Moments|last=Young|first=John|date=June 21, 2013|website=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219152052/http://ew.com/gallery/pixar-top-12-movie-moments/12-the-incredibles-edna-modes-no-capes-speech/|archivedate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> According to Bird, the creation of Edna took the notion of superheroes wearing designed costumes \"to a further extreme\".<ref name=\":38\" />\n\nEdna was named after EMode, a software Pixar used at the time the film was made.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/gallery/2011/jun/26/pixar-animation|title=The 10 best Pixar characters|last=Solomons|first=Jason|date=June 26, 2011|website=The Guardian|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218210210/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/gallery/2011/jun/26/pixar-animation|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.ca/translate?hl=en&sl=nl&u=https://www.vpro.nl/programmas/zomergasten/lees/gasten/2012/achtergronden-fragmenten-2012/the-incredibles.html&prev=search|title=the incredibles|last=|first=|date=2012|website=VPRO|language=Dutch|access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":40\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/female-pixar-characters-who-deserve-film/|title=15 Female Pixar Characters Who Deserve a Feature Film|last=Friday|first=Wednesday Lee|date=June 18, 2016|website=Screen Rant|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> Bird identified Edna as the \"most fun character\" he had written for the film, recalling, \"Any day that I was writing her, I was one happy camper.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Edna follows the tradition of having a director voice one of the film's secondary characters in animated films, which was based around Bird's \"slave-driver voice\" that he used during production.<ref name=\":39\">{{Cite web|url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/the-10-best-pixar-characters-from-infinity-to-squirrel-ed3fd6988175/|title=The 10 Best Pixar Characters: From Infinity to Squirrel!|last=Carr|first=Kevin|date=June 21, 2012|website=Film School Rejects|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> Bird's voice for the character originated during the story boarding process, during which various Pixar employees typically provide characters' voices temporarily while the filmmakers and animators organize the film's pacing and staging in order to \"get a sense of the film.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://moviecitynews.com/archived/Interviews/bird.html|title=Brad Bird & The Incredibles|last=Gronvall|first=Andrea|date=November 10, 2004|website=Movie City News|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202747/http://moviecitynews.com/archived/Interviews/bird.html|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref> Although these voices are usually eventually replaced by professional actors and voice actors, there are some situations in which \"those voices stick\", as was the case with the voice Bird had created for Edna.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://movies.radiofree.com/interviews/theincre_brad_bird.shtml|title=Brad Bird|last=Lee|first=Michael J.|date=October 17, 2004|website=RadioFree.com|access-date=February 16, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217082446/http://movies.radiofree.com/interviews/theincre_brad_bird.shtml|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref> Bird had also provided the temporary voices of other characters during this time, including Bob Parr and Syndrome.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.movingimagesource.us/files/dialogues/2/90944_programs_transcript_html_253.htm|title=A Pinewood Dialogue with Brad Bird|last=Goodman|first=Carl|date=January 9, 2005|website=Moving Image Source|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701005231/http://www.movingimagesource.us/files/dialogues/2/90944_programs_transcript_html_253.htm|archivedate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> Several actresses had been considered for the role; one actress, whom Bird is particularly fond of, constantly asked Bird to repeatedly demonstrate his interpretation of one of Edna's lines until telling him that he should simply voice the character himself since he \"kind of got a beat on it\".<ref name=\":0\" /> The role was also offered to actress and comedian [[Lily Tomlin]], who was sent a tape recording of Bird recording Edna's part in its entirety;<ref name=\":44\" /> Tomlin declined upon hearing Bird's interpretation, feeling she could not voice the character as funnily as he did.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=e1RTP8thtR0C&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25&dq=edna+mode+lily+tomlin&source=bl&ots=ASWFtvrLR7&sig=703hElh4tLysKjuRiC2dgNPYycQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiA0LXjtqzZAhVHRK0KHc2uCHc4ChDoAQg0MAM#v=onepage&q=edna%20mode%20lily%20tomlin&f=false|title=Disney Voice Actors: A Biographical Dictionary|last=Hischak|first=Thomas S.|publisher=McFarland|year=2011|isbn=9780786486946|location=United States|pages=25|via=Google Books|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218090155/https://books.google.ca/books?id=e1RTP8thtR0C&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25&dq=edna+mode+lily+tomlin&source=bl&ots=ASWFtvrLR7&sig=703hElh4tLysKjuRiC2dgNPYycQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiA0LXjtqzZAhVHRK0KHc2uCHc4ChDoAQg0MAM#v=onepage&q=edna%20mode%20lily%20tomlin&f=false|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Bird's colleagues had to heavily convince him to voice the character himself.<ref name=\":37\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/07/best-performances-in-animation-since-aladdin.html|title=The 25 Best Animated Movie Voice Performances Since Aladdin|last=Ebiri|first=Bilge|date=July 10, 2015|website=Vulture.com|access-date=May 2, 2018}}</ref> Finally succumbing to \"popular demand\" from his fellow Pixar employees, Bird joked that he was ultimately cast as Edna simply because he was both affordable and available at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/04/03/398343037/pixars-brad-bird-talks-french-food-animated-rats-and-new-film-tomorrowland|title=Pixar's Brad Bird Talks French Food, Animated Rats And New Film 'Tomorrowland'|date=April 8, 2015|website=NPR|access-date=February 16, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409000805/http://www.npr.org/2015/04/03/398343037/pixars-brad-bird-talks-french-food-animated-rats-and-new-film-tomorrowland|archivedate=April 9, 2015}}</ref> A similar tactic was used for several other supporting characters in the film: animator Bret Parker voices Kari, the Parr family's babysitter, writer [[Bud Luckey]] voices government agent Rick Dicker,<ref name=\":7\" /> and production designer [[Lou Romano]] voices Bernie Kropp, Dash's teacher.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nBird described Edna's voice as a combination of a Japanese and German accent, deciding to draw influence from these countries because \"they're two small countries that have amazing design and amazing technology\", citing cameras and cars of examples of technology in which they specialize.<ref name=\":0\" /> Urban Cinefile's Louise Keller described the character's voice as \"mid European ... complicated by an Asian touch\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.urbancinefile.com.au/home/view.asp?a=9758&s=Reviews|title=Incredibles, The|last=Keller|first=Louise|last2=Urban|first2=Andrew L.|date=December 26, 2004|website=Urban Cinefile|access-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180302103840/http://www.urbancinefile.com.au/home/view.asp?a=9758&s=Reviews|archivedate=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Although Bird's performance is considerably broad, he avoids allowing Edna to become too much of a [[caricature]] in order to maintain the illusion that she is one of the film's smartest characters.<ref name=\":22\" /> In the Italian and French-language versions of the film, Bird's comic accent is replaced by that of French-Italian entertainer [[Amanda Lear]], who offers a more seductive, \"biting\" interpretation.<ref name=\":8\" /> Lear said that dubbing Edna's voice was not an easy process, but accepted the job after being offered the role upon seeing the film at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] in order to fulfill her dream of having always wanted to voice a Disney character.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.ca/translate?hl=en&sl=it&u=http://trovacinema.repubblica.it/news/dettaglio/amanda-lear-doppiando-edna-del-film-gli-incredibili-ho-coronato-il-sogno-di-bambina/281964/&prev=search|title=Amanda Lear: Doubling Edna from the Film 'The Incredibles'{{!}}\"I Crowned My Childhood Dream\"|last=|first=|date=November 18, 2004|website=Trovacinema|language=Italian|access-date=February 17, 2018}}</ref> Edna was the first character Lear was hired to dub in Italian.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n===Personality, design and influences===\nBird believes that he shares some of Edna's personality traits, specifically the way in which he prefers to be involved in virtually every creative aspect of his projects, including story boarding, writing and cinematography,<ref name=\":1\" /> admitting that he and his character demonstrate both a high level of self-confidence and lack of self-doubt when it comes to their own work.<ref name=\":6\" /> Bird elaborated that \"At my most confident, I feel like her \n... She is absolutely convinced that her way is the right way, and if you disagree \u2026 you\u2019re just wrong!\u201d<ref name=\":44\">{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/06/14/incredibles-edna-mode-is-based-on-these-fashion-mavens/|title=\u2018Incredibles\u2019 Edna Mode is based on these fashion mavens|last=Miller|first=Gregory E.|date=June 14, 2018|website=[[New York Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref> Bird identified Edna as one of the film's most difficult characters to design.<ref name=\":38\" /> The character went through several different changes in appearance during the development process, ranging from taller and overweight to older, younger and thinner.<ref name=\":7\" /> Inspired by the large impact that countries such as Japan and Germany have on the world despite being comparatively small in size, Bird decided that Edna would demonstrate this theme by being \"a tiny character that dominates the room when she gets into it.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Her home, which uses high-end technology similar to what she incorporates into the outfits she creates,<ref name=\":31\" /> was deliberately designed to be significantly larger than she is to further emphasize this theme of dominance.<ref name=\":0\" /> Edna's small stature was also inspired by singer [[Bette Midler]], of whom Bird has always been a fan. The director recalled being surprised by Midler's height when he first met her \"Because ... she absolutely dominates the screen. And it just struck me how much personality was in this small body.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In terms of animation, Bird wanted all of the film's characters to move differently from each other, providing Edna with a very confident walk to represent the fact that she has \"never experienced doubt in her life.\"<ref name=\":11\" /> The animators found the fact that Bird provided the character's voice himself to be very helpful as he would often act out the way in which the character acts and behaves himself, which helped in further defining the animator's vision of Edna.<ref name=\":38\" /> According to Bird, Edna, despite her petite stature, is the only non-superhero in ''The Incredibles'' capable of making superheroes feel uncomfortable.<ref name=\":30\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=LhOwDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA142&dq=edna+mode+incredibles&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXseeO49rZAhXCmuAKHZn3DOUQ6AEIVTAJ#v=onepage&q=edna%20mode%20incredibles&f=false|title=Pixar and the Aesthetic Imagination: Animation, Storytelling, and Digital Culture|last=Herhuth|first=Eric|publisher=Univ of California Press|year=2017|isbn=9780520966055|location=United States|pages=142|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308042517/https://books.google.ca/books?id=LhOwDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA142&dq=edna+mode+incredibles&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXseeO49rZAhXCmuAKHZn3DOUQ6AEIVTAJ#v=onepage&q=edna%20mode%20incredibles&f=false|archivedate=March 8, 2018|url-status=live|via=Google Books}}</ref> Bird described Edna as a character who is \"not remotely intimidated by superheroes or anyone\", refusing to accept the word \"no\" when it is used in opposition of her opinions or beliefs.<ref name=\":6\" />\nEdna was actually inspired by Edith Head who was also a costume designer and won a record of 8 Academy Awards for costume design. \n[[Entertainment Weekly|<nowiki/>]][[Entertainment Weekly|<nowiki/>]]\n\nDescribing Edna's physical attributes as \"severe\", Bird had envisioned the character having glasses and a pageboy haircut, while still wanting her to appear modern and elegant at the same time.<ref name=\":38\" /> Edna's ethnicity has been identified as half-German and half-Japanese.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/70795/17-super-facts-about-incredibles|title=17 Super Facts About The Incredibles|last=Cormier|first=Roger|date=November 5, 2015|website=Mental Floss|access-date=February 17, 2018|quote=Edna Mode was made half German and half Japanese after Bird thought about German engineering and Japanese car and camera manufacturing ...|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202918/http://mentalfloss.com/article/70795/17-super-facts-about-incredibles|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=http://movies.disney.com/the-incredibles/characters|title=Characters {{!}} The Incredibles|website=Disney.com|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218210418/http://movies.disney.com/the-incredibles/characters|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Both Edna's physical appearance and voice are widely believed to have based on those of costume designer [[Edith Head]],<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":47\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.racked.com/2018/6/14/17461468/edna-mode-incredibles-fashion|title=The Incredibles\u2019 Edna Mode Is Film\u2019s Best Fashion Character|last=Wisel|first=Carlye|date=June 14, 2018|website=Racked|access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref> with whom she shares her signature round glasses and black [[bob cut]].<ref name=\":8\" /> According to Head's entry in the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]], the character is inspired by both the costume designer's signature glasses and \"forthright personality\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/collection-highlights/edith-head|title=Edith Head|website=Oscars.org|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218090311/http://www.oscars.org/collection-highlights/edith-head|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Bird described Edna as a combination of both Head and [[Q (James Bond)|Q]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://themovieboy.com/reviews/i/04_incredibles.htm|title=The Incredibles (2004)|last=Putman|first=Dustin|date=November 6, 2004|website=TheFilmFile|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319213642/http://themovieboy.com/reviews/i/04_incredibles.htm|archive-date=March 19, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=March 19, 2018|quote=Also notable is Edna \"E\" Mode (voiced wonderfully by director Brad Bird and taking a page from the James Bond series' M figure)}}</ref> a character featured in the ''[[James Bond]]'' franchise.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://ew.com/article/2004/11/19/who-incredibles-fashion-maven-based/|title=Who is the ''Incredibles'' fashion maven based on?|last=Daly|first=Steve|date=November 19, 2004|website=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202839/http://ew.com/article/2004/11/19/who-incredibles-fashion-maven-based/|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":24\">{{Cite web|url=http://q13fox.com/2015/11/20/here-are-pixars-15-best-characters/|title=Here are Pixar\u2019s 15 best characters|last=|first=|date=November 20, 2015|website=[[Q13 FOX News]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219090619/http://q13fox.com/2015/11/20/here-are-pixars-15-best-characters/|archivedate=February 19, 2018|access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> The director has generally declined to confirm any direct influences on the character, insisting that Edna is \"not based on a specific person\",<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-incredible-edna-vol-62-no-22/|title=Picks and Pans Review: Incredible Edna|date=November 29, 2004|website=People|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202840/http://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-incredible-edna-vol-62-no-22/|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref> including publicly refuting claims that he based the character on Head, although she continues to be considered the character's \"most legitimate\" alleged inspiration.<ref name=\":47\" /> However, animator [[Teddy Newton]], who co-designed Edna with Bird, revealed that he and Pixar were inspired by the film ''[[Unzipped (film)|Unzipped]]'' (1995), a documentary depicting the petulance of fashion designer [[Isaac Mizrahi]] and stylist [[Polly Allen Mellen]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Fans have long speculated about the real-life inspiration behind Edna's design and appearance.<ref name=\":44\" /><ref name=\":47\" /> Bird stated he has constantly been told by various fans and viewers that the character reminds them of at least 15 different celebrities since the character debuted in ''The Incredibles''.<ref name=\":2\" /> Contributing to ''[[Fashion (magazine)|Fashion]]'', Erin Dunlop described the character as \"a supercharged hybrid of every fashion industry legend we can think of\".<ref name=\":34\">{{Cite web|url=https://fashionmagazine.com/culture/fashion-industry-fictional-characters/|title=The 10 coolest fashion industry pros (hint: they\u2019re all fictional characters)|last=Dunlop|first=Erin|date=February 4, 2016|website=Fashion|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315070538/https://fashionmagazine.com/culture/fashion-industry-fictional-characters/|archive-date=March 15, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> In an article discussing who Edna is based on, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''[[Entertainment Weekly|<nowiki/>']]<nowiki/>s Steve Daly cited ''Vogue'' editor-in-chief [[Anna Wintour]], designer [[Coco Chanel]] and actress [[Lotte Lenya]] as possible influences, while drawing similarities between the character's use of large-framed glasses to architect [[Philip Johnson]], producer [[Robert Evans]], talent agent [[Irving Paul Lazar|Swifty Lazar]], studio executive [[Lew Wasserman]], and fashion editor [[Carrie Donovan]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Some critics have suspected that the character is also based on [[Mary Quant]] and Una Jones.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=gyjob_gq3yoC&pg=PA391&lpg=PA391&dq=brad+bird+edna+mode+interview&source=bl&ots=HHGSLlhwsz&sig=AcTYOvZ0uNXi8FqyMHwrQvnVcHY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwic3cHmtazZAhWKxYMKHR8YDYg4HhDoAQheMAw#v=onepage&q=brad%20bird%20edna%20mode%20interview&f=false|title=Edith Head: The Fifty-Year Career of Hollywood's Greatest Costume Designer|last1=Jorgensen|first1=Jay|date=2010|publisher=Running Press|isbn=9780762441730|location=United States|page=391|language=en|via=Google Books|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218092128/https://books.google.ca/books?id=gyjob_gq3yoC&pg=PA391&lpg=PA391&dq=brad+bird+edna+mode+interview&source=bl&ots=HHGSLlhwsz&sig=AcTYOvZ0uNXi8FqyMHwrQvnVcHY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwic3cHmtazZAhWKxYMKHR8YDYg4HhDoAQheMAw#v=onepage&q=brad%20bird%20edna%20mode%20interview&f=false|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Acknowledging that there are several female fashion designers who wear glasses upon whom Edna could have been based, Bird admitted that the character was inspired by author [[Patricia Highsmith]] and actress [[Linda Hunt]], elaborating: \"When you're designing a character, you're just saying - who is that? ... We tried a lot of stuff and we kept saying no, no, more like this, but I like the nose on this one, and maybe the [[Pageboy|pageboy cut]], maybe glasses should be bigger ... and you end up with something that reminds you of Edith Head and Linda Hunt.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|last1=Gilchrist|first1=Todd|title=The Incredibles: An Interview with Brad Bird|url=http://www.blackfilm.com/20041029/features/bradbird.shtml|website=Blackfilm|accessdate=February 17, 2018|date=November 2004|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625145649/http://www.blackfilm.com/20041029/features/bradbird.shtml|archivedate=June 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":36\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.chasingthefrog.com/reelfaces/devilwearsprada.php|title=The Devil Wears Prada (2006)|website=Chasing the Frog|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321063113/http://www.chasingthefrog.com/reelfaces/devilwearsprada.php|archive-date=March 21, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Entertainment Weekly|<nowiki/>]]\n\nFor the sequel, shading art director Bryn Imagire decided to incorporate more of Edna's Japanese heritage into her two new costumes, basing them on the work of Japanese costume designers [[Rei Kawakubo]], [[Eiko Ishioka]] and Chitose Abe.<ref name=\":44\" /> Imagire was particularly inspired by Kawakubo's quote, \"For something to be beautiful, it doesn\u2019t have to be pretty,\u201d and opting to envision Edna's outfits \"more as abstract sculpture\" as opposed to forms of clothing.<ref name=\":44\" /> In order to design costumes for a fictional character who also happens to be a designer in her own film, Imagire drew upon lessons she had learned while attending [[art school]], describing Edna's style as \"very to the point and very specific\" while imagining what the character might be thinking while designing her clothes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insidethemagic.net/2018/05/interview-a-very-simple-and-graphic-idea-designing-the-costumes-for-disney-pixars-incredibles-2/|title=A Very Simple and Graphic Idea \u2013 Designing the Costumes for Pixar\u2019s \"Incredibles 2\" (Interview)|last=Celestino|first=Mike|date=May 1, 2018|website=Inside the Magic|access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref> Meanwhile, character artist Deanna Marsigliese's first assignment was to create an entire line of clothing designed by Edna,<ref name=\":46\">{{Cite web|url=https://d23.com/how-to-costume-a-super-in-incredibles-2/|title=How to Costume a Super in Incredibles 2|last=Potter|first=Courtney|date=June 18, 2018|website=D23|access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref> for which she was tasked with \"thinking like Edna\".<ref name=\":45\">{{Cite web|url=https://style.disney.com/news/2018/05/31/incredibles-2-costumes/|title=An Inside Look at the Costumes for Incredibles 2|last=Uribe|first=Mariana|date=May 31, 2018|website=Disney Style|access-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref> Although ultimately the completed clothing line does not appear in the final film, Marsigliese considered the experience to be \" a study in (Edna's) character\" nonetheless, during which she drew inspiration from Edna's appearance and wardrobe in the first film, from her dress to the interior of her house.<ref name=\":46\" /> Although she was aware that Edna enjoys being dramatic, she acknowledge that \"fashion designers don\u2019t necessarily design things that they would wear on their person, they design for their models\", meaning, \"Their [[Aesthetics|aesthetic]] is oftentimes different.\u201d<ref name=\":45\" /> Similarly, Imagire agreed that fashion designers such as Kawakubo, Ishioka and Abe \"always looked really comfortable in contrast to what they were creating for their models\", a contrast that she wanted to incorporate into the character.<ref name=\":45\" /> Recalling that Edna dislikes models, the artist envisioned that the character would instead design her own clothing to serve as \"a vehicle to celebrate superheroes and her powers.\"<ref name=\":45\" /> Inspired by Italian fashion designer [[Elsa Schiaparelli]], Marsigliese created a \"classic, [[Mid-century modern|mid-century]] inspired silhouette\" for Edna's costumes that were also bold and dramatic as though Edna herself had designed them, then rearranging the designs to ultimately give them a more surreal, specific appearance.<ref name=\":45\" /> Dubbing the character a \"woman of the now\", Marsigliese explained that, like Schiaparelli, Edna is \"completely ahead of her time\" despite living in the 1950s; \"she used a lot of surrealist elements, a lot of fun surprises, and that was very inspiring for me.\u201d<ref name=\":46\" /> Imagire designed approximately 25 potential costumes for Edna, 15 of which she showed to Bird before the final two were decided upon: a simple indigo dress and black-and-red kimono.<ref name=\":44\" />\n\n[[Entertainment Weekly|<nowiki/>]]\n\n==Characterization==\n\nAccording to Matthew Brunson of [[Creative Loafing]], Edna provides the majority of the film's [[comic relief]].<ref name=\":29\">{{Cite web|url=http://charlotte.creativeloafing.com/2004-11-10/film_feature2.html|title=Toon In, Toon Out|last=Brunson|first=Matt|date=November 10, 2004|website=Creative Loafing|access-date=March 3, 2018|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060512232812/http://charlotte.creativeloafing.com/2004-11-10/film_feature2.html|archivedate=May 12, 2006}}</ref> Hischak believes that Edna offers \"a whole new viewpoint to the world of superheroes\", in addition to demonstrating the film's \"oddball silliness\".<ref name=\":3\" /> ''[[Vogue Italia]]'' published a biography of Edna, in which author Valentina Fabbri described her as a character who \"knows she\u2019s the best and she doesn\u2019t hide it, and her lack of modesty is equalled only by her intuition\", with whom it is virtually impossible to have a conversation because \"she tends to dominate.\"<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.vogue.it/en/news/encyclo/mania/m/edna-mode|title=Edna Mode|last=Fabbri|first=Valentina|date=|website=[[Vogue Italia]]|pages=1\u20133|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218090311/http://www.vogue.it/en/news/encyclo/mania/m/edna-mode|archivedate=February 18, 2018|access-date=February 17, 2018|quote=The character immediately captured the imagination of the public, which fell in love with her irreverence and friendly sulkiness.}}</ref> Due to her combination of genius-level intellect and \"craziness,\" Fabbri identified Edna as \"a fun, bubbly caricature of the magicians of fashion\" by \"embod[ying] their talent and charisma, their vices and virtues.\"<ref name=\":8\" /> [[Screen Rant]]'s Victoria Robertson observed that the character \"has a lot of personality packed into a small exterior, taking stereotypical traits often attributed to designers and making them her own\", firstly remaining proud of her own work at all times.<ref name=\":27\" /> Oliver Lyttelton of [[IndieWire]] identified Edna as quite possibly the film's most intelligent character.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2015/11/the-30-best-voice-performances-in-pixar-movies-102929/|title=The 30 Best Voice Performances In Pixar Movies|last=Lyttelton|first=Oliver|date=November 24, 2015|website=IndieWire|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219150549/http://www.indiewire.com/2015/11/the-30-best-voice-performances-in-pixar-movies-102929/|archivedate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> Edna's criticisms of fashion can come off as unpleasant at times, but are exaggerated to the point of which audiences find them to be comical.<ref name=\":9\" /> Edna prefers to always think about the future, finding dwelling on the past to be distracting from the present, as demonstrated by her line \"I never look back, dahling, it distracts from the now\",<ref name=\":28\">{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/tournament-of-pixar-round-3-woody-vs-edna-mode|title=Tournament of Pixar, Round 3: Woody vs. Edna Mode|last=K|first=E|date=June 17, 2015|website=National Post|access-date=February 22, 2018}}</ref> and thus has proven capable of determining the needs of her superhero clientele before they have the opportunity to finalize their ideas themselves.<ref name=\":8\" /> Her personality has been described by ''[[GamesRadar+]]''<nowiki/>'s Joshua Winning as \"brassy\" and \"no-nonsense\".<ref name=\":16\" /> Q13 Fox described Edna as \"a gifted designer, an assertive life coach and a witty talker,\"<ref name=\":24\" /> using her mind and intelligence as a means of solving everyday issues.<ref name=\":47\" /> [[BuddyTV]] believes that the character's \"bold and eccentric attitude\" is rivaled only by her considerable talent.<ref name=\":31\" /> According to Kevin Carr of [[Film School Rejects]], Edna \"doesn\u2019t take crap from anyone\" yet \"she does so with poise and pride.\"<ref name=\":39\" /> The ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]''<nowiki/>'s Carla Meyer argues that Edna is \"more a caricature than a character.\"<ref name=\":43\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Just-another-nuclear-family-with-super-powers-2676516.php|title=Just another nuclear family -- with super powers|last=Meyer|first=Carla|date=November 5, 2004|website=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=June 8, 2018}}</ref>\n<nowiki/>[[File:Linda Hunt.jpg|left|thumb|277x277px|Actress [[Linda Hunt]], one of the celebrities to whom Edna's appearance has constantly been compared and often believed to have been based on.]]Scott Tobias of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called Edna \"a reminder that the superhero suit needs to the perfect synthesis of form and function\", without which \"greatness as both a crimefighter and an icon is impossible.\"<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/lists/25-best-pixar-movie-characters-20160615/buzz-lightyear-toy-story-movies-1995-2010-20160615|title=25 Best Pixar Movie Characters|last=Adams|first=Sam|last2=Bramesco|first2=Charles|date=June 15, 2016|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=February 18, 2018|last3=Grierson|first3=Tim|last4=Tobias|first4=Scott|last5=Wilkinson|first5=Alissa|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218150531/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/lists/25-best-pixar-movie-characters-20160615/buzz-lightyear-toy-story-movies-1995-2010-20160615|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> According to Thomas S. Hischak, author of ''100 Greatest American and British Animated Films'', Edna is just as concerned with the appearance of the costumes she designs as she is about their use and practicality,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=YtJKDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA154&lpg=PA154&dq=edna+mode+lily+tomlin&source=bl&ots=PWWci9UG-6&sig=ZYj1Nl_qrfN0i5v2ZhU2LE5YPNk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiA0LXjtqzZAhVHRK0KHc2uCHc4ChDoAQgqMAE#v=onepage&q=edna%20mode%20lily%20tomlin&f=false|title=100 Greatest American and British Animated Films|last=Hischak|first=Thomas S.|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2018|isbn=9781538105696|location=United States|pages=154|via=Google Books|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217141932/https://books.google.ca/books?id=YtJKDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA154&lpg=PA154&dq=edna+mode+lily+tomlin&source=bl&ots=PWWci9UG-6&sig=ZYj1Nl_qrfN0i5v2ZhU2LE5YPNk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiA0LXjtqzZAhVHRK0KHc2uCHc4ChDoAQgqMAE#v=onepage&q=edna%20mode%20lily%20tomlin&f=false|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref> proving capable of designing outfits that can stretch, change their shape and resist oncoming attacks such as missiles and fires.<ref name=\":8\" /> The character proves capable of designing a costume for Violet that is capable of becoming invisible whenever its wearer does.<ref name=\":43\" /> She absolutely refuses to incorporate capes into her new designs due to the accessory having a history of contributing to the deaths of superheroes in the past, among them Dynaguy, Thunderhead, Stratogale, Meta-Man and Splashdown,<ref name=\":18\" /> presenting them as a \"montage of superhero couture [[wikt:Faux pas|faux-pas]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/the-incredibles|title=The Incredibles|last=B|first=N|website=Time Out|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222225638/https://www.timeout.com/london/film/the-incredibles|archivedate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> Ultimately, her knowledge of the dangers of capes results in the death of the film's villain [[Syndrome (character)|Syndrome]].<ref name=\":22\" /> In terms of her own appearance, Edna is costumed in \"[[Futuristic fashion|futuristic]] black\" attire, wearing a black dress that boasts square lines.<ref name=\":8\" /> Estimating her height to be of approximately three feet, ''[[The Tyee]]''<nowiki/>'s Dorothy Woodend wrote that Edna is dressed in [[Issey Miyake]] pleats while being of \"indeterminate gender\".<ref name=\":26\" /> [[VPRO]] drew similarities between the character's hairstyle and personality to that of ''Vogue'' editor Anna Wintour,<ref name=\":18\" /> the resemblance to whom Tech Times' Katherine Derla identified as \"The first thing viewers are likely to remember upon seeing\" the character.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.techtimes.com/articles/165288/20160616/animated-characters-done-right-top-10-pixar-movie-characters.htm|title=Animated Characters Done Right: Top 10 Pixar Movie Characters|last=Derla|first=Katherine|date=June 16, 2016|website=Tech Times|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219090138/http://www.techtimes.com/articles/165288/20160616/animated-characters-done-right-top-10-pixar-movie-characters.htm|archivedate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> According to ''STATUS'' magazine, Edna is often mistaken for the magazine editor largely due to her \"snappy sass and iconic bob\".<ref>{{cite web|title=10 Movie Characters Based on Fashion Icons|url=http://statusmagonline.com/10-movie-characters-based-on-fashion-icons/|website=STATUS Magazine|accessdate=March 14, 2018|date=September 5, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315211418/http://statusmagonline.com/10-movie-characters-based-on-fashion-icons/|archivedate=March 15, 2018}}</ref> Film's Angie Han joked that Edna's \"no-nonsense demeanor\" would leave Wintour \"quaking in her Chanel boots.\"<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/best-pixar-female-characters/2/|title=Pixar\u2019s 15 Best Female Characters|last=Han|first=Angie|date=June 23, 2015|website=/Film|access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> When asked about the alleged similarities between her and the character, Wintour revealed that she has yet to see the film.<ref name=\":36\" /> Derla also wrote that Edna is capable of \"run[ing] the world\" but opts to operate from behind the scenes instead.<ref name=\":23\" /> The term \"diminutive\" is often used to describe the character's height.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/12-best-supporting-pixar-characters/|title=12 Best Supporting Pixar Characters|last=Winning|first=Joshua|date=February 18, 2010|website=GamesRadar+|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218210424/https://www.gamesradar.com/12-best-supporting-pixar-characters/|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nConsidering herself to be \"too talented\" to design clothes for normal humans,<ref name=\":8\" /> Edna resents having been forced to resort to designing clothes for [[supermodel]]s during the 15-year-long absence of superheroes,<ref name=\":4\" /> dismissing them as \"Spoiled, stupid little stick figures with poofy lips who think only about themselves\",<ref name=\":24\" /> an opinion she formed after being forced to work with such individuals in Milan and Paris.<ref name=\":31\">{{cite web|url=http://www.buddytv.com/info/edna-mode-info.aspx|title=Edna Mode|last=|first=|date=|website=[[BuddyTV]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309054425/http://www.buddytv.com/info/edna-mode-info.aspx|archive-date=March 9, 2018|accessdate=March 8, 2018|quote=Edna Marie \u2018E\u2019 Mode is a fictional fashion designer, and supporting character from the Disney and Pixar motion picture The Incredibles.}}</ref><ref name=\":35\" /> Edna believes that designing clothes for superheroes is similar to designing for gods, and thus considers herself to be far superior to other fashion designers.<ref name=\":31\" /> Despite her considerable success as one of the world's top fashion designers internationally,<ref name=\":38\" /> Edna longs to return to working with superheroes so that she can challenge her designs by \"fus[ing] the latest technology with her impeccable fashion sense\" to the public's amusement, who continue to adore both her and her creations,<ref name=\":35\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pixar.com/feature-films/the-incredibles/#the-incredibles-1|title=The Incredibles|website=Pixar Animation Studios|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315133306/https://www.pixar.com/feature-films/the-incredibles/#the-incredibles-1|archive-date=March 15, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> insisting that there is nothing \"super\" about supermodels.<ref name=\":38\" /> Despite designing elaborate costumes for a living, Edna prefers a more simple aesthetic for herself, generally avoiding nail polish and accessories.<ref name=\":47\" /> [[Racked.com|Racked]]'s Carlye Wisel observed that although the sequel \"may have deep roots in midcentury-modern design ... Edna remains true to her forward-looking style, wearing a red silk kimono as well as an asymmetrical sheath that feels like yet another nod to Kawakubo\u2019s work.\"<ref name=\":47\" /> In addition to being a talented fashion designer, Edna has also demonstrated proficiency in [[psychology]]. In addition to designing their clothes, she offers advice to her clients whenever she feels that they require it,<ref name=\":8\" /> demonstrating a \"zero-tolerance policy for emotional weakness\" which, according to ''[[The Dissolve]]'''s Charles Bramesco, represents Bird's \"lament[ing] regular folks\u2019 tendency to impede awesome people from being awesome.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bramesco|first1=Charles|title=The slippery politics of The Incredibles and other superheroes|url=https://thedissolve.com/features/movie-of-the-week/812-the-slippery-politics-of-the-incredibles-and-other/|website=The Dissolve|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=November 6, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224112902/https://thedissolve.com/features/movie-of-the-week/812-the-slippery-politics-of-the-incredibles-and-other/|archivedate=February 24, 2018}}</ref> Edna is known for her tendency to refer to her cohorts as \"dahling\",<ref name=\":17\" /><ref name=\":19\" /> while her colleagues affectionately refer to her as \"E\".<ref name=\":38\" /> In addition to citing her resemblance to Wintour, journalist [[Hadley Freeman]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' believes that Edna's use of fashion in the film represents \"The highest pinnacle of human achievement. Without them the world would come to an end.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/jan/31/fashion.lifeandhealth|title=Which couturiers make the cut on screen?|last=Freeman|first=Hadley|date=January 31, 2008|website=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315070526/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/jan/31/fashion.lifeandhealth|archive-date=March 15, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\nEdna first appears in ''The ednas a bam Incredibles'' as a fashion designer to superheroes and close friend of the titular characters.<ref name=\":8\" /> During the \u201cgolden age of superheroes\",<ref name=\":40\" /> Edna is one of a few elite guests who attend the private wedding ceremony of Bob and Helen Parr, then better-known to the public as the superheroes Mr. Incredible and Elastigirl. After all superheroes have been [[outlaw]]ed and forced to retire following a series of lawsuits,<ref name=\":16\" /> forcing Edna to retire from superhero work due to government restrictions,<ref name=\":40\" /> Edna does not appear again until approximately midway through film when she is unexpectedly visited by Bob who has resumed superhero work undercover, a secret he keeps from his family. Bob initially asks Edna to simply repair his original super suit, but she ultimately convinces him to allow her to design an entirely new outfit on the condition that capes not be incorporated whatsoever due to safety concerns, ultimately ending her 15 years-long retirement from superhero work.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=https://d23.com/23-favorite-pixar-supporting-characters/|title=23 Favorite Pixar Supporting Characters|last=|first=|date=|website=D23.com|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-access=registration }}</ref> Helen soon discovers that Bob's original super suit had received a [[Patchwork|patch job]], determining that the only person capable of repairing a super suit would be Edna and growing more suspicious of Bob's actions.<ref name=\":30\" /> Later in the film, Helen visits Edna in the hopes of finding out more information about Bob's whereabouts, discovering that she had taken the liberty of designing a complete matching set of super suits for his family.<ref name=\":43\" /> Although their reunion is brief, Edna provides an initially distraught Helen with the encouragement she needs to resume her identity as Elastigirl in order to save her husband (and their marriage), in addition to introducing the character to the homing device she had implanted in her husband's suit, intentionally revealing his exact location to her.<ref name=\":43\" />\n\nEdna appears in the film's sequel, ''[[Incredibles 2]]'' (2018). When Helen is recruited by a pair of entrepreneurs to change the public's perception of superheroes and thus returns to work to fight crime as Elastigirl,<ref name=\":47\" /> Edna is upset to learn that Elastigirl's costume has been designed by a rival designer. Bob soon becomes overwhelmed by Jack-Jack's emerging superpowers, and recruits Edna for assistance with controlling him. Although Edna is initially reluctant to [[Babysitting|babysit]] Jack-Jack,<ref name=\":47\" /> she soon develops a strong liking for the baby and she is willing to babysit him overnight free of charge; during this time, she upgrades his suit with sensors and a remote control so that the family can monitor his powers and rein them in as needed.<ref name=\":44\" /> She gives the enhanced suit to Bob in a custom shopping bag, which bears a logo for her services that incorporates her signature eyeglasses into its lettering.<ref name=\":47\" /> Edna also appears in [[Disney on Ice]]'s adaptation of the film: ''The Incredibles in a Magic Kingdom Adventure''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/lifestyles/disney-on-ice-unmasks-incredibles-ice-show/article_8986404c-616d-5a6f-9e93-b81ec67755f0.html|title=Disney on Ice unmasks 'Incredibles' ice show|last=Woulfe|first=Molly|date=January 24, 2006|website=The Times of Northwest Indiana|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313092504/http://www.nwitimes.com/lifestyles/disney-on-ice-unmasks-incredibles-ice-show/article_8986404c-616d-5a6f-9e93-b81ec67755f0.html|archive-date=March 13, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=March 12, 2018}}</ref> The time that Edna spends looking after Jack-Jack is the focus of the animated short ''Auntie Edna''.\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe public was immediately captivated by Edna upon her debut, becoming particularly enamored with the character's combination of irreverence and sulkiness.<ref name=\":8\" /> Edna instantly established herself as a fan favorite when the film was released in 2004,<ref name=\":44\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hypable.com/incredibles-2-superheroes-ranked-from-worst-to-best/|title=\u2018Incredibles 2\u2019 superheroes ranked from worst to best|last=Locke|first=Aaron|date=June 19, 2018|website=Hypable|access-date=June 20, 2018}}</ref> which Racked's Carlye Wisel has attributed to the character's combination of wit and style.<ref name=\":47\" /> Several critics have referred to Edna as a [[Scene stealer|scene-stealing]] character;<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bullz-eye.com/mguide/reviews_2004/the_incredibles.htm|title=The Incredibles|last=Medsker|first=David|date=2004|website=Bullz-Eye.com|access-date=February 20, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223110906/http://www.bullz-eye.com/mguide/reviews_2004/the_incredibles.htm|archivedate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> ''Fashion'' magazine's Erin Dunlop crowned Edna \"the undisputed scene-stealer of\" the film.<ref name=\":34\" /> Dubbing her \"One of the great scene-stealing characters in ''The Incredibles''\", [[HowStuffWorks]] contributor Vicki Arkoff called Edna \"deliciously [[Deadpan humor|deadpan]]\".<ref name=\":6\" /> Ken Hanke, writing for the ''[[Mountain Xpress]]'', considers Edna to be among the film's gags and characters who \"are delightful and very funny\", particularly highlighting the character's anti-cape monologue while deeming her \"worth the price of admission\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mountainx.com/movies/reviews/incredibles-php/|title=The Incredibles|last=Hanke|first=Ken|date=November 10, 2004|website=Mountain Xpress|access-date=March 3, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180302225411/https://mountainx.com/movies/reviews/incredibles-php/|archivedate=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Film critic [[Peter Bradshaw]], contributing to ''[[The Irish Times]]'', described Edna as \"a joy with her wonderful and appropriate maxim: 'I never look back, darling. It distracts from the now.'\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/is-toy-story-better-than-up-all-19-pixar-films-ranked-1.3406416|title=Is \u2018Toy Story\u2019 better than \u2018Up\u2019? All 19 Pixar films ranked|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|date=February 27, 2018|website=The Irish Times|access-date=April 9, 2018}}</ref> Dorothy Woodend, writing for ''The Tyee'', praised Edna as \"a more interesting creature than all the Incredibles put together.\" Describing her as \"a personage I'd like to see more of\", Woodend continued that the character \"steals the show, and does fabulous things with it, darling.\"<ref name=\":26\">{{Cite web|url=https://thetyee.ca/Entertainment/2004/11/19/%27Incredibles%27RiteofPassage/|title=\u2018Incredibles\u2019 Rite of Passage|last=Woodend|first=Dorothy|date=November 19, 2004|website=The Tyee|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223051216/https://thetyee.ca/Entertainment/2004/11/19/%27Incredibles%27RiteofPassage/|archivedate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> Referred to as one of the film's \"high point[s]\", Kevin Lally of ''[[Film Journal International]]'' described the character's anti-cape montage as \"pricelessly funny\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.filmjournal.com/node/15186|title=The Incredibles|last=Lally|first=Kevin|date=November 5, 2004|website=Film Journal International|access-date=February 23, 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224053047/http://www.filmjournal.com/node/15186|archivedate=February 24, 2018}}</ref> a sentiment with which Matt Brunson of Creative Loafing agreed.<ref name=\":29\" /> The ''[[National Post]]'' described Edna as \"exactly the kind of person you want at your dinner party\".<ref name=\":28\" /> Notable Biographies identified Edna as \"one of the audience's favorite characters\".<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2005-A-Fi/Bird-Brad.html|title=Brad Bird Biography|website=Notable Biographies|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218090740/http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2005-A-Fi/Bird-Brad.html|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBird has also garnered critical acclaim for his performance. Nell Minow of [[Common Sense Media]] wrote that Bird \"plays the funniest character in the film\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commonsensemedia.org/movie-reviews/the-incredibles|title=The Incredibles|last=Minnow|first=Nell|website=Common Sense Media|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225133931/https://www.commonsensemedia.org/movie-reviews/the-incredibles|archivedate=December 25, 2017}}</ref> while [[AllMovie]]'s Perry Seibert described his performance as \"screamingly funny\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-incredibles-v287450/review|title=The Incredibles (2004)|last=Seibert|first=Perry|date=2004|website=AllMovie|access-date=February 23, 2004|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625171828/http://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-incredibles-v287450/review|archivedate=June 25, 2012}}</ref> Pete Vonder Haar of ''[[Film Threat]]'' wrote that Bird contributes \"the best work\" to the film as Edna in terms of dialogue and vocal performance, calling her rant about the \"idiocy\" of capes \"priceless.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.filmthreat.com/reviews/6624/|title=The Incredibles|last=Haar|first=Pete Vonder|date=November 6, 2004|website=Film Threat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021201814/http://www.filmthreat.com/reviews/6624/|archive-date=October 21, 2012|access-date=February 22, 2018}}</ref> Scott Chitwood, writing for [[ComingSoon.net]], agreed that Bird is \" absolutely hilarious as Edna\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chitwood|first1=Scott|title=The Incredibles|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/reviews/7031-the-incredibles|website=ComingSoon.net|accessdate=March 5, 2018|date=November 3, 2004|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306082955/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/reviews/7031-the-incredibles|archivedate=March 6, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Empire magazine|Empire]]''<nowiki/>'s Colin Kennedy dubbed Bird's voice work \"an unmistakable highlight\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/incredibles/review/|title=The Incredibles Review|last=Kennedy|first=Colin|date=January 1, 2011|website=Empire|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223052835/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/incredibles/review/|archivedate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> [[Bbc.co.uk|BBC]]'s Stella Papamichael agreed that the director \"steals the show\" as Edna.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Papamichael|first1=Stella|title=The Incredibles (2004)|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2004/11/09/the_incredibles_2004_review.shtml|website=BBC|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=November 25, 2004|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827071510/http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2004/11/09/the_incredibles_2004_review.shtml|archivedate=August 27, 2012}}</ref> Carla Meyer, writing for the ''San Francisco Chronicle'', wrote that Bird's performance as Edna \"shows his versatility\".<ref name=\":43\" /> In 2005, Bird won an [[Annie Award]] for [[Annie Award for Voice Acting in a Feature Production|Voice Acting in a Feature Production]] at the 32nd Annie Awards for his performance as Edna,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2005/digital/awards/incredibles-tops-annies-1117917174/|title=\u2018Incredibles\u2019 tops Annies|last=Walton|first=Alice M.|date=January 30, 2005|website=Variety|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218150525/http://variety.com/2005/digital/awards/incredibles-tops-annies-1117917174/|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> in addition to being rewarded for writing and directing the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2005/01/31/incredibles-sweeps-annie-awards.html|title='The Incredibles' Sweeps Annie Awards|date=January 31, 2005|website=Fox News|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218210206/http://www.foxnews.com/story/2005/01/31/incredibles-sweeps-annie-awards.html|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Bird was rewarded over actor [[Samuel L. Jackson]], who had been nominated in the same category for his role as [[Frozone]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/49127/incredibles-super-at-toon-awards|title=\"Incredibles\" Super at 'Toon Awards|last=Grossberg|first=Josh|date=January 31, 2005|website=E!|access-date=February 17, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218090533/http://www.eonline.com/news/49127/incredibles-super-at-toon-awards|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Wisel appreciated Edna's cameo in the sequel, describing it as \"perfect in its restraint.\"<ref name=\":47\" />\n\n[[Vulture.com]] ranked Bird's role as Edna the fourth greatest performance in an animated film, calling it \"a scene- and movie-stealing performance\".<ref name=\":37\" /> Similarly, ''Entertainment Weekly'' placed Edna fourth on their ranking of \"The 10 greatest Pixar voice performances\", with author Marc Snetiker calling it \"an all-too-short but memorably delicious appearance\" in which Bird \"left an indelible mark on his own universe\".<ref name=\":41\">{{Cite web|url=http://ew.com/movies/pixar-greatest-voice-performances/#4-brad-bird-as-edna-mode|title=The 10 greatest Pixar voice performances|last=Snetiker|first=Marc|date=November 24, 2017|website=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=May 29, 2018}}</ref> Snetiker called the character \"overwhelmingly funny thanks to Bird\u2019s unrestrained efforts on even the simplest lines.\"<ref name=\":41\" /> [[IndieWire]] ranked Bird's performance as Edna the 14th \"30 Best Voice Performances In Pixar Movies\".<ref name=\":22\" /> Kiko Martinez of the ''[[San Antonio Current]]'' found Bird's performance to be worthy of an Academy Award, ranking him among \"15 Actors Who Should\u2019ve Won an Oscar for Their Voice Work\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacurrent.com/ArtSlut/archives/2016/06/13/15-actors-who-shouldve-won-an-oscar-for-their-voice-work?showFullText=true|title=15 Actors Who Should\u2019ve Won an Oscar for Their Voice Work|last=Martinez|first=Kiko|date=June 13, 2016|website=San Antonio Current|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218091234/https://www.sacurrent.com/ArtSlut/archives/2016/06/13/15-actors-who-shouldve-won-an-oscar-for-their-voice-work?showFullText=true|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Bird revealed that fans tend to be more impressed by the fact that he provides Edna's voice than his success as a director and writer,<ref name=\":49\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/programs/triplej-breakfast/brad-bird-incredibles-two/9859680|title=Incredibles director Brad Bird on the much-anticipated sequel|last=|first=|date=June 12, 2018|website=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|access-date=August 6, 2018}}</ref> explaining, \"If I say a line in Edna\u2019s voice, that\u2019s far more delightful than the fact that I spent four years wrestling something into being.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/director-brad-bird-talks-about-mission-impossible-ghos-1798230889|title=Director Brad Bird talks about Mission: Impossible\u2014Ghost Protocol and live-action versus animation|last=Robinson|first=Tasha|date=April 18, 2012|website=The A. V. Club|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202639/https://film.avclub.com/director-brad-bird-talks-about-mission-impossible-ghos-1798230889|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Impact and legacy==\nEdna's popularity among audiences established her as the film's [[breakout character]].<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/the-incredibles/news/a849700/the-incredibles-2-new-poster-edna-mode-new-york-fashion-week/|title=New The Incredibles 2 poster brings Edna Mode to New York Fashion Week|last=James|first=Sarah|date=February 11, 2018|website=[[Digital Spy]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218213205/http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/the-incredibles/news/a849700/the-incredibles-2-new-poster-edna-mode-new-york-fashion-week/|archivedate=February 18, 2018|access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/99434/edna-mode-back-first-trailer-incredibles-2-watch/|title=Edna Mode is back in the brand new trailer for The Incredibles 2 \u2013 watch here!|last=Damshenas|first=Sam|date=February 15, 2018|website=[[Gay Times]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303053219/http://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/99434/edna-mode-back-first-trailer-incredibles-2-watch/|archivedate=March 3, 2018|access-date=February 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wsbuzz.com/tv-movies/new-incredibles-2-poster-features-edna-mode-new-york-fashion-week/|title=New The Incredibles 2 Poster Features Edna Mode At New York Fashion Week|last=|first=|date=February 11, 2018|website=WSBuzz.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303052031/http://wsbuzz.com/tv-movies/new-incredibles-2-poster-features-edna-mode-new-york-fashion-week/|archivedate=March 3, 2018|access-date=February 24, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/incredibles-2-edna-mode-video-d23/|title=Watch The Incredibles\u2019 D23 Edna Mode Retrospective Video|last=Welch|first=Alex|date=July 14, 2017|website=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920070529/http://screenrant.com/incredibles-2-edna-mode-video-d23/|archive-date=September 20, 2017|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> Screen Rant's Alex Welch attributes this designation to both her [[Comic timing|comedic rapport]] with the titular family and passion for superhero costumes.<ref name=\":32\" /> Gregory E. Miller of the ''[[New York Post]]'' cited Edna's impact since ''The Incredibles'' as significant despite her relatively brief appearance,<ref name=\":44\" /> while [[HelloGiggles]] writer Sydney Bucksbaum crowned her the film's \"real hero\".<ref name=\":48\">{{Cite web|url=https://hellogiggles.com/news/edna-mode-incredibes-poster/|title=The latest \"Incredibles 2\" poster features the real star of the movie \u2014 Edna Mode|last=Bucksbaum|first=Sydney|date=February 12, 2018|website=[[HelloGiggles]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=June 20, 2018}}</ref> ''Vogue Italia'' contributor Valentina Fabbri wrote that Edna ended the trope of \"superheroes [dressed] in homemade outfits\".<ref name=\":8\" /> According to Fabbri, Edna is one of Pixar's most beloved characters,<ref name=\":8\" /> while [[Hollywood.com]]'s Julia Emmanuele dubbed her \"one of the most memorable Pixar characters of all time\" who has ultimately \"become the film\u2019s enduring legacy\", despite her supporting role.<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hollywood.com/movies/superheroes-hq-why-the-incredibles-is-the-best-superhero-movie-of-all-time-60227157/|title=Why \u2018The Incredibles\u2019 Is the Best Superhero Movie of All Time|last=Emmanuele|first=Julia|date=April 4, 2014|website=[[Hollywood.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> [[Uproxx]] contributor Donna Dickens wrote that the character \"went down in [[Pop culture icon|pop culture history]]\" from the moment she uttered \"No capes!\u201d<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/hitfix/incredibles-edna-mode-documentary/|title=Titans Of Fashion Pay Tribute To Edna Mode Of \u2018The Incredibles\u2019|last=Dickens|first=Donna|date=July 14, 2017|website=[[Uproxx]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218024159/http://uproxx.com/hitfix/incredibles-edna-mode-documentary/|archivedate=February 18, 2018|access-date=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMedia publications consistently rank Edna among Pixar's greatest characters.<ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":17\" /><ref name=\":39\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://20some.com/a-countdown-of-the-5-best-pixar-characters-of-all-time/|title=Can We All Agree That These Are the 5 Best Pixar Characters of All Time?|last=Sambeck|first=Becca Van|date=July 14, 2015|website=20Some|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219090411/http://20some.com/a-countdown-of-the-5-best-pixar-characters-of-all-time/|archivedate=February 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/galleries/the-all-time-best-pixar-characters/27/|title=The 27 All-Time Best Pixar Characters|website=TV Guide|access-date=May 4, 2018}}</ref> In their article \"Top 10 Pixar Movie Characters\", ''Tech Times'' ranked Edna seventh.<ref name=\":23\" /> [[IGN]] ranked Edna eighth in their countdown of the \"Top 10 Pixar Characters\", calling her \"a pint-sized fashionista\" with \"a flair that only a superhero could truly appreciate.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/05/21/top-10-pixar-characters |title=Top 10 Pixar Characters |date=May 21, 2009 |website=IGN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326164120/http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/05/21/top-10-pixar-characters |archive-date=March 26, 2018 |url-status=live |access-date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' placed her ninth on the website's list of the \"25 Best Pixar Movie Characters\", ranking her ahead of Mr. Incredible (24th), Violet Parr (20th) and Elastigirl (14th).<ref name=\":15\" /> Contributor Scott Tobias wrote that the character \"stops the action cold just to have a sequence about appropriate action-wear for the specially abled, culminating in a brilliant screed on the impracticality of capes.\"<ref name=\":15\" /> Including Edna among the studio's 20 best characters, Victoria Robertson of Screen Rant cited her as \"proof of how important even the most minor characters in a film can be.\"<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/best-pixar-characters/|title=20 Best Characters From Pixar Movies|last=Robertson|first=Victoria|date=November 20, 2013|website=Screen Rant|access-date=February 20, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220212249/https://screenrant.com/best-pixar-characters/|archivedate=February 20, 2018}}</ref> ''GamesRadar+'' included Edna among Pixar's \"50 Greatest Pixar Characters Of All Time\", with author George Wales crowning her \"One of Pixar's finest comic creations\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/50-greatest-pixar-characters-of-all-time/4/#article-body|title=50 Greatest Pixar Characters Of All Time|last=Wales|first=George|date=August 17, 2012|website=GamesRadar+|access-date=February 23, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223232224/https://www.gamesradar.com/50-greatest-pixar-characters-of-all-time/4/#article-body|archivedate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> Additionally, the same publication ranked Edna among Pixar's 12 greatest supporting characters.<ref name=\":16\" /> [[D23 (Disney)|D23.com]] recognized Edna as one of Pixar's \"23 Favorite ... Supporting Characters\", deeming her \"An icon in her own right\".<ref name=\":20\" /> /Film ranked Edna Pixar's sixth best female character, crowning her \"the wisest character in the entire Incredibles universe\" due to her anti-cape stance, which author Angie Han has described as the film's \"most valuable piece of advice\".<ref name=\":25\" /> [[The Odyssey Online]] published an article discussing \"Why Edna Mode Is The Disney Heroine We Never Knew We Needed\", in which author Erin Farmer dubbed her \"the real heroine of the Disney Franchise\" while comparing her motivational speeches to those of [[Mahatma Gandhi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theodysseyonline.com/why-edna-mode-is-the-disney-heroine-we-never-knew-we-needed|title=Why Edna Mode Is The Disney Heroine We Never Knew We Needed|last=Farmer|first=Erin|date=February 13, 2017|website=The Odyssey Online|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223110917/https://www.theodysseyonline.com/why-edna-mode-is-the-disney-heroine-we-never-knew-we-needed|archivedate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> ''GamesRadar+'' ranked Edna's introductory scene the 12th best moment in a Pixar film, deeming her \"the perfect embodiment of the film's tongue-in-cheek approach to realism\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/50-greatest-pixar-moments/4/#article-body|title=50 greatest Pixar moments|last=Kinnear|first=Simon|date=November 19, 2015|website=GamesRadar+|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223050756/https://www.gamesradar.com/50-greatest-pixar-moments/4/#article-body|archivedate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> ''Entertainment Weekly'' ranked Edna's anti-capes speech the 12th best Pixar moment.<ref name=\":21\" /> In 2015, [[E!]] ranked Edna 10th on their list of \"11 Forgotten Disney Characters Who Should Totally Be Your Favorites\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/ca/news/635000/11-forgotten-disney-characters-who-should-totally-be-your-favorites|title=11 Forgotten Disney Characters Who Should Totally Be Your Favorites|last=Hays|first=Julia|date=March 12, 2015|website=E!|access-date=February 24, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303050909/http://www.eonline.com/ca/news/635000/11-forgotten-disney-characters-who-should-totally-be-your-favorites|archivedate=March 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' ranked the character the hundredth greatest film character of all-time.<ref name=\":33\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/100-greatest-movie-characters/|title=The 100 Greatest Movie Characters|last=|first=|date=June 29, 2005|website=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151213002250/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/100-greatest-movie-characters/|archive-date=December 13, 2015|access-date=March 14, 2015}}</ref> In 2013, Screen Rant crowned Edna \"The world\u2019s greatest fashion designer\".<ref name=\":32\" /> ''Fashion'' ranked Edna among the magazine's \"10 coolest fashion industry pros\".<ref name=\":34\" /> In their \"critical assessment of 7 fictional fashion designers\", Mary Sollosi of ''Entertainment Weekly'' wrote that she is \"consistently impressed by Ms. Mode\u2019s truly groundbreaking textile work\" despite feeling that she tends to limit herself to familiar silhouettes, joking, \"we are perplexed by her stubborn refusal to incorporate new design features \u2014 most notably capes.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/09/12/fictional-fashion-designers/|title=A critical assessment of 7 fictional fashion designers|last=Sollosi|first=Mary|date=September 12, 2017|website=Entertainment Weekly|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225235836/http://ew.com/movies/2017/09/12/fictional-fashion-designers/|archive-date=December 25, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> In June 2018, Carlye Wisel of [[Racked.com|Racked]] crowned Edna \"Film\u2019s greatest fashion character\", deeming her \"the best fictional fashion personality ever to exist, animated or not\". She prefers her over ''[[The Devil Wears Prada (film)|The Devil Wears Prada]]''<nowiki/>'s Miranda Priestly ([[Meryl Streep]]), insisting that Edna \"feels more grounded and true\" Miranda, a fictional magazine editor who is frequently touted the \"best-ever fashion character\".<ref name=\":47\" /> Describing her as \"effortless and memorable,\" Wisel concluded, \"at a time when a label like Gucci is exploding its brand with misspellings and magpie tendencies to draw attention, she remains classic. Edna is never anything but fully herself \u2014 all hair, accent, and attitude.\"<ref name=\":47\" />\n\nEdna's [[catchphrase]] against using capes in superhero costumes has become one of the most popular phrases among superhero fans.<ref name=\":42\" /> Edna has become so popular that fans have begun to demand a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] film revolving around the character.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/film-tv/g12151384/best-superhero-movies-list/?slide=5|title=The 30 Best Superhero Movies of All Time|last=Janes|first=DeAnna|date=March 30, 2018|website=Harper's Bazaar|access-date=May 31, 2018|quote=It\u2019s such a good time, fans are demanding a spin-off starring scene-stealing designer Edna Mode}}</ref> Screen Rant ranked Edna the third Pixar heroine who deserves her own film, with author Wednesday Lee Friday writing, \"There are so many things Pixar could do with Edna, she might be worthy of a trilogy.\"<ref name=\":40\" /> At the [[77th Academy Awards]] in 2005, Edna presented the [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design]] alongside actor [[Pierce Brosnan]].<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":16\" /> In 2013, the D23 Expo hosted its first official cosplay competition, naming it \"Heroes and Villains \u00e0 la Mode\" in honor of Edna; contestants competed in five categories, with the winners being awarded miniature statuettes of the character.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mouseplanet.com/10460/D23_Expo__Heroes_and_Villains_a_la_Mode_Costume_Contest|title=D23 Expo - Heroes and Villains a la Mode Costume Contest|last=Wien|first=Stephanie|date=August 26, 2013|website=MousePlanet|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> To promote the film's sequel in which Edna appeared,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2017/11/18/incredibles-2-watch-first-trailer/|title=The Incredibles 2: Oh Baby! - watch Disney-Pixar's first trailer|date=November 18, 2017|website=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218210309/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2017/11/18/incredibles-2-watch-first-trailer/|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Disney released a [[mockumentary]]-style teaser trailer that features various celebrities involved in the fashion industry paying tribute to Edna and describing ways in which the character has influenced them over the years ever since she decided to venture into [[haute couture]].<ref name=\":10\" /> Disney revealed the trailer at the [[D23 Expo]] in 2017.<ref name=\":10\" /> Fashion models [[Heidi Klum]], [[Kendall Jenner]] and [[Rachel Zoe]] are among the celebrities who speak about Edna's influence on the fashion industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.joe.ie/movies-tv/the-incredibles-2-info-595306|title=Loads of new details have been revealed about The Incredibles 2|last=Cashin|first=Rory|date=2017|website=JOE.ie|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218102508/https://www.joe.ie/movies-tv/the-incredibles-2-info-595306|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Impressed by their commitment to pretending Edna is real, Halle Kiefer of Vulture.com joked that the tribute features some of the participants' \"most impressive onscreen roles to date\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2017/07/the-fashion-world-pays-tribute-to-the-incredibles-edna-mode.html|title=Kendall Jenner, Andr\u00e9 Leon Talley Play Pretty Convincing Tribute to The Incredibles\u2019 Fashion Designer Edna Mode|last=Kiefer|first=Halle|date=July 14, 2017|website=Vulture.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321063032/http://www.vulture.com/2017/07/the-fashion-world-pays-tribute-to-the-incredibles-edna-mode.html|archive-date=March 21, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=March 20, 2018}}</ref> Rachel Kolb of Uproxx wrote that having Edna design new costumes for the family in ''Incredibles 2'' would be one way to ensure that the sequel is better than the original.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/10-ways-pixar-can-make-the-incredibles-2-better-than-the-original/|title=How Can Pixar Make \u2018The Incredibles 2\u2019 Even Better Than The Original? Here Are A Few Ideas.|last=Kolb|first=Rachel|date=November 5, 2014|website=Uproxx|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217192153/http://uproxx.com/movies/10-ways-pixar-can-make-the-incredibles-2-better-than-the-original/|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref> Beginning in 2018, Edna has been used heavily in ''Incredibles 2''<nowiki/>'s first [[advertising campaign]].<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newnownext.com/edna-mode-incredibles-2/02/2018/|title=Edna Mode Star Of First Ad Campaign For \"Incredibles 2\"|last=Avery|first=Dan|date=February 12, 2018|website=[[NewNowNext]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219031130/http://www.newnownext.com/edna-mode-incredibles-2/02/2018/|archivedate=February 19, 2018|access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In February 2018, the character's likeness was used heavily on several bus and subway posters within Manhattan, New York surrounding [[New York Fashion Week]].<ref name=\":13\" /> Disney-Pixar's announced on their Twitter account: \"If you thought she\u2019d miss #NYFW, you thought wrong, dahling\".<ref name=\":13\" /> The poster features a black and white closeup image of the character with only her lips colored red,<ref name=\":48\" /> accompanied by the caption \"It's been too long, dahlings.\"<ref name=\":14\" /> Bucksbaum called the poster \"stunning\".<ref name=\":48\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The Incredibles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mode, Edna}}\n[[Category:Fictional inventors]]\n[[Category:The Incredibles characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional people in fashion]]\n[[Category:Fictional women scientists]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 2004]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with dwarfism]]\n[[Category:Fictional American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Fictional American people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Fictional smokers]]\n[[Category:Animated human characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|\"The Incredibles\" character}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color              = #080410\n| series             = [[The Incredibles (franchise)|The Incredibles]]\n| name               = Edna Mode\n| image              = Edna Mode promotional image.jpg\n| first              = ''[[The Incredibles]]'' (2004)\n| last               = ''[[Incredibles 2]]'' (2018)\n| creator            = [[Brad Bird]]\n| voice              = Brad Bird\n| full_name          = Edna Mode\n| nickname           = E\n| species            = Human\n| occupation         = [[Fashion design]]er<br>[[Costume designer]]\n}}\n'''Edna \"E\" Mode'''<ref name=\":38\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=YyniCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA156&lpg=PA156&dq=Spoiled,+stupid+little+stick+figures+with+poofy+lips+who+think+only+about+themselves&source=bl&ots=dESvSHX-_1&sig=7EGgbqG1-Al1dcsSXDy_d8uiumY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiC9K_W0azZAhWD6YMKHS3oB9UQ6AEIYjAO#v=onepage&q=Spoiled%2C%20stupid%20little%20stick%20figures%20with%20poofy%20lips%20who%20think%20only%20about%20themselves&f=false|title=The Art of The Incredibles|last=Cotta Vaz|first=Mark|publisher=Chronicle Books|year=2015|isbn=9781452147574|location=United States|pages=62|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218090250/https://books.google.ca/books?id=YyniCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA156&lpg=PA156&dq=Spoiled,+stupid+little+stick+figures+with+poofy+lips+who+think+only+about+themselves&source=bl&ots=dESvSHX-_1&sig=7EGgbqG1-Al1dcsSXDy_d8uiumY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiC9K_W0azZAhWD6YMKHS3oB9UQ6AEIYjAO#v=onepage&q=Spoiled%2C%20stupid%20little%20stick%20figures%20with%20poofy%20lips%20who%20think%20only%20about%20themselves&f=false|archivedate=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":31\" /> is a fictional character in [[Pixar]]'s [[Computer animation|animated]] [[superhero film]] ''[[The Incredibles]]'' (2004) and its sequel ''[[Incredibles 2]]'' (2018). She is an eccentric fashion designer renowned for designing the costumes of several famous superheroes, having worked particularly closely with [[Bob Parr (The Incredibles)|Mr. Incredible]] and [[Elastigirl]] (Bob and Helen Parr), with whom she has maintained a strong friendship. When the couple resumes their superheroic careers after fifteen years, Edna is summoned out of retirement to aid both characters, first by equipping Mr. Incredible with a new costume and then by restoring Elastigirl's confidence in herself as a superheroine.\n\nEdna was created by screenwriter and director [[Brad Bird]] to explain how ''The Incredibles''<nowiki/>' superheroes obtain their costumes, a topic he believes is rarely explored in superhero films convincingly. Bird also decided to voice the character himself after several actresses originally considered for the role failed to replicate Edna's unique accent. The director understood that, in addition to fashion expertise, the character would also need to demonstrate proficiency in science, engineering and technology in order to create costumes capable of withstanding the trials of superheroic activities, and ultimately conceived her as a short, confident character of both German and Japanese descent based on these countries' reputations as small yet powerful nations. Inspired by [[Q (James Bond)|Q]] from the ''[[James Bond (franchise)|James Bond]]'' franchise, Edna is widely believed to have been based primarily on costume designer [[Edith Head]], although there continues to be constant speculation as to which celebrities inspired Edna, particularly ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' editor-in-chief [[Anna Wintour]] and actress [[Linda Hunt]].\n\nDespite having only supporting roles in both films, Edna has since established herself as ''The Incredibles''{{'}} [[breakout character]] due to her popularity among fans. While film critics agree that Edna is a [[Scene stealer|scene-stealer]], particularly praising her humor and dialogue, Bird has also been lauded for his voice acting, earning an [[Annie Award]] for [[Annie Award for Voice Acting in a Feature Production|Voice Acting in a Feature Production]] for his performance as the character. Edna has been recognized as one of Pixar's greatest characters by several prominent media publications.\n\n==Development==\n===Creation and voice===\n[[File:Brad bird cropped 2009.jpg|thumb|209x209px|In addition to creating the character, writer and director [[Brad Bird]] also provides the voice of Edna, using a unique accent that has been described as a hybrid between German and Japanese.|left]]Edna was created for ''The Incredibles'' by writer and director [[Brad Bird]].<ref name=\":33\" /> Having watched several [[Superhero fiction|superhero-themed films and television shows]] prior to developing ''The Incredibles'', Bird had often found himself wondering who is responsible for making the superheroes' elaborate costumes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2004/oct/22/20041022-090900-7146r/|title=\u2018Incredibles\u2019 creator eyes superheroes\u2019 home lives|last=|first=|date=October 22, 2004|website=[[The Washington Times]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202659/https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2004/oct/22/20041022-090900-7146r/|archivedate=February 17, 2018|access-date=February 17, 2018}}</ref> Bird conceived Edna upon discovering that, despite featuring characters dressed in fancy, extravagant costumes, traditional [[superhero film]]s rarely offer plausible explanations as to how superheroes come to obtain these outfits, or who provides them in the first place.<ref name=\":0\" /> The director wanted to debunk the [[Trope (literature)|trope]] of muscular superheroes sewing their own costumes, finding it hard to believe that superheroes would suddenly develop a strong enough interest in fashion and textiles to design their own outfits.<ref name=\":0\" /> Therefore, Bird decided that if the world was populated with superheroes, there would naturally also be people responsible for designing their costumes who must also have a background in science and engineering,<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://lifestyle.howstuffworks.com/family/activities/movie-fun-night/how-the-incredibles-works4.htm|title=Ultimate Guide to 'The Incredibles' \u2013 'The Incredibles' Characters|last=Arkoff|first=Vicki|date=|website=[[HowStuffWorks]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202846/https://lifestyle.howstuffworks.com/family/activities/movie-fun-night/how-the-incredibles-works4.htm|archivedate=February 17, 2018|access-date=February 17, 2018}}</ref> thereby envisioning Edna as a scientist and technical genius in addition to being a fashion designer.<ref name=\":0\" /> The director elaborated, \"The way I saw it, the costumes had to be created by somebody with a scientific and engineering background\", thus conceiving Edna as \"a half-German, half-Japanese, tiny powerhouse of a character\".<ref name=\":6\" /> ''The Incredibles'' was the first Pixar film to earn a [[PG-Rating|PG rating]]; Edna is considered to be one of the studio's earliest attempts at approaching \"[[Dark-comedy|darker, edgier comedy]],\" which is particularly demonstrated by the scene in which the character cites several [[Graphic violence|graphic]] examples of capes directly resulting in the deaths of several superheroes, one of whom is shown being consumed and killed by a jet turbine.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite web|url=http://ew.com/gallery/pixar-top-12-movie-moments/12-the-incredibles-edna-modes-no-capes-speech|title=Pixar: Top 12 Movie Moments|last=Young|first=John|date=June 21, 2013|website=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219152052/http://ew.com/gallery/pixar-top-12-movie-moments/12-the-incredibles-edna-modes-no-capes-speech/|archivedate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> According to Bird, the creation of Edna took the notion of superheroes wearing designed costumes \"to a further extreme\".<ref name=\":38\" />\n\nEdna was named after EMode, a software Pixar used at the time the film was made.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/gallery/2011/jun/26/pixar-animation|title=The 10 best Pixar characters|last=Solomons|first=Jason|date=June 26, 2011|website=The Guardian|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218210210/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/gallery/2011/jun/26/pixar-animation|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.ca/translate?hl=en&sl=nl&u=https://www.vpro.nl/programmas/zomergasten/lees/gasten/2012/achtergronden-fragmenten-2012/the-incredibles.html&prev=search|title=the incredibles|last=|first=|date=2012|website=VPRO|language=Dutch|access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":40\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/female-pixar-characters-who-deserve-film/|title=15 Female Pixar Characters Who Deserve a Feature Film|last=Friday|first=Wednesday Lee|date=June 18, 2016|website=Screen Rant|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> Bird identified Edna as the \"most fun character\" he had written for the film, recalling, \"Any day that I was writing her, I was one happy camper.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Edna follows the tradition of having a director voice one of the film's secondary characters in animated films, which was based around Bird's \"slave-driver voice\" that he used during production.<ref name=\":39\">{{Cite web|url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/the-10-best-pixar-characters-from-infinity-to-squirrel-ed3fd6988175/|title=The 10 Best Pixar Characters: From Infinity to Squirrel!|last=Carr|first=Kevin|date=June 21, 2012|website=Film School Rejects|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> Bird's voice for the character originated during the story boarding process, during which various Pixar employees typically provide characters' voices temporarily while the filmmakers and animators organize the film's pacing and staging in order to \"get a sense of the film.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://moviecitynews.com/archived/Interviews/bird.html|title=Brad Bird & The Incredibles|last=Gronvall|first=Andrea|date=November 10, 2004|website=Movie City News|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202747/http://moviecitynews.com/archived/Interviews/bird.html|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref> Although these voices are usually eventually replaced by professional actors and voice actors, there are some situations in which \"those voices stick\", as was the case with the voice Bird had created for Edna.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://movies.radiofree.com/interviews/theincre_brad_bird.shtml|title=Brad Bird|last=Lee|first=Michael J.|date=October 17, 2004|website=RadioFree.com|access-date=February 16, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217082446/http://movies.radiofree.com/interviews/theincre_brad_bird.shtml|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref> Bird had also provided the temporary voices of other characters during this time, including Bob Parr and Syndrome.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.movingimagesource.us/files/dialogues/2/90944_programs_transcript_html_253.htm|title=A Pinewood Dialogue with Brad Bird|last=Goodman|first=Carl|date=January 9, 2005|website=Moving Image Source|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701005231/http://www.movingimagesource.us/files/dialogues/2/90944_programs_transcript_html_253.htm|archivedate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> Several actresses had been considered for the role; one actress, whom Bird is particularly fond of, constantly asked Bird to repeatedly demonstrate his interpretation of one of Edna's lines until telling him that he should simply voice the character himself since he \"kind of got a beat on it\".<ref name=\":0\" /> The role was also offered to actress and comedian [[Lily Tomlin]], who was sent a tape recording of Bird recording Edna's part in its entirety;<ref name=\":44\" /> Tomlin declined upon hearing Bird's interpretation, feeling she could not voice the character as funnily as he did.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=e1RTP8thtR0C&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25&dq=edna+mode+lily+tomlin&source=bl&ots=ASWFtvrLR7&sig=703hElh4tLysKjuRiC2dgNPYycQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiA0LXjtqzZAhVHRK0KHc2uCHc4ChDoAQg0MAM#v=onepage&q=edna%20mode%20lily%20tomlin&f=false|title=Disney Voice Actors: A Biographical Dictionary|last=Hischak|first=Thomas S.|publisher=McFarland|year=2011|isbn=9780786486946|location=United States|pages=25|via=Google Books|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218090155/https://books.google.ca/books?id=e1RTP8thtR0C&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25&dq=edna+mode+lily+tomlin&source=bl&ots=ASWFtvrLR7&sig=703hElh4tLysKjuRiC2dgNPYycQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiA0LXjtqzZAhVHRK0KHc2uCHc4ChDoAQg0MAM#v=onepage&q=edna%20mode%20lily%20tomlin&f=false|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Bird's colleagues had to heavily convince him to voice the character himself.<ref name=\":37\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/07/best-performances-in-animation-since-aladdin.html|title=The 25 Best Animated Movie Voice Performances Since Aladdin|last=Ebiri|first=Bilge|date=July 10, 2015|website=Vulture.com|access-date=May 2, 2018}}</ref> Finally succumbing to \"popular demand\" from his fellow Pixar employees, Bird joked that he was ultimately cast as Edna simply because he was both affordable and available at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/04/03/398343037/pixars-brad-bird-talks-french-food-animated-rats-and-new-film-tomorrowland|title=Pixar's Brad Bird Talks French Food, Animated Rats And New Film 'Tomorrowland'|date=April 8, 2015|website=NPR|access-date=February 16, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409000805/http://www.npr.org/2015/04/03/398343037/pixars-brad-bird-talks-french-food-animated-rats-and-new-film-tomorrowland|archivedate=April 9, 2015}}</ref> A similar tactic was used for several other supporting characters in the film: animator Bret Parker voices Kari, the Parr family's babysitter, writer [[Bud Luckey]] voices government agent Rick Dicker,<ref name=\":7\" /> and production designer [[Lou Romano]] voices Bernie Kropp, Dash's teacher.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nBird described Edna's voice as a combination of a Japanese and German accent, deciding to draw influence from these countries because \"they're two small countries that have amazing design and amazing technology\", citing cameras and cars of examples of technology in which they specialize.<ref name=\":0\" /> Urban Cinefile's Louise Keller described the character's voice as \"mid European ... complicated by an Asian touch\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.urbancinefile.com.au/home/view.asp?a=9758&s=Reviews|title=Incredibles, The|last=Keller|first=Louise|last2=Urban|first2=Andrew L.|date=December 26, 2004|website=Urban Cinefile|access-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180302103840/http://www.urbancinefile.com.au/home/view.asp?a=9758&s=Reviews|archivedate=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Although Bird's performance is considerably broad, he avoids allowing Edna to become too much of a [[caricature]] in order to maintain the illusion that she is one of the film's smartest characters.<ref name=\":22\" /> In the Italian and French-language versions of the film, Bird's comic accent is replaced by that of French-Italian entertainer [[Amanda Lear]], who offers a more seductive, \"biting\" interpretation.<ref name=\":8\" /> Lear said that dubbing Edna's voice was not an easy process, but accepted the job after being offered the role upon seeing the film at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] in order to fulfill her dream of having always wanted to voice a Disney character.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.ca/translate?hl=en&sl=it&u=http://trovacinema.repubblica.it/news/dettaglio/amanda-lear-doppiando-edna-del-film-gli-incredibili-ho-coronato-il-sogno-di-bambina/281964/&prev=search|title=Amanda Lear: Doubling Edna from the Film 'The Incredibles'{{!}}\"I Crowned My Childhood Dream\"|last=|first=|date=November 18, 2004|website=Trovacinema|language=Italian|access-date=February 17, 2018}}</ref> Edna was the first character Lear was hired to dub in Italian.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n===Personality, design and influences===\nBird believes that he shares some of Edna's personality traits, specifically the way in which he prefers to be involved in virtually every creative aspect of his projects, including story boarding, writing and cinematography,<ref name=\":1\" /> admitting that he and his character demonstrate both a high level of self-confidence and lack of self-doubt when it comes to their own work.<ref name=\":6\" /> Bird elaborated that \"At my most confident, I feel like her \n... She is absolutely convinced that her way is the right way, and if you disagree \u2026 you\u2019re just wrong!\u201d<ref name=\":44\">{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/06/14/incredibles-edna-mode-is-based-on-these-fashion-mavens/|title=\u2018Incredibles\u2019 Edna Mode is based on these fashion mavens|last=Miller|first=Gregory E.|date=June 14, 2018|website=[[New York Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref> Bird identified Edna as one of the film's most difficult characters to design.<ref name=\":38\" /> The character went through several different changes in appearance during the development process, ranging from taller and overweight to older, younger and thinner.<ref name=\":7\" /> Inspired by the large impact that countries such as Japan and Germany have on the world despite being comparatively small in size, Bird decided that Edna would demonstrate this theme by being \"a tiny character that dominates the room when she gets into it.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Her home, which uses high-end technology similar to what she incorporates into the outfits she creates,<ref name=\":31\" /> was deliberately designed to be significantly larger than she is to further emphasize this theme of dominance.<ref name=\":0\" /> Edna's small stature was also inspired by singer [[Bette Midler]], of whom Bird has always been a fan. The director recalled being surprised by Midler's height when he first met her \"Because ... she absolutely dominates the screen. And it just struck me how much personality was in this small body.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In terms of animation, Bird wanted all of the film's characters to move differently from each other, providing Edna with a very confident walk to represent the fact that she has \"never experienced doubt in her life.\"<ref name=\":11\" /> The animators found the fact that Bird provided the character's voice himself to be very helpful as he would often act out the way in which the character acts and behaves himself, which helped in further defining the animator's vision of Edna.<ref name=\":38\" /> According to Bird, Edna, despite her petite stature, is the only non-superhero in ''The Incredibles'' capable of making superheroes feel uncomfortable.<ref name=\":30\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=LhOwDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA142&dq=edna+mode+incredibles&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXseeO49rZAhXCmuAKHZn3DOUQ6AEIVTAJ#v=onepage&q=edna%20mode%20incredibles&f=false|title=Pixar and the Aesthetic Imagination: Animation, Storytelling, and Digital Culture|last=Herhuth|first=Eric|publisher=Univ of California Press|year=2017|isbn=9780520966055|location=United States|pages=142|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308042517/https://books.google.ca/books?id=LhOwDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA142&dq=edna+mode+incredibles&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXseeO49rZAhXCmuAKHZn3DOUQ6AEIVTAJ#v=onepage&q=edna%20mode%20incredibles&f=false|archivedate=March 8, 2018|url-status=live|via=Google Books}}</ref> Bird described Edna as a character who is \"not remotely intimidated by superheroes or anyone\", refusing to accept the word \"no\" when it is used in opposition of her opinions or beliefs.<ref name=\":6\" />\nEdna was actually inspired by Edith Head who was also a costume designer and won a record of 8 Academy Awards for costume design. \n[[Entertainment Weekly|<nowiki/>]][[Entertainment Weekly|<nowiki/>]]\n\nDescribing Edna's physical attributes as \"severe\", Bird had envisioned the character having glasses and a pageboy haircut, while still wanting her to appear modern and elegant at the same time.<ref name=\":38\" /> Edna's ethnicity has been identified as half-German and half-Japanese.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/70795/17-super-facts-about-incredibles|title=17 Super Facts About The Incredibles|last=Cormier|first=Roger|date=November 5, 2015|website=Mental Floss|access-date=February 17, 2018|quote=Edna Mode was made half German and half Japanese after Bird thought about German engineering and Japanese car and camera manufacturing ...|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202918/http://mentalfloss.com/article/70795/17-super-facts-about-incredibles|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=http://movies.disney.com/the-incredibles/characters|title=Characters {{!}} The Incredibles|website=Disney.com|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218210418/http://movies.disney.com/the-incredibles/characters|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Both Edna's physical appearance and voice are widely believed to have based on those of costume designer [[Edith Head]],<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":47\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.racked.com/2018/6/14/17461468/edna-mode-incredibles-fashion|title=The Incredibles\u2019 Edna Mode Is Film\u2019s Best Fashion Character|last=Wisel|first=Carlye|date=June 14, 2018|website=Racked|access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref> with whom she shares her signature round glasses and black [[bob cut]].<ref name=\":8\" /> According to Head's entry in the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]], the character is inspired by both the costume designer's signature glasses and \"forthright personality\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/collection-highlights/edith-head|title=Edith Head|website=Oscars.org|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218090311/http://www.oscars.org/collection-highlights/edith-head|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Bird described Edna as a combination of both Head and [[Q (James Bond)|Q]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://themovieboy.com/reviews/i/04_incredibles.htm|title=The Incredibles (2004)|last=Putman|first=Dustin|date=November 6, 2004|website=TheFilmFile|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319213642/http://themovieboy.com/reviews/i/04_incredibles.htm|archive-date=March 19, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=March 19, 2018|quote=Also notable is Edna \"E\" Mode (voiced wonderfully by director Brad Bird and taking a page from the James Bond series' M figure)}}</ref> a character featured in the ''[[James Bond]]'' franchise.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://ew.com/article/2004/11/19/who-incredibles-fashion-maven-based/|title=Who is the ''Incredibles'' fashion maven based on?|last=Daly|first=Steve|date=November 19, 2004|website=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202839/http://ew.com/article/2004/11/19/who-incredibles-fashion-maven-based/|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":24\">{{Cite web|url=http://q13fox.com/2015/11/20/here-are-pixars-15-best-characters/|title=Here are Pixar\u2019s 15 best characters|last=|first=|date=November 20, 2015|website=[[Q13 FOX News]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219090619/http://q13fox.com/2015/11/20/here-are-pixars-15-best-characters/|archivedate=February 19, 2018|access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> The director has generally declined to confirm any direct influences on the character, insisting that Edna is \"not based on a specific person\",<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-incredible-edna-vol-62-no-22/|title=Picks and Pans Review: Incredible Edna|date=November 29, 2004|website=People|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202840/http://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-incredible-edna-vol-62-no-22/|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref> including publicly refuting claims that he based the character on Head, although she continues to be considered the character's \"most legitimate\" alleged inspiration.<ref name=\":47\" /> However, animator [[Teddy Newton]], who co-designed Edna with Bird, revealed that he and Pixar were inspired by the film ''[[Unzipped (film)|Unzipped]]'' (1995), a documentary depicting the petulance of fashion designer [[Isaac Mizrahi]] and stylist [[Polly Allen Mellen]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Fans have long speculated about the real-life inspiration behind Edna's design and appearance.<ref name=\":44\" /><ref name=\":47\" /> Bird stated he has constantly been told by various fans and viewers that the character reminds them of at least 15 different celebrities since the character debuted in ''The Incredibles''.<ref name=\":2\" /> Contributing to ''[[Fashion (magazine)|Fashion]]'', Erin Dunlop described the character as \"a supercharged hybrid of every fashion industry legend we can think of\".<ref name=\":34\">{{Cite web|url=https://fashionmagazine.com/culture/fashion-industry-fictional-characters/|title=The 10 coolest fashion industry pros (hint: they\u2019re all fictional characters)|last=Dunlop|first=Erin|date=February 4, 2016|website=Fashion|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315070538/https://fashionmagazine.com/culture/fashion-industry-fictional-characters/|archive-date=March 15, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> In an article discussing who Edna is based on, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''[[Entertainment Weekly|<nowiki/>']]<nowiki/>s Steve Daly cited ''Vogue'' editor-in-chief [[Anna Wintour]], designer [[Coco Chanel]] and actress [[Lotte Lenya]] as possible influences, while drawing similarities between the character's use of large-framed glasses to architect [[Philip Johnson]], producer [[Robert Evans]], talent agent [[Irving Paul Lazar|Swifty Lazar]], studio executive [[Lew Wasserman]], and fashion editor [[Carrie Donovan]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Some critics have suspected that the character is also based on [[Mary Quant]] and Una Jones.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=gyjob_gq3yoC&pg=PA391&lpg=PA391&dq=brad+bird+edna+mode+interview&source=bl&ots=HHGSLlhwsz&sig=AcTYOvZ0uNXi8FqyMHwrQvnVcHY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwic3cHmtazZAhWKxYMKHR8YDYg4HhDoAQheMAw#v=onepage&q=brad%20bird%20edna%20mode%20interview&f=false|title=Edith Head: The Fifty-Year Career of Hollywood's Greatest Costume Designer|last1=Jorgensen|first1=Jay|date=2010|publisher=Running Press|isbn=9780762441730|location=United States|page=391|language=en|via=Google Books|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218092128/https://books.google.ca/books?id=gyjob_gq3yoC&pg=PA391&lpg=PA391&dq=brad+bird+edna+mode+interview&source=bl&ots=HHGSLlhwsz&sig=AcTYOvZ0uNXi8FqyMHwrQvnVcHY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwic3cHmtazZAhWKxYMKHR8YDYg4HhDoAQheMAw#v=onepage&q=brad%20bird%20edna%20mode%20interview&f=false|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Acknowledging that there are several female fashion designers who wear glasses upon whom Edna could have been based, Bird admitted that the character was inspired by author [[Patricia Highsmith]] and actress [[Linda Hunt]], elaborating: \"When you're designing a character, you're just saying - who is that? ... We tried a lot of stuff and we kept saying no, no, more like this, but I like the nose on this one, and maybe the [[Pageboy|pageboy cut]], maybe glasses should be bigger ... and you end up with something that reminds you of Edith Head and Linda Hunt.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|last1=Gilchrist|first1=Todd|title=The Incredibles: An Interview with Brad Bird|url=http://www.blackfilm.com/20041029/features/bradbird.shtml|website=Blackfilm|accessdate=February 17, 2018|date=November 2004|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625145649/http://www.blackfilm.com/20041029/features/bradbird.shtml|archivedate=June 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":36\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.chasingthefrog.com/reelfaces/devilwearsprada.php|title=The Devil Wears Prada (2006)|website=Chasing the Frog|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321063113/http://www.chasingthefrog.com/reelfaces/devilwearsprada.php|archive-date=March 21, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Entertainment Weekly|<nowiki/>]]\n\nFor the sequel, shading art director Bryn Imagire decided to incorporate more of Edna's Japanese heritage into her two new costumes, basing them on the work of Japanese costume designers [[Rei Kawakubo]], [[Eiko Ishioka]] and Chitose Abe.<ref name=\":44\" /> Imagire was particularly inspired by Kawakubo's quote, \"For something to be beautiful, it doesn\u2019t have to be pretty,\u201d and opting to envision Edna's outfits \"more as abstract sculpture\" as opposed to forms of clothing.<ref name=\":44\" /> In order to design costumes for a fictional character who also happens to be a designer in her own film, Imagire drew upon lessons she had learned while attending [[art school]], describing Edna's style as \"very to the point and very specific\" while imagining what the character might be thinking while designing her clothes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insidethemagic.net/2018/05/interview-a-very-simple-and-graphic-idea-designing-the-costumes-for-disney-pixars-incredibles-2/|title=A Very Simple and Graphic Idea \u2013 Designing the Costumes for Pixar\u2019s \"Incredibles 2\" (Interview)|last=Celestino|first=Mike|date=May 1, 2018|website=Inside the Magic|access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref> Meanwhile, character artist Deanna Marsigliese's first assignment was to create an entire line of clothing designed by Edna,<ref name=\":46\">{{Cite web|url=https://d23.com/how-to-costume-a-super-in-incredibles-2/|title=How to Costume a Super in Incredibles 2|last=Potter|first=Courtney|date=June 18, 2018|website=D23|access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref> for which she was tasked with \"thinking like Edna\".<ref name=\":45\">{{Cite web|url=https://style.disney.com/news/2018/05/31/incredibles-2-costumes/|title=An Inside Look at the Costumes for Incredibles 2|last=Uribe|first=Mariana|date=May 31, 2018|website=Disney Style|access-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref> Although ultimately the completed clothing line does not appear in the final film, Marsigliese considered the experience to be \" a study in (Edna's) character\" nonetheless, during which she drew inspiration from Edna's appearance and wardrobe in the first film, from her dress to the interior of her house.<ref name=\":46\" /> Although she was aware that Edna enjoys being dramatic, she acknowledge that \"fashion designers don\u2019t necessarily design things that they would wear on their person, they design for their models\", meaning, \"Their [[Aesthetics|aesthetic]] is oftentimes different.\u201d<ref name=\":45\" /> Similarly, Imagire agreed that fashion designers such as Kawakubo, Ishioka and Abe \"always looked really comfortable in contrast to what they were creating for their models\", a contrast that she wanted to incorporate into the character.<ref name=\":45\" /> Recalling that Edna dislikes models, the artist envisioned that the character would instead design her own clothing to serve as \"a vehicle to celebrate superheroes and her powers.\"<ref name=\":45\" /> Inspired by Italian fashion designer [[Elsa Schiaparelli]], Marsigliese created a \"classic, [[Mid-century modern|mid-century]] inspired silhouette\" for Edna's costumes that were also bold and dramatic as though Edna herself had designed them, then rearranging the designs to ultimately give them a more surreal, specific appearance.<ref name=\":45\" /> Dubbing the character a \"woman of the now\", Marsigliese explained that, like Schiaparelli, Edna is \"completely ahead of her time\" despite living in the 1950s; \"she used a lot of surrealist elements, a lot of fun surprises, and that was very inspiring for me.\u201d<ref name=\":46\" /> Imagire designed approximately 25 potential costumes for Edna, 15 of which she showed to Bird before the final two were decided upon: a simple indigo dress and black-and-red kimono.<ref name=\":44\" />\n\n[[Entertainment Weekly|<nowiki/>]]\n\n==Characterization==\n\nAccording to Matthew Brunson of [[Creative Loafing]], Edna provides the majority of the film's [[comic relief]].<ref name=\":29\">{{Cite web|url=http://charlotte.creativeloafing.com/2004-11-10/film_feature2.html|title=Toon In, Toon Out|last=Brunson|first=Matt|date=November 10, 2004|website=Creative Loafing|access-date=March 3, 2018|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060512232812/http://charlotte.creativeloafing.com/2004-11-10/film_feature2.html|archivedate=May 12, 2006}}</ref> Hischak believes that Edna offers \"a whole new viewpoint to the world of superheroes\", in addition to demonstrating the film's \"oddball silliness\".<ref name=\":3\" /> ''[[Vogue Italia]]'' published a biography of Edna, in which author Valentina Fabbri described her as a character who \"knows she\u2019s the best and she doesn\u2019t hide it, and her lack of modesty is equalled only by her intuition\", with whom it is virtually impossible to have a conversation because \"she tends to dominate.\"<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.vogue.it/en/news/encyclo/mania/m/edna-mode|title=Edna Mode|last=Fabbri|first=Valentina|date=|website=[[Vogue Italia]]|pages=1\u20133|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218090311/http://www.vogue.it/en/news/encyclo/mania/m/edna-mode|archivedate=February 18, 2018|access-date=February 17, 2018|quote=The character immediately captured the imagination of the public, which fell in love with her irreverence and friendly sulkiness.}}</ref> Due to her combination of genius-level intellect and \"craziness,\" Fabbri identified Edna as \"a fun, bubbly caricature of the magicians of fashion\" by \"embod[ying] their talent and charisma, their vices and virtues.\"<ref name=\":8\" /> [[Screen Rant]]'s Victoria Robertson observed that the character \"has a lot of personality packed into a small exterior, taking stereotypical traits often attributed to designers and making them her own\", firstly remaining proud of her own work at all times.<ref name=\":27\" /> Oliver Lyttelton of [[IndieWire]] identified Edna as quite possibly the film's most intelligent character.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2015/11/the-30-best-voice-performances-in-pixar-movies-102929/|title=The 30 Best Voice Performances In Pixar Movies|last=Lyttelton|first=Oliver|date=November 24, 2015|website=IndieWire|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219150549/http://www.indiewire.com/2015/11/the-30-best-voice-performances-in-pixar-movies-102929/|archivedate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> Edna's criticisms of fashion can come off as unpleasant at times, but are exaggerated to the point of which audiences find them to be comical.<ref name=\":9\" /> Edna prefers to always think about the future, finding dwelling on the past to be distracting from the present, as demonstrated by her line \"I never look back, dahling, it distracts from the now\",<ref name=\":28\">{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/tournament-of-pixar-round-3-woody-vs-edna-mode|title=Tournament of Pixar, Round 3: Woody vs. Edna Mode|last=K|first=E|date=June 17, 2015|website=National Post|access-date=February 22, 2018}}</ref> and thus has proven capable of determining the needs of her superhero clientele before they have the opportunity to finalize their ideas themselves.<ref name=\":8\" /> Her personality has been described by ''[[GamesRadar+]]''<nowiki/>'s Joshua Winning as \"brassy\" and \"no-nonsense\".<ref name=\":16\" /> Q13 Fox described Edna as \"a gifted designer, an assertive life coach and a witty talker,\"<ref name=\":24\" /> using her mind and intelligence as a means of solving everyday issues.<ref name=\":47\" /> [[BuddyTV]] believes that the character's \"bold and eccentric attitude\" is rivaled only by her considerable talent.<ref name=\":31\" /> According to Kevin Carr of [[Film School Rejects]], Edna \"doesn\u2019t take crap from anyone\" yet \"she does so with poise and pride.\"<ref name=\":39\" /> The ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]''<nowiki/>'s Carla Meyer argues that Edna is \"more a caricature than a character.\"<ref name=\":43\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Just-another-nuclear-family-with-super-powers-2676516.php|title=Just another nuclear family -- with super powers|last=Meyer|first=Carla|date=November 5, 2004|website=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=June 8, 2018}}</ref>\n<nowiki/>[[File:Linda Hunt.jpg|left|thumb|277x277px|Actress [[Linda Hunt]], one of the celebrities to whom Edna's appearance has constantly been compared and often believed to have been based on.]]Scott Tobias of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called Edna \"a reminder that the superhero suit needs to the perfect synthesis of form and function\", without which \"greatness as both a crimefighter and an icon is impossible.\"<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/lists/25-best-pixar-movie-characters-20160615/buzz-lightyear-toy-story-movies-1995-2010-20160615|title=25 Best Pixar Movie Characters|last=Adams|first=Sam|last2=Bramesco|first2=Charles|date=June 15, 2016|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=February 18, 2018|last3=Grierson|first3=Tim|last4=Tobias|first4=Scott|last5=Wilkinson|first5=Alissa|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218150531/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/lists/25-best-pixar-movie-characters-20160615/buzz-lightyear-toy-story-movies-1995-2010-20160615|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> According to Thomas S. Hischak, author of ''100 Greatest American and British Animated Films'', Edna is just as concerned with the appearance of the costumes she designs as she is about their use and practicality,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=YtJKDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA154&lpg=PA154&dq=edna+mode+lily+tomlin&source=bl&ots=PWWci9UG-6&sig=ZYj1Nl_qrfN0i5v2ZhU2LE5YPNk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiA0LXjtqzZAhVHRK0KHc2uCHc4ChDoAQgqMAE#v=onepage&q=edna%20mode%20lily%20tomlin&f=false|title=100 Greatest American and British Animated Films|last=Hischak|first=Thomas S.|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2018|isbn=9781538105696|location=United States|pages=154|via=Google Books|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217141932/https://books.google.ca/books?id=YtJKDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA154&lpg=PA154&dq=edna+mode+lily+tomlin&source=bl&ots=PWWci9UG-6&sig=ZYj1Nl_qrfN0i5v2ZhU2LE5YPNk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiA0LXjtqzZAhVHRK0KHc2uCHc4ChDoAQgqMAE#v=onepage&q=edna%20mode%20lily%20tomlin&f=false|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref> proving capable of designing outfits that can stretch, change their shape and resist oncoming attacks such as missiles and fires.<ref name=\":8\" /> The character proves capable of designing a costume for Violet that is capable of becoming invisible whenever its wearer does.<ref name=\":43\" /> She absolutely refuses to incorporate capes into her new designs due to the accessory having a history of contributing to the deaths of superheroes in the past, among them Dynaguy, Thunderhead, Stratogale, Meta-Man and Splashdown,<ref name=\":18\" /> presenting them as a \"montage of superhero couture [[wikt:Faux pas|faux-pas]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/the-incredibles|title=The Incredibles|last=B|first=N|website=Time Out|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222225638/https://www.timeout.com/london/film/the-incredibles|archivedate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> Ultimately, her knowledge of the dangers of capes results in the death of the film's villain [[Syndrome (character)|Syndrome]].<ref name=\":22\" /> In terms of her own appearance, Edna is costumed in \"[[Futuristic fashion|futuristic]] black\" attire, wearing a black dress that boasts square lines.<ref name=\":8\" /> Estimating her height to be of approximately three feet, ''[[The Tyee]]''<nowiki/>'s Dorothy Woodend wrote that Edna is dressed in [[Issey Miyake]] pleats while being of \"indeterminate gender\".<ref name=\":26\" /> [[VPRO]] drew similarities between the character's hairstyle and personality to that of ''Vogue'' editor Anna Wintour,<ref name=\":18\" /> the resemblance to whom Tech Times' Katherine Derla identified as \"The first thing viewers are likely to remember upon seeing\" the character.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.techtimes.com/articles/165288/20160616/animated-characters-done-right-top-10-pixar-movie-characters.htm|title=Animated Characters Done Right: Top 10 Pixar Movie Characters|last=Derla|first=Katherine|date=June 16, 2016|website=Tech Times|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219090138/http://www.techtimes.com/articles/165288/20160616/animated-characters-done-right-top-10-pixar-movie-characters.htm|archivedate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> According to ''STATUS'' magazine, Edna is often mistaken for the magazine editor largely due to her \"snappy sass and iconic bob\".<ref>{{cite web|title=10 Movie Characters Based on Fashion Icons|url=http://statusmagonline.com/10-movie-characters-based-on-fashion-icons/|website=STATUS Magazine|accessdate=March 14, 2018|date=September 5, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315211418/http://statusmagonline.com/10-movie-characters-based-on-fashion-icons/|archivedate=March 15, 2018}}</ref> Film's Angie Han joked that Edna's \"no-nonsense demeanor\" would leave Wintour \"quaking in her Chanel boots.\"<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/best-pixar-female-characters/2/|title=Pixar\u2019s 15 Best Female Characters|last=Han|first=Angie|date=June 23, 2015|website=/Film|access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> When asked about the alleged similarities between her and the character, Wintour revealed that she has yet to see the film.<ref name=\":36\" /> Derla also wrote that Edna is capable of \"run[ing] the world\" but opts to operate from behind the scenes instead.<ref name=\":23\" /> The term \"diminutive\" is often used to describe the character's height.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/12-best-supporting-pixar-characters/|title=12 Best Supporting Pixar Characters|last=Winning|first=Joshua|date=February 18, 2010|website=GamesRadar+|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218210424/https://www.gamesradar.com/12-best-supporting-pixar-characters/|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nConsidering herself to be \"too talented\" to design clothes for normal humans,<ref name=\":8\" /> Edna resents having been forced to resort to designing clothes for [[supermodel]]s during the 15-year-long absence of superheroes,<ref name=\":4\" /> dismissing them as \"Spoiled, stupid little stick figures with poofy lips who think only about themselves\",<ref name=\":24\" /> an opinion she formed after being forced to work with such individuals in Milan and Paris.<ref name=\":31\">{{cite web|url=http://www.buddytv.com/info/edna-mode-info.aspx|title=Edna Mode|last=|first=|date=|website=[[BuddyTV]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309054425/http://www.buddytv.com/info/edna-mode-info.aspx|archive-date=March 9, 2018|accessdate=March 8, 2018|quote=Edna Marie \u2018E\u2019 Mode is a fictional fashion designer, and supporting character from the Disney and Pixar motion picture The Incredibles.}}</ref><ref name=\":35\" /> Edna believes that designing clothes for superheroes is similar to designing for gods, and thus considers herself to be far superior to other fashion designers.<ref name=\":31\" /> Despite her considerable success as one of the world's top fashion designers internationally,<ref name=\":38\" /> Edna longs to return to working with superheroes so that she can challenge her designs by \"fus[ing] the latest technology with her impeccable fashion sense\" to the public's amusement, who continue to adore both her and her creations,<ref name=\":35\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pixar.com/feature-films/the-incredibles/#the-incredibles-1|title=The Incredibles|website=Pixar Animation Studios|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315133306/https://www.pixar.com/feature-films/the-incredibles/#the-incredibles-1|archive-date=March 15, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> insisting that there is nothing \"super\" about supermodels.<ref name=\":38\" /> Despite designing elaborate costumes for a living, Edna prefers a more simple aesthetic for herself, generally avoiding nail polish and accessories.<ref name=\":47\" /> [[Racked.com|Racked]]'s Carlye Wisel observed that although the sequel \"may have deep roots in midcentury-modern design ... Edna remains true to her forward-looking style, wearing a red silk kimono as well as an asymmetrical sheath that feels like yet another nod to Kawakubo\u2019s work.\"<ref name=\":47\" /> In addition to being a talented fashion designer, Edna has also demonstrated proficiency in [[psychology]]. In addition to designing their clothes, she offers advice to her clients whenever she feels that they require it,<ref name=\":8\" /> demonstrating a \"zero-tolerance policy for emotional weakness\" which, according to ''[[The Dissolve]]'''s Charles Bramesco, represents Bird's \"lament[ing] regular folks\u2019 tendency to impede awesome people from being awesome.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bramesco|first1=Charles|title=The slippery politics of The Incredibles and other superheroes|url=https://thedissolve.com/features/movie-of-the-week/812-the-slippery-politics-of-the-incredibles-and-other/|website=The Dissolve|accessdate=February 23, 2018|date=November 6, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224112902/https://thedissolve.com/features/movie-of-the-week/812-the-slippery-politics-of-the-incredibles-and-other/|archivedate=February 24, 2018}}</ref> Edna is known for her tendency to refer to her cohorts as \"dahling\",<ref name=\":17\" /><ref name=\":19\" /> while her colleagues affectionately refer to her as \"E\".<ref name=\":38\" /> In addition to citing her resemblance to Wintour, journalist [[Hadley Freeman]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' believes that Edna's use of fashion in the film represents \"The highest pinnacle of human achievement. Without them the world would come to an end.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/jan/31/fashion.lifeandhealth|title=Which couturiers make the cut on screen?|last=Freeman|first=Hadley|date=January 31, 2008|website=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315070526/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/jan/31/fashion.lifeandhealth|archive-date=March 15, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\nEdna first appears in ''The Incredibles'' as a fashion designer to superheroes and close friend of the titular characters.<ref name=\":8\" /> During the \u201cgolden age of superheroes\",<ref name=\":40\" /> Edna is one of a few elite guests who attend the private wedding ceremony of Bob and Helen Parr, then better-known to the public as the superheroes Mr. Incredible and Elastigirl. After all superheroes have been [[outlaw]]ed and forced to retire following a series of lawsuits,<ref name=\":16\" /> forcing Edna to retire from superhero work due to government restrictions,<ref name=\":40\" /> Edna does not appear again until approximately midway through film when she is unexpectedly visited by Bob who has resumed superhero work undercover, a secret he keeps from his family. Bob initially asks Edna to simply repair his original super suit, but she ultimately convinces him to allow her to design an entirely new outfit on the condition that capes not be incorporated whatsoever due to safety concerns, ultimately ending her 15 years-long retirement from superhero work.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=https://d23.com/23-favorite-pixar-supporting-characters/|title=23 Favorite Pixar Supporting Characters|last=|first=|date=|website=D23.com|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-access=registration }}</ref> Helen soon discovers that Bob's original super suit had received a [[Patchwork|patch job]], determining that the only person capable of repairing a super suit would be Edna and growing more suspicious of Bob's actions.<ref name=\":30\" /> Later in the film, Helen visits Edna in the hopes of finding out more information about Bob's whereabouts, discovering that she had taken the liberty of designing a complete matching set of super suits for his family.<ref name=\":43\" /> Although their reunion is brief, Edna provides an initially distraught Helen with the encouragement she needs to resume her identity as Elastigirl in order to save her husband (and their marriage), in addition to introducing the character to the homing device she had implanted in her husband's suit, intentionally revealing his exact location to her.<ref name=\":43\" />\n\nEdna appears in the film's sequel, ''[[Incredibles 2]]'' (2018). When Helen is recruited by a pair of entrepreneurs to change the public's perception of superheroes and thus returns to work to fight crime as Elastigirl,<ref name=\":47\" /> Edna is upset to learn that Elastigirl's costume has been designed by a rival designer. Bob soon becomes overwhelmed by Jack-Jack's emerging superpowers, and recruits Edna for assistance with controlling him. Although Edna is initially reluctant to [[Babysitting|babysit]] Jack-Jack,<ref name=\":47\" /> she soon develops a strong liking for the baby and she is willing to babysit him overnight free of charge; during this time, she upgrades his suit with sensors and a remote control so that the family can monitor his powers and rein them in as needed.<ref name=\":44\" /> She gives the enhanced suit to Bob in a custom shopping bag, which bears a logo for her services that incorporates her signature eyeglasses into its lettering.<ref name=\":47\" /> Edna also appears in [[Disney on Ice]]'s adaptation of the film: ''The Incredibles in a Magic Kingdom Adventure''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/lifestyles/disney-on-ice-unmasks-incredibles-ice-show/article_8986404c-616d-5a6f-9e93-b81ec67755f0.html|title=Disney on Ice unmasks 'Incredibles' ice show|last=Woulfe|first=Molly|date=January 24, 2006|website=The Times of Northwest Indiana|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313092504/http://www.nwitimes.com/lifestyles/disney-on-ice-unmasks-incredibles-ice-show/article_8986404c-616d-5a6f-9e93-b81ec67755f0.html|archive-date=March 13, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=March 12, 2018}}</ref> The time that Edna spends looking after Jack-Jack is the focus of the animated short ''Auntie Edna''.\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe public was immediately captivated by Edna upon her debut, becoming particularly enamored with the character's combination of irreverence and sulkiness.<ref name=\":8\" /> Edna instantly established herself as a fan favorite when the film was released in 2004,<ref name=\":44\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hypable.com/incredibles-2-superheroes-ranked-from-worst-to-best/|title=\u2018Incredibles 2\u2019 superheroes ranked from worst to best|last=Locke|first=Aaron|date=June 19, 2018|website=Hypable|access-date=June 20, 2018}}</ref> which Racked's Carlye Wisel has attributed to the character's combination of wit and style.<ref name=\":47\" /> Several critics have referred to Edna as a [[Scene stealer|scene-stealing]] character;<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bullz-eye.com/mguide/reviews_2004/the_incredibles.htm|title=The Incredibles|last=Medsker|first=David|date=2004|website=Bullz-Eye.com|access-date=February 20, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223110906/http://www.bullz-eye.com/mguide/reviews_2004/the_incredibles.htm|archivedate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> ''Fashion'' magazine's Erin Dunlop crowned Edna \"the undisputed scene-stealer of\" the film.<ref name=\":34\" /> Dubbing her \"One of the great scene-stealing characters in ''The Incredibles''\", [[HowStuffWorks]] contributor Vicki Arkoff called Edna \"deliciously [[Deadpan humor|deadpan]]\".<ref name=\":6\" /> Ken Hanke, writing for the ''[[Mountain Xpress]]'', considers Edna to be among the film's gags and characters who \"are delightful and very funny\", particularly highlighting the character's anti-cape monologue while deeming her \"worth the price of admission\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mountainx.com/movies/reviews/incredibles-php/|title=The Incredibles|last=Hanke|first=Ken|date=November 10, 2004|website=Mountain Xpress|access-date=March 3, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180302225411/https://mountainx.com/movies/reviews/incredibles-php/|archivedate=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Film critic [[Peter Bradshaw]], contributing to ''[[The Irish Times]]'', described Edna as \"a joy with her wonderful and appropriate maxim: 'I never look back, darling. It distracts from the now.'\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/is-toy-story-better-than-up-all-19-pixar-films-ranked-1.3406416|title=Is \u2018Toy Story\u2019 better than \u2018Up\u2019? All 19 Pixar films ranked|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|date=February 27, 2018|website=The Irish Times|access-date=April 9, 2018}}</ref> Dorothy Woodend, writing for ''The Tyee'', praised Edna as \"a more interesting creature than all the Incredibles put together.\" Describing her as \"a personage I'd like to see more of\", Woodend continued that the character \"steals the show, and does fabulous things with it, darling.\"<ref name=\":26\">{{Cite web|url=https://thetyee.ca/Entertainment/2004/11/19/%27Incredibles%27RiteofPassage/|title=\u2018Incredibles\u2019 Rite of Passage|last=Woodend|first=Dorothy|date=November 19, 2004|website=The Tyee|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223051216/https://thetyee.ca/Entertainment/2004/11/19/%27Incredibles%27RiteofPassage/|archivedate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> Referred to as one of the film's \"high point[s]\", Kevin Lally of ''[[Film Journal International]]'' described the character's anti-cape montage as \"pricelessly funny\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.filmjournal.com/node/15186|title=The Incredibles|last=Lally|first=Kevin|date=November 5, 2004|website=Film Journal International|access-date=February 23, 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224053047/http://www.filmjournal.com/node/15186|archivedate=February 24, 2018}}</ref> a sentiment with which Matt Brunson of Creative Loafing agreed.<ref name=\":29\" /> The ''[[National Post]]'' described Edna as \"exactly the kind of person you want at your dinner party\".<ref name=\":28\" /> Notable Biographies identified Edna as \"one of the audience's favorite characters\".<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2005-A-Fi/Bird-Brad.html|title=Brad Bird Biography|website=Notable Biographies|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218090740/http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2005-A-Fi/Bird-Brad.html|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBird has also garnered critical acclaim for his performance. Nell Minow of [[Common Sense Media]] wrote that Bird \"plays the funniest character in the film\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commonsensemedia.org/movie-reviews/the-incredibles|title=The Incredibles|last=Minnow|first=Nell|website=Common Sense Media|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225133931/https://www.commonsensemedia.org/movie-reviews/the-incredibles|archivedate=December 25, 2017}}</ref> while [[AllMovie]]'s Perry Seibert described his performance as \"screamingly funny\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-incredibles-v287450/review|title=The Incredibles (2004)|last=Seibert|first=Perry|date=2004|website=AllMovie|access-date=February 23, 2004|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625171828/http://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-incredibles-v287450/review|archivedate=June 25, 2012}}</ref> Pete Vonder Haar of ''[[Film Threat]]'' wrote that Bird contributes \"the best work\" to the film as Edna in terms of dialogue and vocal performance, calling her rant about the \"idiocy\" of capes \"priceless.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.filmthreat.com/reviews/6624/|title=The Incredibles|last=Haar|first=Pete Vonder|date=November 6, 2004|website=Film Threat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021201814/http://www.filmthreat.com/reviews/6624/|archive-date=October 21, 2012|access-date=February 22, 2018}}</ref> Scott Chitwood, writing for [[ComingSoon.net]], agreed that Bird is \" absolutely hilarious as Edna\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chitwood|first1=Scott|title=The Incredibles|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/reviews/7031-the-incredibles|website=ComingSoon.net|accessdate=March 5, 2018|date=November 3, 2004|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306082955/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/reviews/7031-the-incredibles|archivedate=March 6, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Empire magazine|Empire]]''<nowiki/>'s Colin Kennedy dubbed Bird's voice work \"an unmistakable highlight\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/incredibles/review/|title=The Incredibles Review|last=Kennedy|first=Colin|date=January 1, 2011|website=Empire|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223052835/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/incredibles/review/|archivedate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> [[Bbc.co.uk|BBC]]'s Stella Papamichael agreed that the director \"steals the show\" as Edna.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Papamichael|first1=Stella|title=The Incredibles (2004)|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2004/11/09/the_incredibles_2004_review.shtml|website=BBC|accessdate=March 1, 2013|date=November 25, 2004|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827071510/http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2004/11/09/the_incredibles_2004_review.shtml|archivedate=August 27, 2012}}</ref> Carla Meyer, writing for the ''San Francisco Chronicle'', wrote that Bird's performance as Edna \"shows his versatility\".<ref name=\":43\" /> In 2005, Bird won an [[Annie Award]] for [[Annie Award for Voice Acting in a Feature Production|Voice Acting in a Feature Production]] at the 32nd Annie Awards for his performance as Edna,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2005/digital/awards/incredibles-tops-annies-1117917174/|title=\u2018Incredibles\u2019 tops Annies|last=Walton|first=Alice M.|date=January 30, 2005|website=Variety|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218150525/http://variety.com/2005/digital/awards/incredibles-tops-annies-1117917174/|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> in addition to being rewarded for writing and directing the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2005/01/31/incredibles-sweeps-annie-awards.html|title='The Incredibles' Sweeps Annie Awards|date=January 31, 2005|website=Fox News|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218210206/http://www.foxnews.com/story/2005/01/31/incredibles-sweeps-annie-awards.html|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Bird was rewarded over actor [[Samuel L. Jackson]], who had been nominated in the same category for his role as [[Frozone]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/49127/incredibles-super-at-toon-awards|title=\"Incredibles\" Super at 'Toon Awards|last=Grossberg|first=Josh|date=January 31, 2005|website=E!|access-date=February 17, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218090533/http://www.eonline.com/news/49127/incredibles-super-at-toon-awards|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Wisel appreciated Edna's cameo in the sequel, describing it as \"perfect in its restraint.\"<ref name=\":47\" />\n\n[[Vulture.com]] ranked Bird's role as Edna the fourth greatest performance in an animated film, calling it \"a scene- and movie-stealing performance\".<ref name=\":37\" /> Similarly, ''Entertainment Weekly'' placed Edna fourth on their ranking of \"The 10 greatest Pixar voice performances\", with author Marc Snetiker calling it \"an all-too-short but memorably delicious appearance\" in which Bird \"left an indelible mark on his own universe\".<ref name=\":41\">{{Cite web|url=http://ew.com/movies/pixar-greatest-voice-performances/#4-brad-bird-as-edna-mode|title=The 10 greatest Pixar voice performances|last=Snetiker|first=Marc|date=November 24, 2017|website=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=May 29, 2018}}</ref> Snetiker called the character \"overwhelmingly funny thanks to Bird\u2019s unrestrained efforts on even the simplest lines.\"<ref name=\":41\" /> [[IndieWire]] ranked Bird's performance as Edna the 14th \"30 Best Voice Performances In Pixar Movies\".<ref name=\":22\" /> Kiko Martinez of the ''[[San Antonio Current]]'' found Bird's performance to be worthy of an Academy Award, ranking him among \"15 Actors Who Should\u2019ve Won an Oscar for Their Voice Work\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacurrent.com/ArtSlut/archives/2016/06/13/15-actors-who-shouldve-won-an-oscar-for-their-voice-work?showFullText=true|title=15 Actors Who Should\u2019ve Won an Oscar for Their Voice Work|last=Martinez|first=Kiko|date=June 13, 2016|website=San Antonio Current|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218091234/https://www.sacurrent.com/ArtSlut/archives/2016/06/13/15-actors-who-shouldve-won-an-oscar-for-their-voice-work?showFullText=true|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Bird revealed that fans tend to be more impressed by the fact that he provides Edna's voice than his success as a director and writer,<ref name=\":49\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/programs/triplej-breakfast/brad-bird-incredibles-two/9859680|title=Incredibles director Brad Bird on the much-anticipated sequel|last=|first=|date=June 12, 2018|website=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|access-date=August 6, 2018}}</ref> explaining, \"If I say a line in Edna\u2019s voice, that\u2019s far more delightful than the fact that I spent four years wrestling something into being.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/director-brad-bird-talks-about-mission-impossible-ghos-1798230889|title=Director Brad Bird talks about Mission: Impossible\u2014Ghost Protocol and live-action versus animation|last=Robinson|first=Tasha|date=April 18, 2012|website=The A. V. Club|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217202639/https://film.avclub.com/director-brad-bird-talks-about-mission-impossible-ghos-1798230889|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Impact and legacy==\nEdna's popularity among audiences established her as the film's [[breakout character]].<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/the-incredibles/news/a849700/the-incredibles-2-new-poster-edna-mode-new-york-fashion-week/|title=New The Incredibles 2 poster brings Edna Mode to New York Fashion Week|last=James|first=Sarah|date=February 11, 2018|website=[[Digital Spy]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218213205/http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/the-incredibles/news/a849700/the-incredibles-2-new-poster-edna-mode-new-york-fashion-week/|archivedate=February 18, 2018|access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/99434/edna-mode-back-first-trailer-incredibles-2-watch/|title=Edna Mode is back in the brand new trailer for The Incredibles 2 \u2013 watch here!|last=Damshenas|first=Sam|date=February 15, 2018|website=[[Gay Times]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303053219/http://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/99434/edna-mode-back-first-trailer-incredibles-2-watch/|archivedate=March 3, 2018|access-date=February 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wsbuzz.com/tv-movies/new-incredibles-2-poster-features-edna-mode-new-york-fashion-week/|title=New The Incredibles 2 Poster Features Edna Mode At New York Fashion Week|last=|first=|date=February 11, 2018|website=WSBuzz.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303052031/http://wsbuzz.com/tv-movies/new-incredibles-2-poster-features-edna-mode-new-york-fashion-week/|archivedate=March 3, 2018|access-date=February 24, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/incredibles-2-edna-mode-video-d23/|title=Watch The Incredibles\u2019 D23 Edna Mode Retrospective Video|last=Welch|first=Alex|date=July 14, 2017|website=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920070529/http://screenrant.com/incredibles-2-edna-mode-video-d23/|archive-date=September 20, 2017|access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> Screen Rant's Alex Welch attributes this designation to both her [[Comic timing|comedic rapport]] with the titular family and passion for superhero costumes.<ref name=\":32\" /> Gregory E. Miller of the ''[[New York Post]]'' cited Edna's impact since ''The Incredibles'' as significant despite her relatively brief appearance,<ref name=\":44\" /> while [[HelloGiggles]] writer Sydney Bucksbaum crowned her the film's \"real hero\".<ref name=\":48\">{{Cite web|url=https://hellogiggles.com/news/edna-mode-incredibes-poster/|title=The latest \"Incredibles 2\" poster features the real star of the movie \u2014 Edna Mode|last=Bucksbaum|first=Sydney|date=February 12, 2018|website=[[HelloGiggles]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=June 20, 2018}}</ref> ''Vogue Italia'' contributor Valentina Fabbri wrote that Edna ended the trope of \"superheroes [dressed] in homemade outfits\".<ref name=\":8\" /> According to Fabbri, Edna is one of Pixar's most beloved characters,<ref name=\":8\" /> while [[Hollywood.com]]'s Julia Emmanuele dubbed her \"one of the most memorable Pixar characters of all time\" who has ultimately \"become the film\u2019s enduring legacy\", despite her supporting role.<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hollywood.com/movies/superheroes-hq-why-the-incredibles-is-the-best-superhero-movie-of-all-time-60227157/|title=Why \u2018The Incredibles\u2019 Is the Best Superhero Movie of All Time|last=Emmanuele|first=Julia|date=April 4, 2014|website=[[Hollywood.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> [[Uproxx]] contributor Donna Dickens wrote that the character \"went down in [[Pop culture icon|pop culture history]]\" from the moment she uttered \"No capes!\u201d<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/hitfix/incredibles-edna-mode-documentary/|title=Titans Of Fashion Pay Tribute To Edna Mode Of \u2018The Incredibles\u2019|last=Dickens|first=Donna|date=July 14, 2017|website=[[Uproxx]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218024159/http://uproxx.com/hitfix/incredibles-edna-mode-documentary/|archivedate=February 18, 2018|access-date=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMedia publications consistently rank Edna among Pixar's greatest characters.<ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":17\" /><ref name=\":39\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://20some.com/a-countdown-of-the-5-best-pixar-characters-of-all-time/|title=Can We All Agree That These Are the 5 Best Pixar Characters of All Time?|last=Sambeck|first=Becca Van|date=July 14, 2015|website=20Some|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219090411/http://20some.com/a-countdown-of-the-5-best-pixar-characters-of-all-time/|archivedate=February 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/galleries/the-all-time-best-pixar-characters/27/|title=The 27 All-Time Best Pixar Characters|website=TV Guide|access-date=May 4, 2018}}</ref> In their article \"Top 10 Pixar Movie Characters\", ''Tech Times'' ranked Edna seventh.<ref name=\":23\" /> [[IGN]] ranked Edna eighth in their countdown of the \"Top 10 Pixar Characters\", calling her \"a pint-sized fashionista\" with \"a flair that only a superhero could truly appreciate.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/05/21/top-10-pixar-characters |title=Top 10 Pixar Characters |date=May 21, 2009 |website=IGN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326164120/http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/05/21/top-10-pixar-characters |archive-date=March 26, 2018 |url-status=live |access-date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' placed her ninth on the website's list of the \"25 Best Pixar Movie Characters\", ranking her ahead of Mr. Incredible (24th), Violet Parr (20th) and Elastigirl (14th).<ref name=\":15\" /> Contributor Scott Tobias wrote that the character \"stops the action cold just to have a sequence about appropriate action-wear for the specially abled, culminating in a brilliant screed on the impracticality of capes.\"<ref name=\":15\" /> Including Edna among the studio's 20 best characters, Victoria Robertson of Screen Rant cited her as \"proof of how important even the most minor characters in a film can be.\"<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/best-pixar-characters/|title=20 Best Characters From Pixar Movies|last=Robertson|first=Victoria|date=November 20, 2013|website=Screen Rant|access-date=February 20, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220212249/https://screenrant.com/best-pixar-characters/|archivedate=February 20, 2018}}</ref> ''GamesRadar+'' included Edna among Pixar's \"50 Greatest Pixar Characters Of All Time\", with author George Wales crowning her \"One of Pixar's finest comic creations\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/50-greatest-pixar-characters-of-all-time/4/#article-body|title=50 Greatest Pixar Characters Of All Time|last=Wales|first=George|date=August 17, 2012|website=GamesRadar+|access-date=February 23, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223232224/https://www.gamesradar.com/50-greatest-pixar-characters-of-all-time/4/#article-body|archivedate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> Additionally, the same publication ranked Edna among Pixar's 12 greatest supporting characters.<ref name=\":16\" /> [[D23 (Disney)|D23.com]] recognized Edna as one of Pixar's \"23 Favorite ... Supporting Characters\", deeming her \"An icon in her own right\".<ref name=\":20\" /> /Film ranked Edna Pixar's sixth best female character, crowning her \"the wisest character in the entire Incredibles universe\" due to her anti-cape stance, which author Angie Han has described as the film's \"most valuable piece of advice\".<ref name=\":25\" /> [[The Odyssey Online]] published an article discussing \"Why Edna Mode Is The Disney Heroine We Never Knew We Needed\", in which author Erin Farmer dubbed her \"the real heroine of the Disney Franchise\" while comparing her motivational speeches to those of [[Mahatma Gandhi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theodysseyonline.com/why-edna-mode-is-the-disney-heroine-we-never-knew-we-needed|title=Why Edna Mode Is The Disney Heroine We Never Knew We Needed|last=Farmer|first=Erin|date=February 13, 2017|website=The Odyssey Online|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223110917/https://www.theodysseyonline.com/why-edna-mode-is-the-disney-heroine-we-never-knew-we-needed|archivedate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> ''GamesRadar+'' ranked Edna's introductory scene the 12th best moment in a Pixar film, deeming her \"the perfect embodiment of the film's tongue-in-cheek approach to realism\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/50-greatest-pixar-moments/4/#article-body|title=50 greatest Pixar moments|last=Kinnear|first=Simon|date=November 19, 2015|website=GamesRadar+|access-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223050756/https://www.gamesradar.com/50-greatest-pixar-moments/4/#article-body|archivedate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> ''Entertainment Weekly'' ranked Edna's anti-capes speech the 12th best Pixar moment.<ref name=\":21\" /> In 2015, [[E!]] ranked Edna 10th on their list of \"11 Forgotten Disney Characters Who Should Totally Be Your Favorites\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/ca/news/635000/11-forgotten-disney-characters-who-should-totally-be-your-favorites|title=11 Forgotten Disney Characters Who Should Totally Be Your Favorites|last=Hays|first=Julia|date=March 12, 2015|website=E!|access-date=February 24, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303050909/http://www.eonline.com/ca/news/635000/11-forgotten-disney-characters-who-should-totally-be-your-favorites|archivedate=March 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' ranked the character the hundredth greatest film character of all-time.<ref name=\":33\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/100-greatest-movie-characters/|title=The 100 Greatest Movie Characters|last=|first=|date=June 29, 2005|website=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151213002250/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/100-greatest-movie-characters/|archive-date=December 13, 2015|access-date=March 14, 2015}}</ref> In 2013, Screen Rant crowned Edna \"The world\u2019s greatest fashion designer\".<ref name=\":32\" /> ''Fashion'' ranked Edna among the magazine's \"10 coolest fashion industry pros\".<ref name=\":34\" /> In their \"critical assessment of 7 fictional fashion designers\", Mary Sollosi of ''Entertainment Weekly'' wrote that she is \"consistently impressed by Ms. Mode\u2019s truly groundbreaking textile work\" despite feeling that she tends to limit herself to familiar silhouettes, joking, \"we are perplexed by her stubborn refusal to incorporate new design features \u2014 most notably capes.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/09/12/fictional-fashion-designers/|title=A critical assessment of 7 fictional fashion designers|last=Sollosi|first=Mary|date=September 12, 2017|website=Entertainment Weekly|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225235836/http://ew.com/movies/2017/09/12/fictional-fashion-designers/|archive-date=December 25, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> In June 2018, Carlye Wisel of [[Racked.com|Racked]] crowned Edna \"Film\u2019s greatest fashion character\", deeming her \"the best fictional fashion personality ever to exist, animated or not\". She prefers her over ''[[The Devil Wears Prada (film)|The Devil Wears Prada]]''<nowiki/>'s Miranda Priestly ([[Meryl Streep]]), insisting that Edna \"feels more grounded and true\" Miranda, a fictional magazine editor who is frequently touted the \"best-ever fashion character\".<ref name=\":47\" /> Describing her as \"effortless and memorable,\" Wisel concluded, \"at a time when a label like Gucci is exploding its brand with misspellings and magpie tendencies to draw attention, she remains classic. Edna is never anything but fully herself \u2014 all hair, accent, and attitude.\"<ref name=\":47\" />\n\nEdna's [[catchphrase]] against using capes in superhero costumes has become one of the most popular phrases among superhero fans.<ref name=\":42\" /> Edna has become so popular that fans have begun to demand a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] film revolving around the character.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/film-tv/g12151384/best-superhero-movies-list/?slide=5|title=The 30 Best Superhero Movies of All Time|last=Janes|first=DeAnna|date=March 30, 2018|website=Harper's Bazaar|access-date=May 31, 2018|quote=It\u2019s such a good time, fans are demanding a spin-off starring scene-stealing designer Edna Mode}}</ref> Screen Rant ranked Edna the third Pixar heroine who deserves her own film, with author Wednesday Lee Friday writing, \"There are so many things Pixar could do with Edna, she might be worthy of a trilogy.\"<ref name=\":40\" /> At the [[77th Academy Awards]] in 2005, Edna presented the [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design]] alongside actor [[Pierce Brosnan]].<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":16\" /> In 2013, the D23 Expo hosted its first official cosplay competition, naming it \"Heroes and Villains \u00e0 la Mode\" in honor of Edna; contestants competed in five categories, with the winners being awarded miniature statuettes of the character.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mouseplanet.com/10460/D23_Expo__Heroes_and_Villains_a_la_Mode_Costume_Contest|title=D23 Expo - Heroes and Villains a la Mode Costume Contest|last=Wien|first=Stephanie|date=August 26, 2013|website=MousePlanet|access-date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> To promote the film's sequel in which Edna appeared,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2017/11/18/incredibles-2-watch-first-trailer/|title=The Incredibles 2: Oh Baby! - watch Disney-Pixar's first trailer|date=November 18, 2017|website=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=February 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218210309/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2017/11/18/incredibles-2-watch-first-trailer/|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Disney released a [[mockumentary]]-style teaser trailer that features various celebrities involved in the fashion industry paying tribute to Edna and describing ways in which the character has influenced them over the years ever since she decided to venture into [[haute couture]].<ref name=\":10\" /> Disney revealed the trailer at the [[D23 Expo]] in 2017.<ref name=\":10\" /> Fashion models [[Heidi Klum]], [[Kendall Jenner]] and [[Rachel Zoe]] are among the celebrities who speak about Edna's influence on the fashion industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.joe.ie/movies-tv/the-incredibles-2-info-595306|title=Loads of new details have been revealed about The Incredibles 2|last=Cashin|first=Rory|date=2017|website=JOE.ie|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218102508/https://www.joe.ie/movies-tv/the-incredibles-2-info-595306|archivedate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Impressed by their commitment to pretending Edna is real, Halle Kiefer of Vulture.com joked that the tribute features some of the participants' \"most impressive onscreen roles to date\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2017/07/the-fashion-world-pays-tribute-to-the-incredibles-edna-mode.html|title=Kendall Jenner, Andr\u00e9 Leon Talley Play Pretty Convincing Tribute to The Incredibles\u2019 Fashion Designer Edna Mode|last=Kiefer|first=Halle|date=July 14, 2017|website=Vulture.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321063032/http://www.vulture.com/2017/07/the-fashion-world-pays-tribute-to-the-incredibles-edna-mode.html|archive-date=March 21, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=March 20, 2018}}</ref> Rachel Kolb of Uproxx wrote that having Edna design new costumes for the family in ''Incredibles 2'' would be one way to ensure that the sequel is better than the original.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/10-ways-pixar-can-make-the-incredibles-2-better-than-the-original/|title=How Can Pixar Make \u2018The Incredibles 2\u2019 Even Better Than The Original? Here Are A Few Ideas.|last=Kolb|first=Rachel|date=November 5, 2014|website=Uproxx|access-date=February 17, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217192153/http://uproxx.com/movies/10-ways-pixar-can-make-the-incredibles-2-better-than-the-original/|archivedate=February 17, 2018}}</ref> Beginning in 2018, Edna has been used heavily in ''Incredibles 2''<nowiki/>'s first [[advertising campaign]].<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newnownext.com/edna-mode-incredibles-2/02/2018/|title=Edna Mode Star Of First Ad Campaign For \"Incredibles 2\"|last=Avery|first=Dan|date=February 12, 2018|website=[[NewNowNext]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219031130/http://www.newnownext.com/edna-mode-incredibles-2/02/2018/|archivedate=February 19, 2018|access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In February 2018, the character's likeness was used heavily on several bus and subway posters within Manhattan, New York surrounding [[New York Fashion Week]].<ref name=\":13\" /> Disney-Pixar's announced on their Twitter account: \"If you thought she\u2019d miss #NYFW, you thought wrong, dahling\".<ref name=\":13\" /> The poster features a black and white closeup image of the character with only her lips colored red,<ref name=\":48\" /> accompanied by the caption \"It's been too long, dahlings.\"<ref name=\":14\" /> Bucksbaum called the poster \"stunning\".<ref name=\":48\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The Incredibles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mode, Edna}}\n[[Category:Fictional inventors]]\n[[Category:The Incredibles characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional people in fashion]]\n[[Category:Fictional women scientists]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 2004]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with dwarfism]]\n[[Category:Fictional American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Fictional American people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Fictional smokers]]\n[[Category:Animated human characters]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:8c9f:6700:7c6d:cefd:c1dd:e872", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAppearances)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edna_Mode"}
{"title_page": "Rhea (mythology)", "text_new": "{{short description|Ancient Greek goddess and Titan}}\n{{Redirect|Rheia|the 2016 album by Oathbreaker|Rheia (album)}}\n\n{{Infobox deity\n| type         = Greek\n| name         = Rhea\n| deity_of     =  \n| member_of    = the [[Titan (mythology)|Titans]]\n| image        = Rh\u00e9a pr\u00e9sentant une pierre emmaillot\u00e9e \u00e0 Cronos dessin du bas-relief d'un autel romain.jpg\n| alt          =\n| caption      = Rhea presenting Cronus the stone wrapped in cloth\n| other_names  = \n| hiro         = \n| Old_Norse    = \n| Devanagari   = \n| Sanskrit_transliteration = \n| Tamil_script = \n| Tamil_transliteration = \n| Kannada_script = \n| Kannada_transliteration = \n| script_name  = \n| script       = \n| affiliation  = \n| cult_center  =\n| abode        =\n| planet       =\n| mantra       = \n| weapon       =\n| battles      = \n| artifacts    =\n| animals      = Lion\n| symbol       = Chariot, tambourine, crown, cornucopia\n| height       = \n| age          = \n| tree         = Silver fir\n| day          = \n| color        =\n| number       = \n| consort      = [[Cronus]], [[Zeus]] ([[Orphic]])\n| parents      = [[Uranus (mythology)|Uranus]] and [[Gaia (mythology)|Gaia]]\n| siblings     =  {{Collapsible list\n | title =[[Titan (mythology)|Titans]]\n | bullets = on\n | [[Crius]]\n | [[Coeus]]\n | [[Cronus]]\n | [[Hyperion (mythology)|Hyperion]]\n | [[Iapetus (mythology)|Iapetus]]\n | [[Mnemosyne]]\n | [[Oceanus]]\n | [[Phoebe (mythology)|Phoebe]]\n | [[Tethys (mythology)|Tethys]]\n | [[Theia]]\n | [[Themis]]\n}}\n{{Collapsible list\n | title=[[Hekatonkheires]]\n | bullets = on\n | Briareos\n | Cottus\n | Gyges\n}}\n{{Collapsible list\n | title=[[Cyclopes]]\n | bullets = on\n | [[Arges (Cyclops)|Arges]]\n | Brontes\n | Steropes\n}}\n{{Collapsible list\n| title= Other siblings\n| bullets = on\n| [[Gigantes]]\n| [[Erinyes]] (the Furies)\n| [[Meliae]]\n}}\n{{Collapsible list\n| title=[[Half-siblings]]\n| bullets = on\n| [[Aphrodite]]\n| [[Typhon]]\n| [[Python (mythology)|Python]]\n| [[Uranus (mythology)|Uranus]]\n}}\n| offspring    = [[Poseidon]], [[Hades]], [[Demeter]], [[Hestia]], [[Hera]], [[Zeus]], [[Persephone]] ([[Orphic]])\n| predecessor  =\n| successor    =\n| army         =\n| mount        = \n| texts        = \n| Greek_equivalent     = \n| Roman_equivalent     = [[Ops]]\n| Etruscan_equivalent  = \n| Christian_equivalent = \n| Slavic_equivalent    = \n| Hinduism_equivalent  = \n| Canaanite_equivalent =\n| region       = \n| ethnic_group = \n| festivals    = \n}}\n\n'''Rhea''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|i\u02d0|\u0259}}; [[Ancient Greek]]: \u1fec\u03ad\u03b1 {{IPA-el|r\u0325\u00e9.a\u02d0|}}) (or '''Rheia''') is a character in [[Greek mythology]], the [[Titan (mythology)|Titaness]] daughter of the earth goddess [[Gaia (mythology)|Gaia]] and the sky god [[Uranus (mythology)|Uranus]], Gaia's son. She is also the older sister and wife of [[Cronus]]. In early traditions, she is known as \"the mother of gods\" and therefore is strongly associated with Gaia and [[Cybele]], who have similar functions. The classical Greeks saw her as the mother of the [[Twelve Olympians|Olympian gods and goddesses]], but not as an Olympian goddess in her own right. The Romans identified her with [[Magna Mater]] (their form of Cybele), and the Goddess [[Ops]].\n\n==Etymology==\n\n[[Image:Rhea MKL1888.png|thumb|right|250|Rhea or [[Cybele]], drawing of a marble relief (1888)]]\n\nSome ancient etymologists derived ''{{lang|grc-Latn|Rhea}}'' (''{{lang|grc|\u1fec\u03ad\u03b1}}'') (by [[metathesis (linguistics)|metathesis]]) from ''{{lang|grc|\u1f14\u03c1\u03b1}}'', \"ground\";<ref>Hopkinson, p. 176, noting: \"For a full collection of evidence see O. Gruppe, ''Griechische Mythologie und Religionsgeschichte'' (Munich 1906) 1524 n. 2.\".</ref> the same suggest also modern scholars<ref>\u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u0399\u03c9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 (2012) Dictionary of the ancient Greek language. \u0395\u03ba\u03b4\u03cc\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u0394\u03b5\u03b4\u03b5\u03bc\u03ac\u03b4\u03b7. {{ISBN|9789609876292}} p. 874. ''\u00ab'''\u1ffe\u03a1\u03ad\u1fb1 = \u0393\u03b7, \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf \u1f14\u03c1\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03ac\u03b8\u03b5\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03c6\u03b8\u03cc\u03b3\u03b3\u03c9\u03bd.'''\u00bb''</ref>, although a tradition embodied in [[Plato]]<ref>Plato. ''Cratylus'' 402b\u2013c.</ref> and in [[Chrysippus]]<ref>Chrysippus, ''Stoic 2.318''</ref> connected the word with {{lang|grc|\u1fe5\u03ad\u03c9}} (''{{lang|grc|rheo}}''), \"flow\", \"discharge\",<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dr%28e%2Fw \u1fe5\u03ad\u03c9], Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, ''A Greek\u2013English Lexicon'', on Perseus Digital Library</ref> which is what ''[[A Greek\u2013English Lexicon|LSJ]]'' supports.<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3D*%28re%2Fa_ \u1fec\u03ad\u03b1], Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, ''A Greek\u2013English Lexicon'', on Perseus Digital Library</ref> Alternatively, the name ''Rhea'' may be connected with words for the [[pomegranate]], {{lang|grc|\u1fe5\u03cc\u03b1}}, later {{lang|grc|\u1fe5\u03bf\u03b9\u03ac}}.\n\nThe name ''Rhea'' may ultimately derive from a [[Pelasgians|pre-Greek]] or [[Minoan language|Minoan]] source.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/topic/Rhea-Greek-goddess |title=Rhea \u2013 Greek goddess |work=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=-OwRuSQQYi0C&pg=PA536&lpg=PA536&dq=rhea%20pre-greek#v=onepage&q=rhea%20pre-greek&f=false |title=The Minoan-Mycenaean Religion and Its Survival in Greek Religion |first=Martin Persson |last=Nilsson |date=1 January 1950 |publisher=Biblo & Tannen Publishers |via=Google Books |isbn=9780819602732 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/BF01142761 |volume=12 |issue=4 |title=Rhea was a broad: Pre-Hellenic Greek myths for post-Hellenic children |journal=Children's Literature in Education |pages=171\u2013176 |year = 1981|last1 = Sidwell|first1 = R. T.}}</ref> [[Robert Graves|Graves]] suggested that Rhea's name is probably a variant of Era, 'earth'.<ref>[[Robert Graves]]. ''[[The Greek Myths]], section 7''</ref>\nRhea is also super stupid and should stop her futile struggles to prove herself to be superior to pil when she very clearly is not.\n\n==Family==\n\nAccording to [[Hesiod]], [[Cronus]] sired six children by Rhea: [[Hestia]], [[Demeter]], [[Hera]], [[Hades]], [[Poseidon]], and [[Zeus]] in that order.<ref>[[Hesiod]]. ''[[Theogony]],'' ''[http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0020.tlg001.perseus-eng1:453-491 453 ff.]''</ref> The philosopher [[Plato]] recounts that Rhea, Cronus and [[Phorcys]] were the eldest children of [[Oceanus]] and [[Tethys (mythology)|Tethys]].<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Plat.+Tim.+40e&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0180 Plato. ''Timaeus 40e.''] Translated by W.R.M. Lamb. Cambridge, Massachusetts, Harvard University Press; London, William Heinemann Ltd. 1925.</ref> In the Orphic Tradition, Rhea produced a daughter, [[Persephone]], by mating with her own  son, Zeus.\n\n== Mythology ==\nGaia and [[Uranus (mythology)|Uranus]] told Cronus that just as he had overthrown his own father, he was destined to be overcome by his own child; so as each of his children was born, Cronus swallowed them. Rhea, Uranus and Gaia devised a plan to save the last of them, Zeus. Rhea gave birth to Zeus in a cavern on the island of [[Crete]], and gave Cronus a stone wrapped in [[swaddling]] clothes, which he promptly swallowed; Rhea hid her infant son Zeus in a cave on [[Mount Ida]]. Her attendants, the warrior-like [[Korybantes|Kouretes]] and [[Dactyl (mythology)|Dactyls]], acted as a bodyguard for the infant Zeus, helping to conceal his whereabouts from his father.\n\nIn some accounts, by the will of Rhea a golden dog guarded a goat which offered her udder and gave nourishment to the infant Zeus. Later on, Zeus changed the goat into an immortal among the stars while the golden dog that guarded the sacred spot in Crete was stolen by [[Pandareus]].''<ref name=\":0\" />''\n\n==Cult==\n\nRhea had \"no strong local cult or identifiable activity under her control\".<ref name=\"autogenerated171\">Roller, Lynn E., ''In Search of God the Mother: The Cult of Anatolian Cybele,'' University of California Press, 1999. p. 171.</ref> She was originally worshiped on the island of [[Crete]], identified in mythology as the site of Zeus' infancy and upbringing. Her cults employed rhythmic, raucous chants and dances, accompanied by the [[Tympanum (hand drum)|tympanon]] (a wide, handheld drum), to provoke a religious ecstasy. Her priests impersonated her mythical attendants, the Curetes and Dactyls, with a clashing of bronze shields and cymbals.<ref name=\"autogenerated171\" />\n\nThe tympanon's use in Rhea's rites may have been the source for its use in [[Cybele]]'s \u2013 in historical times, the resemblances between the two goddesses were so marked that some Greeks regarded Cybele as their own Rhea, who had deserted her original home on Mount Ida in Crete and fled to Mount Ida in the wilds of Phrygia to escape Cronus.<ref>Roller, Lynn E., ''In Search of God the Mother: The Cult of Anatolian Cybele,'' University of California Press, 1999. p. 171. See also [[Strabo]], ''Geographica'' ([http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/10C*.html ''Book X'', Ch. 3])</ref>. A reverse view was expressed by [[Virgil]],<ref>Virgil's ''[[Aeneid]]'' (''Book III'', ln. 69-120)</ref> that cultural contacts with the mainland brought Cybele to Crete, where she was transformed into Rhea or identified with an existing local goddess and her rites.\n\nRhea was often referred to as ''Meter Theon'' (\u201cMother of the Gods\u201d) and there were several temples around Ancient Greece dedicated to her under that name. Pausanias mentioned temples dedicated to Rhea under the name Meter Theon in Anagyros in Attika,<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]]. ''Description of Greece'' ([http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+1.31.1&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0160:book=1:chapter=31&highlight=Mother Book 1, Ch. 31, sect. 1])</ref> [[Megalopolis]] in Arkadia,<ref>Pausanias. ''Description of Greece'' ([http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+8.30.5&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0160:book=8:chapter=30&highlight=Mother Book 8, Ch. 30, sect. 5])</ref> on the Acropolis of Ancient Corinth,<ref>Pausanias. ''Description of Greece'' ([http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+2.4.7&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0160:book=2:chapter=4&highlight=Mother Book 2, Ch. 4, sect. 7]</ref> and in the district of Keramaikos in Athens, where the statue was made by Pheidias.<ref>Pausanias. ''Description of Greece'' ([http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+1.3.5&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0160:book=1:chapter=3&highlight=Mother Book 1, Ch. 3, sect. 5])</ref> In Sparta there was further more a sanctuary to ''Meter Megale'' (\u201c[the] Great Mother\u201d).<ref>Pausanias. ''Description of Greece'' ([http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+3.12.9&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0160:book=3:chapter=12&highlight=Great Book 3, Ch. 12, sect. 9])</ref> Olympia had both an altar<ref>Pausanias. ''Description of Greece'' ([http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+5.14.9&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0160:book=5:chapter=14&highlight=Mother Book 5, Ch. 14, sect. 9])</ref> as well as a temple to the Meter Theon: \n: \"A temple of no great size [at Olympia] in the Doric style they have called down to the present day Metroion (Temple of the Mother), keeping its ancient name. No image lies in it of the Meter Theon (Mother of the Gods), but there stand in it statues of Roman emperors.\"<ref>Pausanias. ''Description of Greece'' ([http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+5.20.9&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0160:book=5:chapter=20&highlight=Mother Book 5, Ch. 20, sect. 9])</ref>\n\nHer temple in [[Akriai]], Lakedaimon was said to be her oldest sanctuary in Peloponessos: \n: \"Well worth seeing here [at Akriai, Lakedaimon] are a temple and marble image of the Meter Theon (Mother of the Gods). The people of Akriai say that this is the oldest sanctuary of this goddess in the Peloponessos.\"<ref>Pausanias. ''Description of Greece'' ([http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+3.22.4&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0160:book=3:chapter=22&highlight=Mother Book 3, Ch. 22, sect. 4])</ref>\n\nStatues of her were also standing in the sanctuaries of other gods and in other places, such as a statue of Parian marble by Damophon in Messene.<ref>Pausanias. ''Description of Greece'', ([http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+4.31.6&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0160:book=4:chapter=31&highlight=Mother Book 4, Ch. 31, sect. 6])</ref> The scene in which Rhea gave Chronos a stone in the place of Zeus after his birth was assigned to have taken place on Petrakhos Mountain in Arcadia <ref>Pausanias. ''Description of Greece'', ([http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+9.41.6&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.01600:book=4:chapter=31&highlight=Rhea Book 9, Ch. 41, sect. 6])</ref> as well as on Mount Thaumasios in Arcadia, both of which were holy places: \n:''\"Mount Thaumasios (Wonderful) lies beyond the river Maloitas [in Arkadia], and the Methydrians hold that when Rhea was pregnant with Zeus, she came to this mountain and enlisted as her allies, in case Kronos should attack her, Hopladamos and his few Gigantes. They allow that she gave birth to her son on some part of Mount Lykaios, but they claim that here Kronos was deceived, and here took place the substitution of a stone for the child that is spoken of in the Greek legend. On the summit of the mountain is Rhea's Cave, into which no human beings may enter save only the women who are sacred to the goddess.\"''<ref>Pausanias. ''Description of Greece'' ([http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+8.36.2&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0160:book=8:chapter=36&highlight=Rhea Book 8, Ch. 36, sect. 2])</ref>\n\nThe center of the worship of Rhea was however on Crete, where Mount Ida was said to be the place of the birth of Zeus. Reportedly, there was a \"House of Rhea\" in Knossos: \n:''\"The Titanes had their dwelling in the land about Knosos [in Krete], at the place where even to this day men point out foundations of a house of Rhea and a cypress grove which has been consecrated to her from ancient times.\"''<ref>Diodorus Siculus, ''[[Bibliotheca Historica]]'' ([http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/5D*.html#64 ''Book V'', Ch. 65])</ref>\n\nUpon Mount Ida, there was a cave sacred to Rhea:\n:''\"In Crete there is said to be a sacred cave full of bees. In it, as storytellers say, Rhea gave birth to Zeus; it is a sacred place and no one is to go near it, whether god or mortal. At the appointed time each year a great blaze is seen to come out of the cave. Their story goes on to say that this happens whenever the blood from the birth of Zeus begins to boil up. The sacred bees that were the nurses of Zeus occupy this cave.\"''<ref name=\":0\">[[Antoninus Liberalis]]. ''[https://topostext.org/work/216#36 Metamorphoses, 36]''</ref>\n\n==Iconography==\n\n[[Image:Pergamonmuseum - Antikensammlung - Pergamonaltar 37.JPG|thumb|right|200x200px| Rhea rides on a lion, Pergamon Altar, [[Pergamon Museum]], [[Berlin]]]]\n\nRhea only appears in Greek art from the fourth century BC, when her iconography draws on that of [[Cybele]]; the two therefore, often are indistinguishable;<ref>Roller, Lynn E., ''In Search of God the Mother: The Cult of Anatolian Cybele,'' University of California Press, 1999. p. 171. {{ISBN|9780520210240}}</ref> both can be shown on a throne flanked by [[lion]]s, riding a lion, or on a [[chariot]] drawn by two lions. In [[Religion in ancient Rome|Roman religion]], her counterpart Cybele was [[Cybele|Magna Mater deorum Idaea]], who was brought to Rome and was identified in [[Roman mythology]] as an ancestral Trojan deity. On a functional level, Rhea was thought equivalent to Roman [[Ops]] or ''Opis''.\n\n==Depiction in ancient literature==\nIn [[Homer]], Rhea is the mother of the gods, although not a universal mother like [[Cybele]], the [[Phrygians|Phrygia]]n [[Mother Goddess|Great Mother]], with whom she was later identified.\n\nIn the ''[[Argonautica]]'' by [[Apollonius of Rhodes]], the fusion of Rhea and Phrygian Cybele is completed. \"Upon the Mother depend the winds, the ocean, the whole earth beneath the snowy seat of Olympus; whenever she leaves the mountains and climbs to the great vault of heaven, Zeus himself, the son of [[Cronus]], makes way, and all the other immortal gods likewise make way for the dread goddess,\" the seer [[Mopsus]] tells Jason in ''[[Argonautica]]''; Jason climbed to the sanctuary high on [[Dindymon|Mount Dindymon]] to offer sacrifice and libations to placate the goddess, so that the Argonauts might continue on their way. For her ''[[temenos]]'' they wrought an image of the goddess, a ''[[xoanon]]'', from a vine-stump. There \"they called upon the mother of Dindymon, mistress of all, the dweller in Phrygia, and with her [[Dactyl (mythology)|Titias]] and [[Dactyl (mythology)|Kyllenos]] who alone of the many [[Dactyl (mythology)|Cretan Daktyls of Ida]] are called 'guiders of destiny' and 'those who sit beside the Idaean Mother'.\" They leapt and danced in their armour: \"For this reason the Phrygians still worship Rhea with tambourines and drums\".<ref>(Apollonius of Rhodes), Richard Hunter, tr., 1993. ''Jason and the Golden Fleece'' (Oxford: Clarendon Press), Book II, p. 29f.</ref>\n\n==Descendants==\n{{chart top| Descendants of Cronus and Rhea&nbsp;<ref>This chart is based upon [[Hesiod]]'s ''[[Theogony]]'', unless otherwise noted.</ref>|collapsed=no}}\n{{chart/start}}\n{{chart|}}\n{{chart|URA| | | | | | | | |CRO |y|RHE |URA=<small>Uranus' genitals</small>|CRO=[[Cronus]]|RHE='''RHEA'''}}\n{{chart| |!| | |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|^|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.}}\n{{chart| |!| |ZEU |V|~|~|y|~|HER | |POS | |HAD | |DEM | |HES |HES=[[Hestia]]|DEM=[[Demeter]]|ZEU=[[Zeus]]|HER=[[Hera]]|HAD=[[Hades]]|POS=[[Poseidon]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| |,|^|-|.| |!}}\n{{chart|border=0| |!| | | | |:| |!| |AAA |!|AAA= &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;a <ref>According to [[Homer]], ''[[Iliad]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:1.570 1.570\u2013579],  [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:14.338 14.338], ''[[Odyssey]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-eng1:8.312 8.312], Hephaestus was apparently the son of Hera and Zeus, see Gantz, p. 74.</ref>}}\n{{chart|border=0| |!| | | | |:| |!| | |!|BBB |BBB=&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;b <ref>According to [[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Hes.+Th.+927 927\u2013929], Hephaestus was produced by Hera alone, with no father, see Gantz, p. 74.</ref>}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| |!| | |!| |!}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:|ARE | |HEP |HEP=[[Hephaestus]]|ARE=[[Ares]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |D|~|~|~|y|~|~|~|~|MET |MET=[[Metis (mythology)|Metis]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| | |ATH |ATH=[[Athena]] <ref>According to [[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Hes.+Th.+886 886\u2013890], of Zeus' children by his seven wives, Athena was the first to be conceived, but the last to be born; Zeus impregnated Metis then swallowed her, later Zeus himself gave birth to Athena \"from his head\", see Gantz, pp. 51\u201352, 83\u201384.</ref>}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |D|~|~|~|y|~|~|~|~|LET |LET=[[Leto]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| |,|-|^|-|.}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:|APO | |ART |APO=[[Apollo]]|ART=[[Artemis]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |D|~|~|~|y|~|~|~|~|MAI |MAI=[[Maia (mythology)|Maia]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| | |HER |HER=[[Hermes]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |D|~|~|~|y|~|~|~|~|SEM |SEM=[[Semele]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |:| | |DIO |DIO=[[Dionysus]]}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | |L|~|~|~|~|y|~|~|~|DIO |DIO=[[Dione (Titaness)|Dione]]}}\n{{chart|border=0|AAA | | | | | | | |BBB|AAA=&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;a <ref>According to [[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Hes.+Th.+183 183\u2013200], Aphrodite was born from Uranus' severed genitals, see Gantz, pp. 99\u2013100.</ref>|BBB=&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;b <ref>According to [[Homer]], Aphrodite was the daughter of Zeus (''[[Iliad]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:3.374 3.374], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:20.105 20.105]; ''[[Odyssey]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-eng1:8.308 8.308], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-eng1:8.320 320]) and Dione (''[[Iliad]]'' [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-eng1:5.370 5.370\u201371]), see Gantz, pp. 99\u2013100.</ref>}}\n{{chart| |`|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|.| |!}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | |APH |APH=[[Aphrodite]]}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n==Modern namesakes==\nThe name of the bird species ''[[Rhea (bird)|Rhea]]'' is derived from the goddess name ''Rhea''.<ref>C. Michael Hogan. 2009. [http://www.globaltwitcherea: Rhea pinnata'', GlobalTwitcher.com, ed. N. Stromberg] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004094533/http://www.globaltwitcher.com/artspec_information.asp?thingid=14 |date=2011-10-04 }}</ref>\n\n[[Rhea (moon)|Rhea]], the second largest moon of the planet [[Saturn]] is named after her.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* [[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]], ''Apollodorus, The Library, with an English Translation by Sir James George Frazer, F.B.A., F.R.S. in 2 Volumes.'' Cambridge, Massachusetts, [[Harvard University Press]]; London, William Heinemann Ltd. 1921. [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0548.tlg001.perseus-eng1 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library].\n*[[Apollonius of Rhodes|Apollonius Rhodius]], ''[[Argonautica]]'' translated by Robert Cooper Seaton (1853\u20131915), R. C. Loeb Classical Library Volume 001. London, William Heinemann Ltd, 1912. [https://topostext.org/work/126 Online version at the Topos Text Project.]\n*Anonymous, ''The Homeric Hymns and Homerica'' with an English Translation by Hugh G. Evelyn-White. Homeric Hymns. Cambridge, MA.,Harvard University Press; London, William Heinemann Ltd. 1914. [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0138%3Ahymn%3D2 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library.]\n*[[Antoninus Liberalis]], ''The Metamorphoses of Antoninus Liberalis'' translated by Francis Celoria (Routledge 1992). [https://topostext.org/work/216 Online version at the Topos Text Project.]\n*[[Callimachus]]. ''Hymns'', translated by Alexander William Mair (1875\u20131928). London: William Heinemann; New York: G.P. Putnam's Sons. 1921. [https://topostext.org/work/120 Online version at the Topos Text Project.]\n*[[Clement of Alexandria]], ''Recognitions'' from [[Ante-Nicene Period|Ante-Nicene]] Library Volume 8'','' translated by Smith, Rev. Thomas. T. & T. Clark, Edinburgh. 1867. [http://www.theoi.com/Text/ClementRecognitions.html Online version at theio.com]\n*[[Diodorus Siculus]], ''Diodorus Siculus: The Library of History''. Translated by [[Charles Henry Oldfather]]. Twelve volumes. [[Loeb Classical Library]]. Cambridge, Massachusetts: Harvard University Press; London: William Heinemann, Ltd. 1989.[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/home.html Online version at the 